<FIRST>r a AM-People-MissWestVirginia     12-13 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-Miss West Virginia,0304</SECOND>
<HEAD>Magistrate Drops Weapons Charge Against Miss West Virginia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAY FORMANEK Jr.</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> MORGANTOWN </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> W. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION> _ A magistrate on Wednesday dropped a weapons charge against <LOCATION> Miss </LOCATION> <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON> <PERSON> Bittinger </PERSON>, citing a lack of evidence <PERSON> Marion </PERSON> <PERSON> County </PERSON> <PERSON> Magistrate </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> said the 21-year-old beauty queen had a right to defend herself with a small-caliber handgun during her late night tussle with <PERSON> Tammy </PERSON> <PERSON> Boyce </PERSON>, 23. `` Now had she taken the gun out and held it on this woman or initiated the problem, that's different,'' <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> said. `` But if someone has you by the hair, and you just momentarily bring it into view to scare them off, that's not brandishing.'' <PERSON> Boyce </PERSON> had alleged that <PERSON> Bittinger </PERSON> pulled a gun on her during a Nov. 7 scuffle on a city street after a traffic accident. <PERSON> Bittinger </PERSON>, in turn, filed a complaint accusing <PERSON> Boyce </PERSON> of reckless driving, battery and destruction of property. <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> found <PERSON> Boyce </PERSON> guilty of all three counts and sentenced her to two terms of 120 days in the <LOCATION> Marion </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jail </LOCATION>, respectively, on the battery and property charges and 90 days on the driving offense. The sentences are to run concurrently. <PERSON> Boyce </PERSON> was freed on a $ 2,000 property bond that will allow her to remain free until Dec. 27. `` I wanted togive her time to enjoy her holiday,'' <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> said. `` This whole thing was really just a cat fight.'' <PERSON> Bittinger </PERSON> said she wants to put the incident behind her. `` This was n't the first threat I've had from her and it's not the first threat I've had from other people,'' she said. `` I am afraid, but life happens you just have to deal with it.'' <PERSON> Bittinger </PERSON>, whose reign ends in June, said she plans to continue carrying a handgun for protection.
</TEXT>
