<FIRST>r a AM-CharterRevision     12-13 0274</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Charter Revision,0281</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Justice Department Approves Revised Charter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> says it has no objection to the changes to the City Charter that were approved by voters last month. News of the approval came in a letter to <PERSON> Frederick </PERSON> <PERSON> A.O </PERSON>. <PERSON> Schwarz </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Charter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revision </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, from Acting Assistant Attorney General <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Turner </PERSON> of the department's civil rights division `` Our work is now done,'' <PERSON> Schwarz </PERSON> said. `` The foundation has been laid for a more representative, fairer and efficient city government.'' <PERSON> Schwarz </PERSON>, a former city corporation counsel, noted that <PERSON> Turner </PERSON>'s letter `` calls particular attention to the fact that ` minority voters will likely have an increased opportunity to elect members of the enlarged and more powerful City Council.' `` Increasing minority representation in the city government was one of the <ORGANIZATION> Charter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revision </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>'s major goals,'' he said. Although <PERSON> Turner </PERSON> wrote that the department `` interposes no objection'' to the revised charter, he added that federal law allows the option of going to court in the future `` to enjoin the enforcement of these changes.'' The revised charter abolishes the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Estimate </ORGANIZATION> and transfers its fiscal and planning powers to the mayor, the <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> and other city officials. It also increases the size of the council from 35 to 51 members. The <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Estimate </ORGANIZATION> had been declared unconstitutional because it gave equal representation to each borough despite wide disparities in population. <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> Majority Leader <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Vallone </PERSON>, who has long pushed for abolition of the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Estimate </ORGANIZATION> and a more equitable balance of power between the city's executive and legislative branches, also praised the department's decision.
</TEXT>
