<FIRST>r i PM-Czech-Economy Bjt   12-13 0815</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Czech-Economy, Bjt,0846</SECOND>
<HEAD>Political Freedom Doesn't Buy Czechs and Slovaks Western Goods</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MORT ROSENBLUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Huge crowds opposing a Communist government chanted, `` Demisi,'' meaning, resign. But some shifted the chant slightly to `` Devizy.'' That means foreign exchange. To Czechoslovaks, freedom to travel is an empty privilege without currency to spend abroad. Beyond their borders their banknotes in crowns are hardly worth anything. Once a year, Czechoslovaks are allowed to line up for days to buy a maximum of $ 23 at twice the official rate. Or they can buy any amount on the black market at nearly five times the rate. That is one crushing problem <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> faces in trying to retool a centrally planned socialist bloc economy into a prosperous system open to the world. There are a lot more. `` Basically, everything that was wrong before is still wrong,'' observed a Western economic analyst who spoke on the condition of anonymity. `` And things are getting worse.'' <PERSON> Dusan </PERSON> <PERSON> Triska </PERSON>, a senior economist in <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION>, agreed, adding a litany of crises that reformers will have to address. Western banks are lined up to lend money, and investors are milling in the wings. In <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, however, any economic solution hinges on social and political priorities. `` Above all,'' <PERSON> Triska </PERSON> said, `` we have to avoid mistakes made by <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>. Before we open to the exterior, we have to open up inside. We ca n't use foreign resources until we can use our own.'' Until the war, <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> had <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s sixth strongest economy, with heavy industry and some of the world's most advanced technology. During 40 years of Communism, plants were operated with little investment and shoddy maintenance. The once-strong infrastructure now needs billions of dollars worth of capital. The system operates at a loss, with no relation between costs and prices. Milk sells for half what it costs to produce. Bread is so cheap farmers use it for fodder. Since the 1968 Soviet-led invasion, <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> leaders have tried to offer 15 million Czechoslovaks the softest life in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> in exchange for political submissiveness. There is a car for every 4.9 people. An average worker can buy one with 15 months' pay. Most Eastern Europeans wait years for delivery. Everyone has a job, and goldbricking is seldom grounds for dismissal. Workers are encouraged to spend weekends at vacation homes. Shops offer Italian kiwis and French cheeses. If veal is scarce, the lamb is excellent. Vacations are cheap for travelers who like <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION>. The system is rich ground for larceny, from petty to grand. Waiters sell caviar from the refrigerator. Doctors take tips for preferred service. Factory managers wheel and deal. Pressure was contained when lives were lived behind an Iron Curtain. Now that people want to travel and buy Western goods, the closed economy generates growing frustration. The hard part is that it must get worse before it gets better. Any new government will need a firm mandate. `` Someone will have to tell Czechoslovaks they have to work harder and earn less,'' <PERSON> Triska </PERSON> said. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> ca n't do that.'' Most likely, a Western diplomat noted, a coalition government will emerge. `` Coalitions are not famous for taking tough measures,'' he said. Economists agree that reform means massive layoffs and reduced control will send prices soaring. Subsidies have to be eliminated. And incompetent managers must be replaced. `` We will have to abolish many inefficient factories and gradually open to the international market,'' said economist <PERSON> Miroslav </PERSON> <PERSON> Slouf </PERSON>, a deputy mayor of <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION>. `` Any new elected government will be unpopular within months.'' Speaking privately, Czechoslovak specialists wonder if any political leaders will be able to break up the forbidding mass of state monopolies for industries and services. One reformer, who asked not to be named, put it: `` These mafias of managers are too organized, too well protected. They do n't want change. There are so many ways to resist.'' The economy was shaped within the Soviet bloc when central planners prepared to parallel _ and outdo _ the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION>. The systems, though outmoded and largely discredited, remain intact. <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>'s largest employer is an uncompetitive steel industry. It makes its own version of three-quarters of the world's range of engineering items Unlike <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> borrowed little and kept up reserves. As other economies failed, it supplied their staples. With a touch of national pride, leaders subjected Socialist brothers to customs barriers. Czechoslovak economists agree they must avoid borrowing until loans can be put to use expanding earnings. Meantime, the economy needs `` devizy,'' hard currency. Tourism is a potential source. <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> is among <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s most beautiful cities. The countryside, in forests and mountains, is often dramatic. Other service industries are virgin ground for joint ventures. `` A lot is possible,'' <PERSON> Slouf </PERSON> said. `` But you only have to look at the experience of our neighbors. It will not be simple.''
</TEXT>
