<HEAD>Extreme Rightist Politician Faces Criminal Charge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Right-wing extremist <PERSON> Jean-Marie </PERSON> <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Pen </PERSON> could face criminal prosecution for remarks linking a <ORGANIZATION> French </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> minister's name to <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> death camps. Court action is possible because the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>, by a vote of 178-91 on Monday, lifted his immunity. The French <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> had asked the Parliament to remove the immunity of the leader of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> so he could be taken to court on charges of slandering a government minister. <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Pen </PERSON>, at a rally on Sept. 2, 1988, spoke of <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> Minister <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Durafour </PERSON> as `` Durafour-crematoire.'' Crematoire can be used to refer to the crematories where the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION> burned the bodies of their death-camp victims. As a member of the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION> Strasbourg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Pen </PERSON> has immunity from prosecution unless the legislature votes to remove it. Conviction of slandering a <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> minister is punishable by a jail sentence of up to three months and a maximum fine of $ 13,000.
