<SECOND>AM-Helmsley, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0696,0975</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hotel Queen Leona Helmsley Gets 4 Years</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 9-10, `Mrs. Helmsley, wearing ...' with two grafs
to CORRECT her quote to ``I've been found guilty'' sted ``I am guilty''</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos NY30, NY39, NY40</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Leona </PERSON> <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON> was sentenced Tuesday to four years in prison and fined $ 7.1 million by a federal judge who ignored her sobbing plea for mercy and blamed the hotel queen's tax evasion on `` naked greed.'' <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> also sentenced Mrs. <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON>, 69, to three years of probation and 750 hours of community service at <ORGANIZATION> Hale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, a home for infants born addicted to drugs. Mrs. <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON> _ said to have boasted to a maid, `` We do n't pay taxes. Only the little people pay taxes.'' _ was also ordered to repay nearly $ 1.7 million in back taxes and bear the government's costs in bringing her to justice `` Your conduct was a product of naked greed. ... You believed you were above the law and displayed no remorse or contrition,'' <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> told Mrs. <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON>. He said she shirked a `` moral responsibility to uphold the law'' that came with her position, breaking the law `` consciously and repeatedly.'' `` No person,'' he said, `` no matter how wealthy and prominent, stands above the law.'' <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> allowed Mrs. <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON> to remain free pending a decision on her appeal of her Aug. 30 conviction on 33 counts of tax evasion. Should her appeals fail and she goes to prison, she would be eligible for parole after serving a year and three months. Mrs. <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON> could have been sentenced to 127 years in prison if she had been given the maximum sentence for each of her convictions and been ordered to serve them consecutively, which is rare. Mrs. <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON>, wearing a black dress with a gold pendant, told <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> before sentencing, `` I am more humiliated and ashamed than anybody can ever imagine that I've