sley </PERSON> fancied after seeing a similar system at Disney World. There were other expenses: $ 58 for leg waxing, $ 21 for a membership in a crossword club, several purchases of lingerie and underwear. Employees who testified at her trial described her as a capricious, despotic boss who fired people on a whim. When she balked at paying a contractor who built an outdoor barbecue pit at the estate, an employee reminded her that the man had six children. He should have kept his pants on, she replied. These revelations led <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> to describe her as `` the wicked witch'' and developer <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> to call her a `` sick woman.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON> told the judge that coverage of the trial had forced her and her husband to hide from the public in their house. Her attorney, <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> Feffer </PERSON>, told <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> his client had become a `` lightning rod'' for hate mail, death threats and anti-Semitic remarks. `` She has been ridiculed, abused and humiliated in an unprecedented way, having nothing to do with her wrongdoing.'' He asked that her sentence be limited to community service at <ORGANIZATION> Hale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>. Prosecutors asked for up to 15 years of prison time. Two employees were tried and convicted along with Mrs. <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON>. Co-defendant <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Licari </PERSON> received 30 months in prison, three years probation and a $ 75,000 fine. Co-defendant <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Turco </PERSON>, another <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON> employee, received a two-year term, three years probation and a $ 50,000 fine. Her husband originally was charged, but his case was dropped when it was found his mental capacity had diminished. During the two-hour proceeding Tuesd