<HEAD>Democrats, Republicans Signal Fray Over Defense Cuts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Democrats and Republicans are clashing over the adequacy of defense cuts being weighed by the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration, even as former <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> officials support larger reductions. A <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> hearing, held Tuesday to consider the depth of savings that might be found in the defense budget, offered a preview of the partisan clashes likely to dominate debate over the fiscal 1991 budget. While committee Chairman <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Sasser </PERSON>, D-Tenn., argued that military spending can be reduced well below current levels, ranking Republican <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> Domenici </PERSON> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> insisted that cutbacks must be deliberate and well studied <PERSON> Sasser </PERSON> said that as a result of the military buildup of the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration, this year's $ 285 billion <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> budget is $ 70 billion above the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> peacetime average since World War II, excluding the <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> war years. `` Those massive expenditures have ... diverted us from the enterprise of building a sounder, more productive domestic economy,'' he said. <PERSON> Domenici </PERSON>, however, warned that a reduction of the defense budget will have to occur slowly and will not necessarily be an economic panacea. `` Will it solve the problems relating to health care costs?'' he asked. `` Will it make our children study harder in school? Will it make Americans more productive?'' Former <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> McNamara </PERSON> and another one-time top <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> official called for military cuts surpassing those the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration is considering. <PERSON> McNamara </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Korb </PERSON> sought to justify their separate proposals by citing a need to address domestic problems and react to the easing of East-West tensions. `` In the face of ... economic and social problems, it would be folly to spend more than we need for defense,'' <PERSON> McNamara </PERSON>, who served as <ORGANIZATION> defense </ORGANIZATION> secretary under Presidents <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> and <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, told the committee. `` We are doing so.'' <PERSON> McNamara </PERSON> called for holding military spending to $ 290 billion in fiscal 1991, which begins Oct. 1, and cutting it gradually to $ 265 billion in 1994. <PERSON> Korb </PERSON>, assistant defense secretary for manpower and reserve policy from 1981 to 1985, said pressures created by the Gramm-Rudman deficit reduction law and Soviet President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s arms reduction proposals make the time right for cuts in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> defense outlays. `` There is no doubt that the combination of Gramm-Rudman-Gorbachev can and should drive the level of defense spending down by about 25 percent'' over the next five years, <PERSON> Korb </PERSON> told the lawmakers. Under his proposal, the defense budget would drop to $ 225 billion by 1995. The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration is studying cutting the projected rate of growth for <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> spending by up to $ 180 billion over 1992 to 1994, reductions that would still leave military outlays above $ 290 billion for each of those years.
