<HEAD>Bogus Health Plans May Leave Workers Without Benefits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Thousands of workers risk being stuck with paying their own medical bills because of bogus insurance plans that the federal government allows but does n't police, authorities say. The <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s efforts to monitor so-called multiple employer welfare arrangements `` are sorely lacking or are non-existent,'' <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> Donovan </PERSON> <PERSON> Petersen </PERSON>, deputy insurance commissioner in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state, told a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on legislation and national security on Tuesday. The arrangements, which pool health care coverage for small employers who ca n't get coverage from larger insurance carriers, were created under the federal Employee Retirement Income Security Act. States generally regulate insurance and require cash reserves to back claims, witnesses told the <ORGANIZATION> Government </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Operations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>'s subcommittee The health insurance arrangements generally do not maintain reserves to pay claims, said <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Maria </PERSON>, acting inspector general for the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. Ms. <PERSON> Petersen </PERSON> acknowledged that the reserve requirements would hurt many beneficial operators. `` With the expectation of staying afloat for a period of time through aggressive selling and slow claims payment, these fraudulent -LRB- arrangements -RRB- have become a variation of the classic Ponzi scheme,'' <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> said. Many operators abscond with the funds, leaving the workers high and dry, the two witnesses said. Some 5 million such arrangements exist nationwide, <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> said. The number of fraudulent ones is unknown. State enforcement agencies have been frustrated `` by multi-state fraud schemes, limited resources and historical unresponsiveness'' by the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. Both <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> and Ms. <PERSON> Petersen </PERSON> said the operators try to escape state enforcement by claiming that the federal government has jurisdiction. But Ms. <PERSON> Petersen </PERSON> said her efforts to bring in the federal government bore no fruit. She said she was shuttled between the Office of Inspector General and the <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pension </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Welfare </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Benefit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> until she finally gave up and used what state court action she could in an investigation begun in 1988. She said she could n't even get a list of operators. `` You are not required to obtain a license or certificate of authority to operate from the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION>,'' she said. She said she was investigating two operators. One ran programs known as the <ORGANIZATION> Western </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Western </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Timber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Western </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION>; and one ran a program known as the <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loggers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. By the time she obtained a state court order, the operator of <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loggers </ORGANIZATION> had left the state with the program funds and `` hundreds of consumers in some six states with thousands _ probably hundreds of thousands _ of dollars of unpaid medical claims and with no medical coverage.'' `` To date I know of no criminal, civil or other disciplinary action taken or planned by any division of the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> or any other entity,'' she said, adding that the operator, <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stone </PERSON>, has settled in <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> and is setting up another plan. Unpaid medical claims for the other companies total at least $ 100,000.
