<HEAD>Comedy is King in Nielsen Ratings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Comedy is still king in the <PERSON> Nielsen </PERSON>'s weekly ratings book as sitcoms held the top six spots. <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` The Cosby Show'' was first again, and <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Roseanne'' moved up to third place behind <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Cheers,'' according to the <ORGANIZATION> A.C. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nielsen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> ratings for last week's prime-time shows. <PERSON> Cosby </PERSON>'s ratings, as well as his assurance he wants to do another season at <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>, is good news for the first-place network. Despite published reports that <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> had sought his show, <PERSON> Cosby </PERSON> said he wanted to stay with <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>. CBS had negotiated with producers <PERSON> Marcy </PERSON> <PERSON> Carsey </PERSON> and <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Werner </PERSON> for their services as programming chiefs and purchase of their company, which produces `` Cosby'' and <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Roseanne.'' <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> won the week survey by more than 2 ratings points. <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> had an average of 14.2 to <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>'s 11.9 and CBS' 11.3. Each point is the percentage of the nation's 92.1 million homes with televisions tuned to a show. For the season, <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> leads with a 15.0 average to <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>'s 13.3 and CBS' 12.2. Once again, <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> placed its entire Thursday night schedule, plus two comedies from Saturday, in the top 10. Here are last week's top shows: <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` The Cosby Show'' and `` Cheers''; <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Roseanne''; <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` A Different World,'' `` Dear <PERSON> John </PERSON>,'' and `` The Golden Girls''; <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION>' `` 60 Minutes'' and `` Murder, She Wrote''; <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` L.A. Law'' and `` Empty Nest.'' <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s plans to move `` Dear John'' from Thursday to Wednesday in early January could be bad news for the show starring <PERSON> Judd </PERSON> <PERSON> Hirsch </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> will replace it on Thursday with a new show, `` Grand,'' from the <ORGANIZATION> Carsey-Werner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Entertainment </ORGANIZATION> president <PERSON> Brandon </PERSON> <PERSON> Tartikoff </PERSON> said at a televised briefing for affiliate stations Monday that he felt `` Dear <PERSON> John </PERSON>'' was strong enough to survive the move and would be compatible with `` Night Court. He defended giving the coveted Thursday spot to `` Grand,'' saying the show needed nurturing and that <ORGANIZATION> Carsey-Werner </ORGANIZATION> had done well. Three CBS Monday night comedies improved their ratings. `` Designing Women'' moved up to 18th place. `` Newhart'' was 21st and `` <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>'' was tied for 26th. <ORGANIZATION> Fox </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>'s top-rated show is `` Married ... With Children'' in 47th place. However, the <PERSON> Fox </PERSON> shows are down in the ratings since their late summer surge when <PERSON> Fox </PERSON> ran original shows against network reruns. <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> was first in the evening news ratings with 11.2 to <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION>' 10.2 and <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s 9.9.
