<HEAD>1989 Cotton Crop to be Smaller Than Previous Year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Agriculture Department says the 1989 cotton crop is expected to be slightly less than 12.1 million bales, down 22 percent from last year's harvest but virtually the same as estimated in November. In its new estimate Tuesday, based on field conditions as of Dec. 1, the department's <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Statistics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said a 20 percent drop in the acreage for harvest and slightly lower yields account for the decline from 1988 levels. Overall, cotton farmers had 9.53 million acres for harvest this fall, down 20 percent from 1988. The yield is expected to average 608 pounds per acre, down 11 pounds from last year but up a pound from the November forecast. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> states experienced favorable weather during harvest and show an increase from last month,'' the report said. `` In <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, an October freeze lowered expected yields.'' But cotton harvest made good progress last month in the Plains and could be completed ahead of normal, the report said. By Dec. 3, the harvest was 89 percent completed in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, compared with 75 percent a year earlier and the average of 60 percent. Orange production was forecast at 194 million boxes, unchanged from the previous forecast two months ago based on Oct. 1 indications, but 6 percent below last season. `` This decline is due mostly to <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>'s 11 percent decrease from last season,'' the report said. `` Freezing weather in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> during late February killed some of the open bloom and damaged new growth.'' The report also indicated dry edible bean production this year at 24.1 million hundredweight, up 25 percent from last year's drought-reduced harvest but still 7 percent short of 1987 production Acreage for harvest was up 24 percent from last year and the average yield, at 1,436 pounds per acre, was up 1 percent. <PERSON> Burley </PERSON> tobacco production was estimated at 543 million pounds, up 14 percent from 1988 but fractionally below the November forecast. The area for harvest is up 13 percent from last year and the average yield is up 18 pounds per acre. No new estimates were issued for the major field crops such as corn, wheat and soybeans. In a related report, the department's world outlook board said prospective levels of cotton production and use in 1989 remain at near the levels indicated last month, although production prospects are up on a few foreign countries. `` This likely will mean reduced needs for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> cotton in world markets and lower <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> export prospects,'' the report said. The global outlook for wheat is `` largely unchanged'' from the November forecast, the report said. For corn, sorghum, oats and other so-called coarse grains, 1989-90 production and inventories a year from now are expected to be down marginally from last month's outlook `` Larger output is forecast for <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>,'' the report said. `` However, these gains are more than offset by smaller crops in the <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and several other countries.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Private exporting companies have sold the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> an additional 103,632 metric tons of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> corn for delivery in 1989-90 under a long-term supply agreement. The <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday that the corn was shifted by exporters from `` unknown destinations'' to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> for 1989-90 delivery. Orders since Oct. 1, the beginning of the agreement's new year, total 160,700 tons of soybeans, 705,000 tons of soybean meal and 7,300 tons of barley. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> grain sales to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> in 1988-89 were a record of more than 21.7 million tons, including more than 16.3 million tons of corn and nearly 5.4 million tons of wheat. In addition, 1988-89 sales included 298,700 tons of soybeans, 1.35 million tons of soybean meal and 1.02 million tons of grain sorghums. A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 39.4 bushels of corn or 36.7 bushels of wheat or soybeans. The 103,632 tons of corn would be about 4.1 million bushels. The new sales were made by unidentified private exporting companies, which are required to report large sales to the department. No selling prices or further details were released. Corn prices have been averaging about $ 2.22 per bushel at the farm level, according to <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION>'s five-day average, meaning that the latest sale could have a farm value of about $ 9 million.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Agriculture Secretary <PERSON> Clayton </PERSON> <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> says that among the things <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> needs to boost food production are agricultural chemicals, currently the target of environmentalists and federal regulators in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. `` We need to do whatever we can to improve agricultural productivity in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> said Tuesday at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION>. `` Interestingly, there were two principal requests in this area.'' High-protein supplements for livestock feed were one, and agricultural chemicals were the other. `` As we have experienced the situation here where folks are wanting to ban agricultural chemicals in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, the No. 1 priority on the list in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> was agricultural chemicals,'' he said. But the aid package approved by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> does n't include such chemicals, <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> said `` There's little that we can do, perhaps nothing that we can do in the way of agricultural chemicals from a governmental standpoint.'' Thus, he said, the private sector may have to meet <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s request for farm chemicals through grants and donations <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> recently led a presidential mission to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> to help determine what kind of aid may be needed to help that country rebuild its agriculture.
