<FIRST>r a PM-HinduTaxidermist     12-13 0571</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hindu Taxidermist,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hindu Makes His Living Stuffing Animals</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRANDYWINE, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Lucky for Thakorial Mistry, there are no sacred cows in his business. Mistry is probably the only Hindu taxidermist in the world. It might seem strange that a Hindu would make a living stuffing and mounting animals, for Hindus revere living creatures and believe in reincarnation. The people in his hometown outside <LOCATION> Bombay </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, were mostly vegetarians and would never kill an animal, he said. Only the poorest and hungriest would eat a chicken, but only behind closed doors. No wonder that <PERSON> Mistry </PERSON> was considered an oddball _ or worse _ when he began his boyhood hobby of taxidermy. His first specimen was a pigeon, which he grabbed in the rafters of his home, chloroformed and stuffed with cotton. `` It did n't turn out real good but it looked good to me, until it started to smell,'' Mistry said. The boy bagged small birds and chipmunks with a BB gun and stuffed them in the privacy of his attic bedroom. Mistry's secret escaped the notice of his father, the town blacksmith and a devout Hindu, but his neighborhood pals were fascinated. `` I always enjoyed opening animals,'' he said. `` I love animals. My friends thought I was crazy, but when I finished they thought I had created something beautiful. Even my parents, when they found out, they liked it too.'' Mistry arrived in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in 1971 with a degree in chemistry and zoology, about $ 6 in his pocket and plans for a career in medical technology. However, he said, `` my hobby turned into a living.'' After an apprenticeship with taxidermy shops in <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, he went into business for himself in 1976. His large studio in this rural community south of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION> is filled with striking examples of Mistry's artistry, including deer, bear, bison, pheasant, peacocks, fish and big game from <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. Beneath a mounted shark, a red fox leaps after a pair of grouse rising in flight. Two gamecocks lunge in battle, their neck feathers bristling. Mistry, 43, assisted by his wife <PERSON> Jyotsna </PERSON>, stuffs about 1,000 creatures annually, at prices ranging from $ 6 an inch for freshwater fish to as much as $ 2,000 for a grizzly bear. Business is profitable enough for Mistry, who became a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> citizen in 1979, to support his family of four and to help nearly two dozen relatives immigrate from <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>. Lounging on the marble floor of his showroom is one customer's unclaimed white Pekinese dog, one of many small pets that Mistry has lovingly freeze-dried for their grieving owners The Pekinese would make a dandy doorstop, but <PERSON> Mistry </PERSON> says it's so lifelike that `` it makes a good guard dog'' to scare would-be intruders peering through the windows Mistry recalls with a grin the time a husband called to ask, `` Can you stuff my wife?'' On another occasion, a lawyer telephoned to say his client had written a will requesting that his body be freeze-dried. Mistry turned them both down. `` I could do a human being, but it's illegal,'' he said. `` Even if it were legal, I would n't do it.'' How does he feel about stuffing a cow, the most sacred animal in the Hindu religion? `` Sure, I could do a cow,'' Mistry replied. `` No problem. You've got to change to survive wherever you go This is <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>.''
</TEXT>
