<BYLINE>U.S. Says Prison Terms For Drug Killers `Tantamount to Life' ^By
JOHN WRIGHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials are hailing the stiff sentences handed to a pair of Mexican drug lords convicted of masterminding the torture-slayings of a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> narcotics agent and his pilot. `` My heartfelt congratulations go to the government of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and its judicial authorities for their decisive and correct action,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Lawn </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enforcement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Rafael </PERSON> <PERSON> Caro </PERSON> <PERSON> Quintero </PERSON>, 37, and <PERSON> Ernesto </PERSON> <PERSON> Rafael </PERSON> <PERSON> Fonesca </PERSON> <PERSON> Carrillo </PERSON>, 56, were convicted Tuesday of masterminding the 1985 murders of <ORGANIZATION> DEA </ORGANIZATION> agent <PERSON> Enrique </PERSON> <PERSON> Camarena </PERSON> and his Mexican pilot and sentenced to 40 years in prison. `` There is no chance of these sentences being reduced,'' Attorney General <PERSON> Enrique </PERSON> <PERSON> Castillo </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Alvarez </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Fernando </PERSON> <PERSON> Arias </PERSON>, a spokesman for the attorney general, said <PERSON> Caro </PERSON> <PERSON> Quintero </PERSON> and <PERSON> Fonseca </PERSON> would have to serve a total of 74 and 53 years respectively because of other drug-related convictions. There is no parole in drug-related cases. Lawn said the stiff sentences are `` tantamount to life imprisonment'' and send a stern warning to other drug kinpins. He said it shows that `` no matter how wealthy and powerful their infamous trade has made these narco-murderers, they are not beyond the reach of justice.'' <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamilton </PERSON>, spokesman for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> drug czar <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PE