h <ORGANIZATION> Criminal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Guadalajara </LOCATION>, a major drug trafficking center 350 miles west of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> where <PERSON> Camerena </PERSON> was based. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> agent was kidnapped there on Feb. 7, 1985. His pilot, <PERSON> Alfredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Zavala </PERSON> <PERSON> Avelar </PERSON>, was abducted a few days later. Their bullet-riddled bodies were found on March 5 in shallow graves on a ranch 60 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Guadalajara </LOCATION>, the capital of <LOCATION> Jalisco </LOCATION> state. Both <PERSON> Camarena </PERSON> and <PERSON> Fonseca </PERSON> are multi-millionaires whose assets include ranches, aircraft, luxury cars, houses, apartments, hotels and businesses which the government is in the process of confiscating. <PERSON> Caro </PERSON> <PERSON> Quintero </PERSON> and <PERSON> Fonseca </PERSON> also were sentenced Tuesday on several other kidnapping, drug trafficking and weapons charges related to the <PERSON> Camarena </PERSON> case. The sentences, which will be served concurrently, add up to 116 years for <PERSON> Caro </PERSON> <PERSON> Quintero </PERSON> and 144 for <PERSON> Fonseca </PERSON>. <PERSON> Caro </PERSON> <PERSON> Quintero </PERSON> was sentenced to 34 years in another drug case earlier this year and <PERSON> Fonseca </PERSON> was given 13 years. These sentences will run consecutively to those in the <PERSON> Camarena </PERSON> case. Ten other men were sentenced to the maximum term of 40 years for taking part in the killings, and 13 other men received lesser sentences for their involvement in drug operations run by <PERSON> Caro </PERSON> <PERSON> Quintero </PERSON> and <PERSON> Fonseca </PERSON>.
