<HEAD>Transferred Police Dog Returning to Memphis</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An aging police dog whose transfer to <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> provoked protests by congressmen and schoolchildren, is returning to <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION>. The German shepherd named <PERSON> Magoo </PERSON> was transferred in September by the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, spurring petitions and angry letters. `` There's no telling how many letters the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> may have received,'' police Sgt. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Petrowski </PERSON>, <PERSON> Magoo </PERSON>'s former partner and guardian, said Tuesday. <PERSON> Magoo </PERSON> first moved to <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION> six years ago as part of an airport security program. Though assigned to the city dog squad, he remained <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> property. <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION> police withdrew from the airport program about a year ago, and the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> subsequently decided to transfer <PERSON> Magoo </PERSON>. <PERSON> Petrowski </PERSON> collected 7,000 names on a petition he sent to President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. And among those writing on <PERSON> Magoo </PERSON>'s behalf were Gov. <PERSON> Ned </PERSON> <PERSON> McWherter </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>'s two <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> senators and two congressmen. `` One teacher at <ORGANIZATION> Bartlett </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Elementary </ORGANIZATION> called me and said she had used -LRB- newspaper -RRB- stories about <PERSON> Magoo </PERSON> in her class,'' <PERSON> Petrowski </PERSON> said. `` They had all written letters to the president and letters to their pen pals, telling them to write letters to the president to try to get him back.'' <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Barker </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> said his agency reviewed <PERSON> Magoo </PERSON>'s transfer again and agreed to return him to <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION> on the city's promise he would be available for airport bomb duty if needed. <PERSON> Petrowski </PERSON> said <PERSON> Magoo </PERSON> will continue his general police assignments and any needed airport work, but at 8 years old, the dog likely will retire in a year or two. <PERSON> Magoo </PERSON> has lived with <PERSON> Petrowski </PERSON> and his family when off duty and is expected to spend his retirement there as well. `` I'm just as happy as I can be,'' <PERSON> Petrowski </PERSON> said, adding that he expects <PERSON> Magoo </PERSON> to be home in about a week.
