<FIRST>r w PM-Bush-Steel     12-13 0457</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Steel,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Signs Bill to Trigger New Steel Trade Program With 28 Nations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is extending steel import restraints on 28 trading partners, while giving the nations incentives to stop subsidizing their steel industries. Renewal of the curbs through March 1992 will `` eliminate trade-distorting practices in the steel sector,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said in a statement Tuesday. The old pacts, negotiated by the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration in 1984, expired on Sept. 30. The legislation signed by <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> authorizes the federal government to continue the curbs for another 2 -LCB- years. The curbs, negotiated individually with leading steel-exporting nations, place annual, product-by-product limits on the volume of steel that can be shipped to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Negotiators in the office of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Trade Representative <PERSON> Carla </PERSON> <PERSON> Hills </PERSON> announced Tuesday that the talks had been recently completed with all nations targeted by the administration. The talks had to be conducted before <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> signed the bill so that the import program would not lapse. The resulting new pacts will hold the foreign share of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> steel market to 19.1 percent in the first year of the program, <PERSON> Hills </PERSON> said in a statement. She said import restraint agreements had been finalized with the 12-nation European Community and <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Finland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, the Peoples Republic of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Trinidad </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Tobago </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s signature on the `` Steel Trade Liberalization Act'' had been expected for some time. Not only did <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> promise to renew import curbs during the 1988 campaign, but his administration orchestrated a compromise last summer between lawmakers favoring a five-year extension of the restraints and congressional opponents who wanted the program ended. The idea behind the original pacts was to give domestic steelmakers breathing space from subsidized, foreign competition. Many steel-state lawmakers had pushed the administration to extend the curbs for another five years, but <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> opted for a smaller-scale program in deference to steel-using manufacturers. The manufacturers argued that the quotas have driven up prices and caused supply shortages of some steel products. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> called the country-by-county agreements a `` stepping stone'' to the day when all trade-distorting subsidies could be eliminated. The program is structured to give nations incentives to trade freely. For example, the pacts allow some countries' market shares to rise by 1 percentage point per year until quotas are phased out entirely at the end of the program. <PERSON> Hills </PERSON> said the yearly increase will be allocated to nations that exhibit the most willingness to stop subsidizing their domestic steelmakers. Some nations have already been granted such status, <PERSON> Hills </PERSON> said. She identified those Tuesday as the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Trinidad </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Tobago </LOCATION>.
