<FIRST>r w PM-LeaseViolations     12-13 0694</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lease Violations,670</SECOND>
<HEAD>Poor Enforcement Allows Violation of Rules in Oil and Gas Leasing
Program</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> is allowing many violations of environmental regulations under its oil and gas leasing program because of lax monitoring, according to an internal audit. The report by the department's Inspector General's Office said Tuesday that oil and gas lease operators on federal or Indian lands `` who commit violations ... often do so without fear of being punished'' because civil penalties are rarely assessed. Even when lease operators are shown to be repeat offenders, their poor record often was swept clean without monetary penalties if corrections on specific violations were made, the investigators added. The report covered the federal <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Land </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION>'s scrutiny of oil and gas leases throughout the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> during a two-year period beginning in fiscal 1988 Investigators focused on activities in eight bureau offices with jurisdiction over more than 39,000 oil and gas wells, about half of those under the federal program. All the wells are either on federal or Indian land. Bureau spokesman <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Johns </PERSON> said the agency was reviewing the report, but that the bureau agreed generally with many of the findings and recommendations. A formal response by the agency is expected to be completed by February, he said. `` Violations of existing regulations have resulted in environmental damage, lost or unpaid royalties, and a potentially substantial government liability for plugging abandoned wells and cleaning up well sites,'' the report said. The report said that during fiscal 1988, federal inspectors uncovered 1,317 violations of environmental regulations and other infractions but assessed only $ 11,500 in penalties. Among the violations were 277 that were considered `` major,'' the report said. In many cases, however, environmental violations and questionable activities by lease holders went unnoticed because of inadequate checks on well abandonments, venting practices and other activities, the investigators said. Among the findings were: _ Lease operators are being widely allowed to abandon wells without getting required government approval, leaving no clear picture as to how many wells are productive or whether abandoned wells have been properly closed In some cases, wells were found to have been abandoned 15 years or more without an authorized inspectors' approval and certainty of their environmental condition. _ Unauthorized venting or flaring of natural gas, some dating to the 1960s, is widespread among lease operators, posing environmental concerns and preventing the government from collecting royalties _ about $ 291,000 for an estimated 1 billion cubic feet of gas in the limited number of cases documented _ Bonding requirements are inadequate to protect against smaller lease operators abandoning sites without taking proper environmental precautions In many cases, the government will have to assume responsibility. `` There could be a significant number of wells throughout the country which are either plugged improperly or not plugged and ... these wells could be adversely impacting the environment,'' the report said. The cost of potentially capping some 22,000 wells in question was put at more than $ 300 million. Some of the cases cited involved: _ A <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> lease holder who was told he had to test only nine of his 150 wells to determine whether all of them should be considered temporarily closed, operating or be in line for capping `` They did not want to overburden -LRB- him -RRB-,'' the report said. _ A <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> lease purchaser who was allowed to buy 30 closed or temporarily abandoned wells with a bond of only $ 25,000 After he filed for bankruptcy without capping any of the wells, the government was left with a $ 378,000 bill. _ A lease operator who was shown on videotape dumping extracted saltwater into an unlined, unauthorized pit in violation of environmental regulations Although the operator was told in 35 letters over a two-month period to correct the practice, no monetary penalty was assessed. _ A well on Indian land that blew after a lease holder began extracting natural gas without having conducted promised pressure tests He was fined only $ 5,000 although up to 4 million cubic feet of gas a day were released over 65 days, causing the evacuation of nearby residents and raising concern that local water supplies may have been contaminated.
</TEXT>
