<HEAD>Flaws in Radiation Protection Cited at Weapons Plants</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 3-4, `The inspections ...,' to correct location of
Fernald plant to make it near Cincinnati sted Dayton and fix typo in Piketon;
picks up 5th graf pvs, `The Pantex ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Workers at several government nuclear weapons plants face unnecessary risks of radiation contamination, in part because too little is spent on protective measures, according to <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> inspection reports. The problem persists despite greatly increased attention in recent years to health, safety and environmental hazards at the weapons plants. Flaws in worker protection against radiation are a recurring, though little publicized, theme in recently released health and safety reports following inspections of facilities in four states. The inspections by government and private experts, ordered by <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> in June, document radiation control problems at the <ORGANIZATION> Pantex </ORGANIZATION> weapons assembly factory near <LOCATION> Amarillo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>; the Y-12 nuclear materials manufacturing plant at <LOCATION> Oak </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ridge </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>; the Fernald uranium processing plant near <LOCATION> Cincinnati </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, and the Rocky Flats plutonium processing plant near <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colo </LOCATION>. Inspections also were conducted at weapons sites in <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo. </LOCATION>, Mercury, <LOCATION> Nev. </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Piketon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, but the results have not yet been publicly released. All 17 major weapons facilities eventually are to undergo such inspections. The <ORGANIZATION> Pantex </ORGANIZATION> report published last week said that while inspectors found no clear and immediate danger to worker safety, the radiation protection program was generally inadequate as evidenced by `` extensive'' violations of federal regulations. The report said the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> and the company that runs <ORGANIZATION> Pantex </ORGANIZATION> under a government contract, <ORGANIZATION> Mason </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Hanger-Silas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mason </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, have been aware of the problem for several years, yet `` little has been achieved to correct it.'' In a memo attached to the <ORGANIZATION> Pantex </ORGANIZATION> report, <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> said the findings indicate workers are not adequately protected from routine and emergency releases of radiation. He ordered immediate action to fix the problems. In late October, <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> ordered special action to correct weaknesses in radiation protection at the Y-12 plant at the federal <LOCATION> Oak </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ridge </LOCATION> nuclear reservation. The Y-12 inspection team reported a variety of major problems. Among them was a failure of the plant's health physics specialists to routinely check radiation levels in all areas where significant amounts of radiation could be present. The report also said radiation survey results often are poorly documented, and that the plant does not routinely check for flaws in warning devices and other safety features of equipment that generates radiation. For example, such checks are not routinely done on electron-beam welders, which produce radiation fields comparable to, and sometimes higher than, X-ray machines, the report said. The inspectors said no health physics specialists were present to monitor radiation levels when workers removed an air filter from the roof of a building at the Y-12 plant, `` despite the potential for spreading contamination on the roof and also for an unmonitored release of airborne radiation.'' Also, the report said `` safety work permits'' prepared for employees at Y-12 were `` not an effective means of informing workers of the radiological conditions that may be encountered at the job site.'' Significant flaws in radiation protection also were found by inspectors at <LOCATION> Fernald </LOCATION>, where production lines were closed earlier this year because of pressing environmental problems. Workers at one <PERSON> Fernald </PERSON> building may have unknowingly ingested radioactive uranium metal aerosols because of ventilation defects in an area where workers are not required to wear respirators, the inspection report of last August said. Only limited corrections can be made at <ORGANIZATION> Fernald </ORGANIZATION> because of a lack of money, the report said. Budget problems also prevent a quick correction of deficiencies in training of radiation workers and radiation protection technicians, the report said. Inspectors of the Rocky Flats plant, which makes plutonium triggers for nuclear weapons, cited a variety of radiation contamination problems, including uncertainty about the accuracy of measurements of plutonium particles in the air. They said the measuring equipment is old and prone to breakdowns. Rocky Flats' plutonium operations were shut down last month for a management shakeup. Last year the plant was closed for several months after two employees walked unknowingly into a contaminated area and inhaled radioactive particles.
