<HEAD>Leona Helmsley: Rags to Riches to Prison</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Helmsley, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Once she was a cigarette girl. Later, she became a queen. Now, <PERSON> Leona </PERSON> <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON> is a felon facing the prospect of trading her ermine robes for prison stripes. Mrs. <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON> wo n't immediately lose her freedom. She was sentenced to four years in prison, but has appealed her conviction for evading $ 1.2 million in taxes and remains free on bail. She has long since lost the royal aura projected in ads featuring her and promoting her hotels, which described the flagship <ORGANIZATION> Helmsley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Palace </ORGANIZATION> as `` the only palace in the world where the queen stands guard.'' During her trial, Mrs. <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON> was revealed as a woman who charged underwear and other purchases to her business; who fiercely and vituperatively berated employees, firing them on a whim; who mocked the law. `` We do n't pay taxes,'' a maid quoted Mrs. <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON> as saying. `` Only the little people pay taxes.'' The trial was open season on <PERSON> Leona </PERSON>. In opening arguments, her own attorney labeled her `` a tough bitch.'' In closing, a prosecutor attacked her `` selfishness, greed and sheer arrogance.'' She was scorned almost universally. Mayor <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> called her `` the wicked witch.'' <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> said she was `` a sick woman.'' <PERSON> Leona </PERSON> <PERSON> Mindy </PERSON> <PERSON> Rosenthal </PERSON> was born 69 years ago. Her father was a <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION> hatmaker. She has had several careers; she was a showroom model and a <LOCATION> Chesterfield </LOCATION> cigarette girl. Later, she became a successful real estate broker. She met real estate titan <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON> in 1971. He hired her as a $ 500,000-a-year senior vice president and married her a year later, divorcing his wife of 33 years. <PERSON> Leona </PERSON> <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON> had been married before, too. She divorced her lawyer husband in 1959. She had a son by that marriage, <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Panzirer </PERSON>; she cried in court when his death in 1982 was mentioned, though she had taken his widow to court to deny her money from her son's estate. Mrs. <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON>'s devotion to her husband and his devotion to her have never been questioned. She calls him `` gorgeous one ... pussycat ... snooky, wooky, dooky.'' For her birthday, he lighted the Empire State Building _ in which he holds a major stake _ red, white and blue. The <ORGANIZATION> Helmsleys </ORGANIZATION> head a real estate empire valued at $ 5 billion, and their personal wealth is estimated at $ 1 billion. They live lavishly in <LOCATION> Palm </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>; at a duplex atop <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>'s Park Lane Hotel; and at their 28-room mansion, <PERSON> Dunnellen </PERSON> <PERSON> Hall </PERSON>, in <LOCATION> Greenwich </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Dunnellen </PERSON> <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> was at the center of the allegations against the <ORGANIZATION> Helmsleys </ORGANIZATION> <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON>, 80, originally was charged, but he was found incompetent for trial because of diminished mental capacity. Mrs. <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON> was convicted of charging to the business millions of dollars spent to renovate the home. For the moment, she can still enjoy the marble dance floor on the roof of a pool enclosure, the $ 130,000 indoor-outdoor sound system, the jade art objects that cost $ 500,000. But the judge decided Tuesday that she would have to leave all that behind. He ordered a four-year prison sentence. She would be eligible for parole after 16 months.
