<HEAD>Parliament Approves Law Allowing Prosecution of Alleged Nazi War
Criminals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Parliament's decision to allow the government to prosecute alleged Nazi war criminals is expected to result in the trials of at least three aging emigres suspected of the mass murder of Jews. Rabbi <PERSON> Marvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Hier </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Simon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wiesenthal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, which first brought the issue to the attention of British authorities, issued a statement after Tuesday's vote that said: `` The British Parliament's decision is not an act of vengeance but a victory for justice. It states clearly that crimes against humanity can take no refuge in the passing of time, and keeps faith with the victims of the Holocaust.'' Home Secretary <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Waddington </PERSON> urged the trials, saying, `` It is the instinctive wish of most us to get on with our lives in peace and not to rake over the past. But sometimes one is brought face to face with facts that can not be buried.'' Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> and opposition <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leader <PERSON> Neil </PERSON> <PERSON> Kinnock </PERSON> both voted in favor of prosecution, which passed 348-123. In order for the prosecutions to proceed, <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> must pass further legislation that would enable naturalized British citizens to be prosecuted for crimes committed abroad. The office of the <ORGANIZATION> Director </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prosecutions </ORGANIZATION> would decide whether individual prosecutions should go ahead. <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> have passed similar legislation within the past few years. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> investigates and deports suspects for trial in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. The action in <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> followed the publication of a government-commissioned report July 24 saying there is enough evidence to prosecute four suspects, one of whom has since died. It urged further investigation in another 124 cases. The suspects were not identified in the report published after a year-long investigation by two prominent lawyers, including Sir <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Hetherington </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s former Director of Public Prosecutions. The inquiry was set up after the <ORGANIZATION> Simon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wiesenthal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, which accused <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> of foot-dragging on the issue, submitted a list of suspects to the government in 1986. Almost all the suspects in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> are from <LOCATION> Lithuania </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Latvia </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Ukraine </LOCATION> in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. One suspect, <PERSON> Antanas </PERSON> <PERSON> Gecas </PERSON>, 73, a Lithuanian-born mining engineer living in <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>, has been identified by the British media. He has acknowledged witnessing atrocities while serving in a notorious Lithuanian police battalion. But he says he only watched and is the victim of a Soviet smear campaign. The issue has deeply divided legislators. Opponents argued during Tuesday's debate that prosecutions 45 years after the end of World War II will turn into show trials, rekindling old hatreds with witnesses who are unreliable because of age and bent on revenge. `` Most of the witnesses are either senile, infirm or dead,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> legislator <PERSON> Winston </PERSON> <PERSON> Churchill </PERSON>, grandson of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s World War II leader. `` This would lead to the establishment of show trials in this country and has no place in British justice.'' Supporters argued passionately that <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> should not remain what several called `` a safe haven for monsters.'' `` These are not crimes committed in the heat of battle,'' said legislator Sir <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> Braine </PERSON>. `` These are cases of the murder of non-combatants and the slaughter of whole communities of women and children.''
