<HEAD>New York Federal Judge Calls for Legalizing Drugs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The so-called war on drugs is a failure and drugs from cocaine to heroin should be legalized, taxed and dispensed by the state, a federal judge says. In his speech Tuesday evening at the <ORGANIZATION> Cosmopolitan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sweet </PERSON> became the first federal judge to propose publicly that illicit drugs be made legal, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Policy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>, a non-profit organization in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> that researches alternatives to current drug policy. `` I suggest it is time to abolish the prohibition _ to cease treating indulgence in mind alteration as a crime,'' Sweet said. `` More money, more prisoners, more addicts _ these numbers demonstrate to me our present prohibitive policy has failed, flatly and without serious question.'' Among the other prominent individuals favoring legalization are former Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> Kurt </PERSON> <PERSON> Schmoke </PERSON>, economist <PERSON> Milton </PERSON> <PERSON> Friedman </PERSON> and conservative columnist <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Buckley </PERSON>. Sweet said proverty caused the drug epidemic, and drug dealing will continue to attract some poor people as long as potential profits are high. `` Perhaps we must ask not what can we do to eliminate drugs, but what can we do to eliminate or at least reduce the level of poverty,'' he said. Sweet, a former <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> deputy mayor and prosecutor, and a trial judge in the <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> for more than 11 years, said the effort to stem the drug epidemic by jailing more people is not working. He cited a declining commitment to jobs, education, health and housing in the nation at a time when building jails has become a growth industry. The enormous increase of criminal drug trials on the docket forces long delays in civil matters. No juries were available in <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>'s federal court in September for civil trials, he said. Legalizing drugs would identify users, raise revenue for prevention and rehabilitation, and eliminate gangs and drug dealers, Sweet said. `` Obviously, the model is the repeal of Prohibition and the end of <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Capone </PERSON> and Dutch <PERSON> Schultz </PERSON>.'' Sweet said pharmaceutical companies could manufacture the drugs and the state could distribute them to addicts for less than what drug dealers charge, with tax revenue used for research, education and treatment of addiction. Distribution to minors should remain prohibited, Sweet said. The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration has said legalization would create an `` unqualified national disaster'' by creating many more addicts. On Tuesday, drug czar <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> compared legalization supporters to advocates of slavery. `` This is not an economic issue. There were arguments made for slavery based on economic considerations,'' <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said at a news conference in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION>. `` For someone to sit in a room and make an abstract bloodless economic argument _ when we're looking at 200,000 cocaine babies a year _ is to miss the point,'' he said. <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> also said he approved of taking custody away from addicted parents in extreme cases. `` Obviously, you give parents _ you give anybody _ the chance to recover, to get better,'' <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said in an interview. `` But supposing the parent is n't getting better, shows no interest in improving, going into treatment, and it's adversely and dramatically affecting the well-being of the child? The state can intervene.'' <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said most states already have legislation that provides for taking children away from addicts who have proven unfit to raise them.
