<HEAD>Appeals Court: Topeka Not Doing Enough to End School Desegregation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HANNA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOPEKA, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal appeals panel ruled that <LOCATION> Topeka </LOCATION> is not doing enough to desegregate its schools since the landmark <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> vs. <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> case, but a dissenting judge cited `` substantial integration.'' In the majority opinion, Judges <PERSON> Stephanie </PERSON> <PERSON> Seymour </PERSON> and <PERSON> Monroe </PERSON> <PERSON> McKay </PERSON> overturned <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON>' 1987 ruling that <LOCATION> Topeka </LOCATION> schools were not responsible for lingering segregation because the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> did not intend to keep the schools segregated. The three-judge panel of the 10th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> released the full decision on the reopened case Tuesday, sending it back to <ORGANIZATION> Rogers </ORGANIZATION>. The original case led to a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruling in 1954 that set a nationwide precedent for school desegregation and busing cases. But the parents of black schoolchildren sued 10 years ago to have the case reopened. The majority opinion, a reworked version of a 2-1 decision last June, was accompanied by a new dissenting opinion. Today, lawyers for both sides expect to receive the latest ruling. <PERSON> Seymour </PERSON> and <PERSON> McKay </PERSON> already had overruled <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON> in June, but Judge <PERSON> Bobby </PERSON> <PERSON> Baldock </PERSON> did n't release his dissent then. The following month, <PERSON> Seymour </PERSON> and <PERSON> McKay </PERSON> withdrew their decision without explanation. Lawyers speculated that they wanted a chance to respond to <PERSON> Baldock </PERSON>'s dissent. In 1979, the parents of 17 black schoolchildren sued the district to reopen the <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> case, contending that the district had failed to eliminate all segregation. Among those parents was <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> <PERSON> Buckner </PERSON>, who was a student at the time of the 1954 decision and whose maiden name heads the caption of the case. <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON> ruled in the reopened case that the school system had no intention to maintain segregated schools. But <PERSON> Seymour </PERSON> wrote: <ORGANIZATION> Rogers </ORGANIZATION> `` erred by limiting the school district's burden merely to showing that it had non-discriminatory reasons for acting as it did. As 30 years of desegregation law have made clear, the Constitution requires more than ceasing to promote segregation.'' <PERSON> Baldock </PERSON> argued the schools had done enough: `` The school board has demonstrated concern for improving the racial composition in the <LOCATION> Topeka </LOCATION> schools while retaining the neighborhood school concept. `` In some places the two are not compatible, but in this system substantial integration has been achieved.'' <PERSON> Rich </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, an attorney for the parents who sought the case's reopening, said lawyers will key on the dissenting opinion `` This is the first time we get to see the dissent,'' he said. `` The school district will be in a position to make a decision.'' The attorney for the school district, <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Zima </PERSON>, said the board plans to schedule a meeting early next week to consider it actions. <PERSON> Zima </PERSON> said the school district could ask all 10 judges on the <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> to hear the case, ask the <ORGANIZATION> U.