<HEAD>Opposition, Communists in Standoff Over Making Havel President</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs to UPDATE with government drafting laws granting
new freedoms, meeting today. Pickup 9th graf, `Mohorita is ...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIRARD C. STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The new opposition-dominated government today said it is drafting laws guaranteeing free assembly and association and freedom of religion, while Communists lawmakers debated how to pick a new president. The proposed reforms were announced by Deputy Premier <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> Carnogursky </PERSON>, a dissident lawyer who was released from jail just two weeks ago and on Sunday was named to the first government in 41 years led by non-Communists. The changes in the penal code would strengthen the independence of the judiciary and reduce the time a person can be held in custody before charges are filed, <PERSON> Carnogursky </PERSON> said. The presidential tussle is the latest battle for a popular opposition movement that in three weeks got the Communists to oust old Stalinist hard-liners and relinquish the party's 41-year monopoly on power. Under the constitution, <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> must elect a president in 14 days. That would be Dec. 23, two weeks after hard-liner <PERSON> Gustav </PERSON> <PERSON> Husak </PERSON> was forced to resign to satisfy the opposition. Some Communist lawmakers want the choice to be made by public referendum. But the opposition, hoping to keep its momentum while it can, is pressing for a quicker decision. <PERSON> Vasil </PERSON> <PERSON> Mohorita </PERSON>, a member of the Communist Politburo, said opposition leaders agreed during negotiations Tuesday that 14 days is n't enough time to choose a president. Many opposition figures favor <PERSON> Vaclav </PERSON> <PERSON> Havel </PERSON>, a playwright and oft-jailed dissident who is the emotional rallying point of the reform movement. After discussions by constitutional lawyers from all parties on Tuesday, <PERSON> Mohorita </PERSON> said it might take from 45 days to 60 days for an election to be held, whether in <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> or by a vote of the people. <PERSON> Mohorita </PERSON> is a senior Communist who negotiated with the opposition the coalition government chosen last week. The Cabinet was the first to make Communists a minority in the government in four decades. <PERSON> Mohorita </PERSON> conceded that <PERSON> Havel </PERSON> `` represents something and in no way can we underestimate his position in society.'' `` What we are trying to find is the least complicated agreement,'' he said. He said the Communists were aware that `` If Mr. <PERSON> Havel </PERSON> was not elected by <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>, that would also create tensions. That's why we're in negotations.'' But <PERSON> Havel </PERSON>, who was being denounced as an isolated, anti-Socialist dissident only a month ago, is apparently difficult for many Communists to accept as president. Central <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> is plastered with posters pushing <PERSON> Havel </PERSON>'s candidacy, and about 500 demonstrators stood outside <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> shouting support for him Tuesday as deputies entered the <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> building <PERSON> Mohorita </PERSON> said the Communists sought the quick solution to the impasse because `` we are more or less facing a constitutional crisis,'' a reference to the 14-day deadline the constitution mandates. Deputy <PERSON> Anton </PERSON> <PERSON> Blazej </PERSON>, speaking on behalf of the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> deputies who dominate the 350-member parliament, proposed amending the constitution to allow for a presidential referendum within a month. It failed to pass. Civic Forum, the opposition movement <PERSON> Havel </PERSON> has guided through the past three weeks of crisis, strongly rejects a referendum. It said that although the idea seemed `` enticingly democratic,'' it in fact would mean swiftly amending a constitution for the second time in less than three weeks, and could lead to a presidential campaign leaving the country `` more divided than united.'' The government instead should press ahead with free elections, the group said in a statement. Then, a new, freely elected <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> would choose a new president. `` We are not concerned with whether <PERSON> Havel </PERSON> would have a better chance'' in Parliament than in a referendum, said Civic Forum spokesman <PERSON> Lubos </PERSON> <PERSON> Dobrovsky </PERSON>. `` We are concerned with democracy having a better chance.'' Last week, Civic Forum indicated there was virtual agreement with the Communists that the president should be a Czech and non-party member, balancing the Communist premier, <PERSON> Marian </PERSON> <PERSON> Calfa </PERSON>, a Slovak. Traditionally, top posts in <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> have been divided between Czechs and Slovaks. <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Dubcek </PERSON>, 68, the leader of the 1968 `` Prague Spring'' reforms that were crushed by a Soviet-led invasion, also is a candidate for president. Others are <PERSON> Ladislav </PERSON> <PERSON> Adamec </PERSON>, who resigned as <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> premier last week after failing to reach an agreement with the opposition; and <PERSON> Cestmir </PERSON> <PERSON> Cisar </PERSON>, a `` Prague Spring'' leader who like <PERSON> Dubcek </PERSON> was expelled from the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> in 1970 but has retained many Socialist ideals. <PERSON> Husak </PERSON>, 76, resigned Sunday after swearing in a government containing some dissidents who were jailed because of his policies after the 1968 invasion. Other hard-liners lost their last leadership positions Tuesday, when they resigned from the presidium that guides the Parliament. The 15 deputies who stepped down included ousted Communist party chief <PERSON> Milos </PERSON> <PERSON> Jakes </PERSON>, who last week also was expelled from party ranks; and <PERSON> Vasil </PERSON> <PERSON> Bilak </PERSON>, the Communist held most responsible for the 1968 invasion.
