<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> said today that embargoes by non-Communist nations helped create the economic problems that caused many of its citizens to flee to other countries in search of better economic opportunity. The commentary by the official <ORGANIZATION> Vietnam </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> also reiterated the government's condemnation of <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>'s forcible repatriation on Tuesday of more than 50 Vietnamese refugees. `` The policies of hostility and economic sanctions ... by some countries against <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> over the past 10 years is one of the reasons causing economic difficulties in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>. This led to the fact that some people fled the country,'' said the commentary carried by the <ORGANIZATION> Voice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Vietnam </ORGANIZATION> radio and monitored in <LOCATION> Bangkok </LOCATION>. `` <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> can not ignore its compatriots who nurtured the illusion of looking for a paradise in other countries and have been detained in camps for years,'' it said. <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> and its colonial ruler, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, flew back home 51 Vietnamese from a <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> camp Tuesday in the first forced repatriation. <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> considers 44,000 Vietnamese who poured into the territory since June 1988 to be illegal immigrants seeking jobs, not political refugees from <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>'s Communist regime. `` <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> always welcomes those who are willing to repatriate and at the same time rejects forced repatriation,'' the commentary said. `` The repatriation from <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, including those who returned on Dec. 12, 1989, are part of the framework of that policy.'' <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> has been largely isolated from the non-Communist world since <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> overthrew the U.S.-backed <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> government in April 1975, triggering the boat exodus. Most non-Communist countries, including <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, imposed or continued embargoes on <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> after its troops invaded <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> in late 1978 and installed a pro-Vietnamese government.
