<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Alfredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON> says the latest Central American accord strips the leftist rebels of any legitimacy and if they do n't disband `` the army will deal with them.'' The five Central American presidents on Tuesday demanded the dismantling of both the leftist <ORGANIZATION> Farabundo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marti </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> and the U.S.-backed Contras fighting in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. The two-day summit in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jose </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION>, was the latest in a series that have raised hopes but failed to bring peace to <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. It was the first to focus on <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>, and it renewed a call earlier this year for the dissolution of the Contras. The joint condemnation of both insurgencies was viewed as a victory for rightist <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON> as well as <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s leftist President <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON>, but it was also clouded by skepticism and suspicion. `` I do not trust <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON>,'' said <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON>. Neither of the rebel armies was represented at the summit and neither has agreed to be disbanded. `` This continues to be the problem with all Central American accords,'' said <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Sanchez </PERSON> <PERSON> Sancho </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Opposition </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, a coalition that opposes <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s leftist Sandinista government in elections set for Feb. 25. <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON> said the five presidents had a position paper from the Salvadoran rebels. `` Two of the presidents laughed. Others read it with dismay,'' he said. `` The impression was that it was too much gall on the part of the <ORGANIZATION> FMLN </ORGANIZATION>, after what they have done, to continue trying to look like <PERSON> Robin </PERSON> <PERSON> Hood </PERSON>.'' <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> said the success of the accord hinges on the cooperation of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> `` has the main responsibility for the demobilization of the Contras because they continue financing them and sending them supplies,'' he said in a national radio and television address in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> on Tuesday. The summit accord implicitly chides the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> by saying `` nations with interests in the region'' should be more directly involved in the peace process. The presidents also requested increased <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> involvement in the effort to demobilize `` irregular forces.'' The Salvadoran rebels have rejected the summit accord, saying it does nothing to contribute to the possibility of a negotiated solution to the civil war they have waged for more than a decade against a series of U.S.-backed governments. `` The <ORGANIZATION> FMLN </ORGANIZATION> can not be demobilized by means of agreements between governments, because it is a legitimate force with popular roots in the whole Salvadoran territory,'' they said in a communique. The summit followed a sharp escalation in the Salvadoran civil war, which has claimed more than 71,000 lives. The rebels launched a huge offensive on Nov. 11 in which more than 1,500 people _ guerrillas, soldiers and civilians _ are estimated to have been killed. The accord calls on the <ORGANIZATION> FMLN </ORGANIZATION> to stop fighting and resume peace talks with <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON>'s rightist government. `` With this agreement, the <ORGANIZATION> FMLN </ORGANIZATION> loses its room to maneuver,'' said <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON>. `` The presidents are saying to the guerrillas: ` You have no right to continue violent actions.''' If the <ORGANIZATION> FMLN </ORGANIZATION> keeps fighting, `` the armed forces of <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> will deal with them,'' <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON> told a news conference Tuesday after returning from the summit. <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON> said his government is willing to resume peace talks broken off by the rebels Oct. 31 after the bombing of a union headquarters. But he said the <ORGANIZATION> FMLN </ORGANIZATION> must cease hostilities first. The <ORGANIZATION> FMLN </ORGANIZATION> had earlier called for a cease-fire with international verification and recognition of territories under their control. `` That position is definitely unacceptable,'' said <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON>. <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> said his delegation insisted on international verification of human rights and again criticized the <LOCATION> Salvadoran </LOCATION> government for the assassination during the <ORGANIZATION> FMLN </ORGANIZATION> offensive of six Jesuit academics. The murders have been blamed on the military. Presidents <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Azcona </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoyo </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Vinicio </PERSON> <PERSON> Cerezo </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION> and host <PERSON> Oscar </PERSON> <PERSON> Arias </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION> also signed the summit accord.
