<HEAD>Bill Would Grant Aquino Further Emergency Powers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLARO CORTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The House of Representatives today approved a bill granting further emergency powers to President <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> to impose law and order after last week's failed coup attempt. In the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, the passage of a similar bill was blocked, with an opposition senator warning the legislation moved the nation a step closer to dictatorship. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> is expected to pass a similar version Thursday. The bill was passed overwhelmingly on second reading in the lower chamber. A final reading will be held Thursday. Lone opposition Sen. <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Ponce </PERSON> <PERSON> Enrile </PERSON>, who once administered martial law under the late <PERSON> Ferdinand </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>, denounced the emergency decree as a move toward dictatorship. But former human rights lawyer Sen. <PERSON> Rene </PERSON> <PERSON> Saguisag </PERSON> defended the move in light of the recent coup attempt. In a speech before the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Enrile </PERSON> said the emergency powers also could be used to extend the lease on the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military bases in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Fidel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramos </PERSON> said today that rebel soldiers who launched the coup attempt Dec. 1 were still capable of staging terror attacks and assassinations, although they surrendered their last stronghold Saturday. <PERSON> Ramos </PERSON> told a news conference the government will no longer seek <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> air cover over <LOCATION> Philippine </LOCATION> territory. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> jets flew over rebel-held bases to discourage more bombing runs on the <LOCATION> Malacanang </LOCATION> presidential palace, and the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> help turned the tide in favor of the government on the first day of the mutiny. The Cabinet also was told that the business community is looking for signs the government will move decisively to address the political, social and economic damage wrought by the sixth and bloodiest attempt so far to oust Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>. Share prices on the <ORGANIZATION> Manila </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> fell for the third consecutive day since trading resumed after the coup attempt. On Dec. 6, Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> declared a nationwide state of emergency, but officials said the legislation would give her further powers. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> versions of the emergency bill grant Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> the power to order the search for weapons and ammunition in private homes without the normal legal constraints. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> voted against allowing Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> to intervene in labor disputes and suspend labor laws which may impede production. A majority of the 23-member <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> voted to keep the provision, regarded by critics as a strike ban. Both versions allow Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> to take over public utilities, such as privately-owned transportation firms if they violate `` national policy.'' The House bill limits Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>'s emergency powers to a 90-day period, while the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> version extends it up to six months.
