<HEAD>Minister's Daughter Freed, Ending 6-Day Ordeal</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 16 grafs to UPDATE with group warning of future kidnappings,
details on woman's release. Pickup 14th graf, `The Kashmir...' Subs last
graf to move down that Singh is Hindu.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ASKARI ZAIDI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SRINAGAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Kidnappers today freed a senior <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> minister's daughter they had held for six days after the government met their demand and released five jailed Moslem militants, officials said. <PERSON> Rubaiya </PERSON> <PERSON> Sayeed </PERSON>, 22, was released two hours after the prisoners went free, thereby ending the first crisis of the 12-day-old government of Prime Minister V.P. <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>, state-run television reported. The chairman of the militants' organization warned of future kidnappings unless the government `` behaves.'' The television flashed a news bulletin saying `` Rubaiya Sayeed Freed,'' interrupting a cricket match between <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. Ms. <PERSON> Sayeed </PERSON>'s father is Home Minister <PERSON> Mufti </PERSON> <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Sayeed </PERSON>. She was kidnapped at gunpoint on Friday in <LOCATION> Srinagar </LOCATION>, the summer capital of <LOCATION> Jammu-Kashmir </LOCATION> state and a popular tourist resort, and the separatist <ORGANIZATION> Kashmir </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> claimed responsibility. Militants had threatened to kill Ms. <PERSON> Sayeed </PERSON>, a medical intern, unless their five jailed comrades were freed. The release followed haggling over the site of the swap and the safety of the prisoners. The five were released at an undisclosed site in the city, culminating five days of negotiations between the government and the front, said the police officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity. About two hours after the militants were released, a dazed Ms. <PERSON> Sayeed </PERSON> was dropped at a friend's house and then taken to her home. Later, she was to be flown to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION> for a reunion with her family. `` By the grace of the Almighty and the blessings of millions of my countrymen, <PERSON> Rubaiya </PERSON> has a new lease on life,'' a relieved <PERSON> Sayeed </PERSON> said after hearing his youngest daughter was safe. `` Our ordeal of anxiety and agony has ended. Their prayers and good wishes have restored our child to us.'' <PERSON> Sayeed </PERSON>, unshaven but smiling and wrapped in a brown shawl, condemned his daughter's captors. `` There is no bravery in attacking a girl. It is cowardly. You do n't need guns and swords to attack a girl,'' he said. `` They have lost the sympathy of the people in the state, in <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> and the world.'' Among the freed militants was <PERSON> Abdul </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamid </PERSON> <PERSON> Sheikh </PERSON>, a top leader in the <ORGANIZATION> Kashmir </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>, police said. Sheikh, who was arrested last month after being wounded in a clash with police, was taken by ambulance from a <LOCATION> Srinagar </LOCATION> hospital to the site and turned over to his organization. The other four were identified as <PERSON> Noor </PERSON> <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Kalwal </PERSON>, <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Altaf </PERSON> <PERSON> Bhat </PERSON>, <PERSON> Sher </PERSON> <PERSON> Khan </PERSON> <PERSON> Azad </PERSON> and <PERSON> Javed </PERSON> <PERSON> Ahmed </PERSON> <PERSON> Zargar </PERSON>, officials said. All had been arrested on suspicion of subversive activities during the past year but no charges had been filed. As news of the swap spread throughout the city, 3,000 people filled the streets, setting off firecrackers, waving <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> flags and shouting anti-India slogans. In <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Amanullah </PERSON> <PERSON> Khan </PERSON>, chairman of the militants' group, said <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> had made `` a wise step'' and he hoped the government would adopt `` a similar wise attitude toward the future of <LOCATION> Kashmir </LOCATION> and leave <LOCATION> Kashmir </LOCATION> honorably instead of waiting until it is shunted out and humiliated by <PERSON> Kashmiri </PERSON> freedom fighters.'' Asked whether the swap would encourage the front to launch a campaign of kidnappings to secure its demands, <PERSON> Khan </PERSON> said: `` It depends on how the Indian government behaves ... because they compelled us to take this step.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Kashmir </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>, which wants <LOCATION> Jammu-Kashmir </LOCATION> to either become independent or part of <LOCATION> Islamic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, commands a large following in the Moslem-dominated <LOCATION> Srinagar </LOCATION>. The front, formed in 1965, has often attacked the government and sponsored successful strikes in <LOCATION> Jammu-Kashmir </LOCATION>, the only Moslem majority state in the predominantly <ORGANIZATION> Hindu </ORGANIZATION> <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>. At <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s request, the government of <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> had appealed to the militants not to harm Ms. <PERSON> Sayeed </PERSON>. Moslems make up 64 percent of the state's 5 million people, but comprise just 11 percent of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s 880 million people. Hindus account for about 80 percent of the population. <LOCATION> Kashmir </LOCATION> is claimed both by <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, and the two countries have fought three wars over the territory since gaining independence from <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> in 1947. In a bid to halt the separatism, the new prime minister appointed <PERSON> Sayeed </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Kashmiri </LOCATION>, as head of a <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> committee on <LOCATION> Jammu-Kashmir </LOCATION> and neighboring <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>, where Sikh militants also are demanding an independent homeland. <PERSON> Sayeed </PERSON> is the first Moslem to be named <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s home minister, a key post that oversees the country's internal security. The appointment was seen as part of <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>'s efforts to appease Moslems who have borne the brunt of Hindu-Moslem religious riots that claimed more than 300 lives this fall. <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> is a Hindu.
