<HEAD>Students' Pedal Copter Certified as Making First Human-Powered Flight</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN LUIS OBISPO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Engineering students who designed a pedal-operated flying machine have been notified that its 6.8 seconds in the air have been certified as the first human-powered helicopter flight, officials said today. `` We are satisfied it was not a jump start, but a bona fide hover that did take place,'' said <PERSON> Malvern </PERSON> <PERSON> Gross </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. The aircraft, dubbed <PERSON> Da </PERSON> <PERSON> Vinci </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> by the students at <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Polytechnic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, hovered about 8 inches off the ground Sunday under the observation of an <ORGANIZATION> NAA </ORGANIZATION> consultant, <LOCATION> Cal </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Poly </LOCATION> spokesman <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> said. The <ORGANIZATION> NAA </ORGANIZATION>, the official keeper of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aviation records, certified the feat late Tuesday, <PERSON> Gross </PERSON> said. Although school officials at the time said the flight lasted 7.1 seconds, the observer clocked it at 6.8 seconds, the agency said. The record-setting flight wo n't be the end of the school's development of human-powered aircraft `` This will just make them work harder,'' <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> said. `` They're already talking about building <PERSON> Da </PERSON> <PERSON> Vinci </PERSON> IV when they get back from vacation.'' Engineering students built the 97-pound, 100-foot-long <PERSON> Da </PERSON> <PERSON> Vinci </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> out of space-age materials, including carbon graphite. The machine was powered by cyclist <PERSON> Greg </PERSON> <PERSON> McNeil </PERSON>. <PERSON> Da </PERSON> <PERSON> Vinci </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> flew twice before, on Nov. 12 and Nov. 27. The experimental vehicle is the fourth pedal-copter built by <LOCATION> Cal </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Poly </LOCATION> students since 1981. When they build <PERSON> Da </PERSON> <PERSON> Vinci </PERSON> IV, the students will try to lighten their flying machine, <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> said. The ultimate goal is a $ 20,000 prize offered by the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Helicopter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> to the first group to fly a human-powered helicopter for one minute and reach a height of at least three meters.
