<HEAD>Communists May Lose Dominant Role in Bulgaria</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with party deciding to abolish
its monoploly on power. CORRECTS that Balev not former interior minister.
Pickup 3rd pvs, `Since his...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TEDDIE WEYR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SOFIA, Bulgaria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The ruling <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> today decided to ask <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> to formally abolish the party's monopoly on power by repealing constitutional clauses guaranteeing party supremacy, state media said. Also today, the party expelled long-time leader <PERSON> Todor </PERSON> <PERSON> Zhivkov </PERSON> along with his son and a close associate, the state <ORGANIZATION> BTA </ORGANIZATION> news agency reported. The developments, which came on the third day of a key session of the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, are in line with new leader <PERSON> Petar </PERSON> <PERSON> Mladenov </PERSON>'s stated goal of reforming the party and democratizing society. They also are in line with the rapid changes under way elsewhere in the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> bloc. In <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> has lost its constitutional guarantee of supremacy, and in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> the party lost its supremacy in elections. The state news agency <ORGANIZATION> BTA </ORGANIZATION> said the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'s parliamentary committee planned Thursday to introduce a motion to abolish two constitutional paragraphs One establishes the party as `` the leading force in society and in -LRB- the -RRB- state,'' and the other says the party `` heads the construction of an advanced socialist society.'' The report did not elaborate. <ORGANIZATION> BTA </ORGANIZATION> offered no details on the ousting of <PERSON> Zhivkov </PERSON>, who was replaced as party leader Nov. 10 and removed from the ruling Politburo shortly afterward. Also expelled were <PERSON> Zhivkov </PERSON>'s son, <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON>, and <PERSON> Milko </PERSON> <PERSON> Balev </PERSON>, a long-time <PERSON> Zhivkov </PERSON> associate, said <ORGANIZATION> BTA </ORGANIZATION> in its one-line dispatch. Since his removal from power the 78-year-old <PERSON> Zhivkov </PERSON>, who led the country for more than 35 years, has come under increasing attacks in the state media for alleged corruption and mismanagement. His son <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON>, said to have enjoyed an opulent lifestyle during his father's tenure, was removed from his job at the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>'s culture department less than two weeks after his father was toppled from his positions as party chief and state president. The Central Committe and Politburo have been purged repeatedly since new party chief <PERSON> Petar </PERSON> <PERSON> Mladenov </PERSON> took power and embarked on a course of reform similar to that under way in other East bloc countries. Also today <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Dyulgerov </PERSON>, the head of the official trade unions, resigned from the ruling Politburo. He was seen as a holdover from the <PERSON> Zhivkov </PERSON> regime. In an effort to appease <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION>'s growing pro-democracy movement, <PERSON> Mladenov </PERSON> has largely revamped the Politburo by bringing in new people more likely to embrace reform. <PERSON> Dyulgerov </PERSON> reportedly said he was resigning as president of the trade unions because they had recently declared their independence from party domination. It was not clear whether he remained on the policy-making Central Committee. Thousands of Bulgarians held a candlelight vigil outside party headquarters Tuesday evening to emphasize their call for political change. Several speakers denounced <PERSON> Zhivkov </PERSON> and accused the old leadership of economic and political blunders. Politburo member <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Lilov </PERSON> repeated earlier calls for the punishment of <PERSON> Zhivkov </PERSON> and his closest associates, and questioned how the system could allow `` dictators'' to rule so long. <PERSON> Zhivkov </PERSON> had been in power since 1954. <PERSON> Mladenov </PERSON> proposed Monday that the party relinquish its consitutional monopoly on power and open dialogue with independent groups. He also proposed that free elections be announced by May 1990. Also Tuesday the head of the <ORGANIZATION> Sofia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Georgi </PERSON> <PERSON> Grigorov </PERSON>, likened the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> to a sinking ship with a crew `` beheaded'' by decades of hard-line rule. He said the party was `` beheaded in terms of personnel.'' `` Who are the young economists, who are the professionals, who are our ideologists?'' <PERSON> Grigorov </PERSON> asked according to the state news agency <ORGANIZATION> BTA </ORGANIZATION>, which carried excerpts from the closed-door session. `` Maybe we have these young people, but all of them were molded in a similar way,'' he said. `` We put all of them on our ship, which is sinking.'' <PERSON> Boiko </PERSON> <PERSON> Dimitrov </PERSON>, who replaced <PERSON> Mladenov </PERSON> as foreign minister last month, suggested that some people in the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> still linked to the <PERSON> Zhivkov </PERSON> government should resign. <PERSON> Evgeni </PERSON> <PERSON> Alexandrov </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> member and party spokesman, told a news conference that it was `` more important that the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> members realize ... that we are living in a different age and elect a <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGA