<HEAD>FAA, NTSB Looking into Rudder Trim Problems Following N.Y. Accident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 More than a dozen reports of problems with rudder controls on <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 737s have been made since a plane skidded off a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> airport runway with such a problem, two federal agencies say. The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday they have asked the <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> to provide data on any reports it has received before or since the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> accident on rudders set in unexpected positions on its 737-300 and 737-400 model jets. The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> will use the information to decide whether to order any action, such as a design change or modification, said <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Duff </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Lopatkiewicz </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, said the agency had received at least a dozen reports, two involving foreign airlines, of instances `` where the crew says it discovered the rudder was trimmed in a way that they did n't expect.'' `` The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> has looked into the incidents to try to determine if the cause was related to human factors or a mechanical problem or a combination of both,'' <PERSON> Duff </PERSON> said. The inquiries are limited to the <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 737-300 and 737-400 models because they have electrically driven controls. Earlier 737-100 and 737-200 models have manual cranks. <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION> investigators found that the rudder was improperly set on a <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION> jet trying to take off from <LOCATION> LaGuardia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> on Sept. 20. The 737-400 veered on the runway and the crew aborted takeoff, but the plane skidded into the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>. The plane broke into three pieces and two passengers were killed and 45 injured. The investigations will look into whether a crew member inadvertently activated the rudder switch and examine the cockpit gauge that indicates how the rudder is set, <PERSON> Duff </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commercial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Planes </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Schleh </PERSON> said the firm is compiling the data for investigators.
