<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Here are excerpts from recent editorials in newspapers throughout the country: Dec. 8 <ORGANIZATION> Argus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Leader </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Sioux </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Falls </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> S.D. </LOCATION>, on the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>: <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> President <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> appears to have survived another coup attempt, the sixth and most serious one she has endured since taking office four years ago. This time, it took <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> intervention to help her through. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> responded properly. But in the long run, intervention may prove to be the catalyst that finally altered relations between the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> would be wise to step up plans to move its two important military bases from the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>: <LOCATION> Subic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> naval base and <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> air base. <LOCATION> Subic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> are the largest <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> bases on foreign soil and are of strategic importance in the <LOCATION> Southeast </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> region. However, the bases are also becoming increasingly unpopular with Filipinos. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>'s recent actions will no doubt make the bases even more unpopular in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>. ... -LRB- A -RRB- t <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>'s request, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> jets flew air cover for loyalist Philippine forces. The move helped prevent insurgents from continuing their own air strikes and taking over <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>'s government <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> fighter planes did not fire on rebel troops. But just the fact the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> warplanes threatened <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> people enraged many Filipinos. President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and Vice President <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> responded quickly _ and properly _ to <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>'s request. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> helped preserve a democratically elected government and, in doing so, also protected <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military interests. But <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> had to have been desperate to make such an extreme request.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 Dec. 11 <ORGANIZATION> Star </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION>, on drug wars: Here's the way <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>'s troubles, on such horrendous display lately, ought to get resolved. An Avianca airliner is blown up at the direction of a cocaine cartel. Drug lords are probably behind the car-bombing that shredded national police headquarters and surrounding buildings in <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION>. President <PERSON> Virgilio </PERSON> <PERSON> Barco </PERSON> pledges to keep fighting the cartels. Colombians, having lived under democracy most of this century, resoundingly support the government. The cartels crumble. Unfortunately, the happy ending is wishful thinking. Violence on a grand scale has visited <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> periodically, as in the 1950s, when hundreds of thousands died; it could return. And the cocaine trade enriches <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>'s economy while prices for coffee, its leading export, have fallen. The lesson is familiar: The best way for the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to help <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> fight its drug war is to cut drug demand at home.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 Dec. 8 <ORGANIZATION> Tampa </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION> -RRB- <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION> on the drug summit: -LRB- The -RRB- bomb blast in downtown <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION> that killed at least 42 peeple and injured more than 1,000 was a terrible tragedy. But even more spine-chilling for Americans was a bomb attack that killed two policemen in <LOCATION> Cartagena </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Cartagena </LOCATION> is the tentative site of a mid-February drug `` summit'' of President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and Latin American presidents. <LOCATION> Cartagena </LOCATION> _ or anywhere else in <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> _ is too risky for the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> President to be, for whatever purpose.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 Dec. 9 The <ORGANIZATION> Seattle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> on auto insurance: A long road through the courts lies ahead, but a ruling ... by the <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> insurance commissioner is an overdue stab at the inequities that permeate the auto insurance rate jungle. Under the ruling ... a <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> driver's address, gender or marital status no longer can be considered by insurance companies when setting rates. ... There is something intrinsically wrong in assumptions that a single or divorced woman is a less responsible driver than a married woman _ and should pay a higher rate. Or that men are worse than women drivers. Or that a zip code alone makes a driver a higher risk. Blanket rating by gender and marital status is as unconscionable as rating by race. ... While outlawing the so-called `` ZIP code rating,'' -LRB- the ruling -RRB- said insurers can consider population density, traffic density, medical costs and litigation rates when establishing auto rates. That makes sense. Insurers argue all those things are factored into ZIP-code ratings, but it does n't always work out that way. Insurance rate-setting is grossly unfair to too many people. The industry argues it works fairly well for most. -LRB- The -RRB- ruling sends a needed message: That's not good enough.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 Dec. 7 The Bulletin, Bend, <LOCATION> Ore. </LOCATION>, on the ATV industry: Consumer safety advocates are feigning surprise and outrage at the results of an undercover survey which found that more than half of all-terrain vehicle dealers violate an agreement that they not pitch adult-size machines as being safe for youngsters under the age of 16. The government was asking for this trouble when it announced an ill-considered consent decree with ATV manufacturers in 1988. The agreement required ATV distributors to use their `` best efforts'' to assure that dealers do not sell adult-size ATVs for use by children. ... The decree was based on the flawed assumption that manufacturers could force ATV salesmen to dissuade adults from buying the machines for youngsters. ... The fact is the much-ballyhooed consent decree signed a year ago is an ineffective way to ensure that young people do not end up on full-size ATVs. If the government truly believes these four-wheeled vehicles are inherently dangerous for young people, then it should make it illegal for those under the age of 16 to drive the machines.
</TEXT>
