<TEXT>
 Dec. 8 The Providence -LRB- <LOCATION> R.I. </LOCATION> -RRB- Journal-Bulletin on the S & amp; L scandal: The savings and loan scandal is so vast and complex that an outraged public feels hard pressed to come up with a central villain. ... <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Danny </PERSON> <PERSON> Wall </PERSON> will serve in that role for -LRB- now -RRB-, but we should bear in mind that the wings are crowded with bad guys. ... His agency -LRB- the Office of Thrift Supervision -RRB- should be put out of its misery. ... As for other key villains, let's start with <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>'s own <PERSON> Fernand </PERSON> <PERSON> St </PERSON> <PERSON> Germain </PERSON>, who as chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> pushed through legislation ... raising bank and <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; L deposit insurance to $ 100,000 per account. That gave <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; L operators a big, riskless treasure chest of capital with which to gamble. Then we have President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s one-time chief of staff, <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Regan </PERSON>; members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> ... as well as the relentless lobbyists of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institutions </ORGANIZATION>. All acted to protect shady operators as deregulation slid into nonregulation.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 Dec. 11 <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrat-Times </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Greenville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Miss. </LOCATION>, on helping people get homes: President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s plan to assist the homeless, low-income families and first-time buyers is, in far too many respects, more of the same from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>: Throwing money at a perceived problem under the assumption that only government has the solution. Nonetheless, his $ 7 billion Home Ownership and Opportunity for People Everywhere -LRB- HOPE -RRB- makes sufficient nods in the direction of self-help and market concepts to make the plan palatable. One of the program's more farsighted elements could enable millions of renters to become homeowners. About $ 1 billion would be made available for tenants to convert and rehabilitate federally subsidized housing into resident-owned cooperatives. ... The best element of the plan would provide vouchers to low-income families to help them escape from public housing projects and find living quarters more suitable to their needs. Encouraging families with initiatives to solve their own housing problems makes infinitely more sense than condemning them to grim federal projects. ... Clearly, HOPE is not meant as a cure-all for the nation's housing problems But on balance it is a positive step in addressing those problems in ways that encourage inividual and collective enterprise.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 Dec. 8 The Phoenix Gazette on AIDS and civil liberties: It's been said that AIDS is the first politically protected disease in history. There is some truth in that statement. Concern for the civil liberties of AIDS victims is appropriate, but it ought not to be the central issue, nor should it stand in the way of warning people at risk. It is difficult to understand how the spread of the disease can be contained when no one, including those who are infected, knows who is carrying the HIV virus. Some officials admit the problem and encourage voluntary testing to control the spread of the disease. Unfortunately, voluntary testing has limited effectiveness. For example, a study at <ORGANIZATION> Bellevue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> revealed that voluntary hospital screening missed more than 85 percent of pregnant women infected with the deadly virus. The fastest growing population of HIV-infected individuals is I.V. drug users in inner-city minority populations. Perhaps it would be more useful to policy-makers if the recommendations were put in order of priority.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 Dec. 12 The Daily Oklahoman, <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, on communism and <PERSON> Fidel </PERSON> <PERSON> Castro </PERSON>: Lest anyone think communism is dying, <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> President <PERSON> Fidel </PERSON> <PERSON> Castro </PERSON> has declared that the demise of Communist rule in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> will mean a shift of global alliances. <PERSON> Castro </PERSON> predicted the Stalinist regimes of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> will join <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> to uphold orthodox communism. That boast may be only a product of <PERSON> Castro </PERSON>'s exaggerated self-importance. But the fact remains that, while the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> is allowing communism's strength to be sapped in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, it continues to subsidize <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> and the Marxist government in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> to the tune of more than $ 6 billion a year.
