<HEAD>UNDATED: a year.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Dec. 8 Las Cruces -LRB- N.M. -RRB- Sun-News on communism: A poll says half of all Americans think communism has failed and is now on its deathbed. We think that possibly they may be half right. Marxism is generally regarded as a failure. But what we perceive as the evils of the communist system could persist under any number of new names. We should never forget that rivalries among nations spring from deeper causes than ideology. The nations of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> have been warring for years over territory and economic advantage. Communism was no more than a radical pipedream when the nations of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> blundered into World War I. National antipathies and rivalries brought that on. And many of the same rivalries and antipathies exist today. It is only human to expect that every favorable development on the international scene means the millennium is being ushered in. But history tells us not to expect it. History tells us that world powers always tend to collide when their interests conflict. We must never lose hope, but we must never expect too much. Complacency, such as that reflected in the poll, could prove to be our worst enemy.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 Dec. 10 The News and <PERSON> Courier </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> S.C. </LOCATION>, on Soviet-Vatican relations: When <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> met with Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> in the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION>, many commentators recalled <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>'s facetious remark to <PERSON> Winston </PERSON> <PERSON> Churchill </PERSON>: `` How many divisions does the pope have?'' Yet the historic encounter between the head of the <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> and the leader of the international communist movement signified more than an acknowledgment by ... <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> that the pope's power can not be measured in military terms. ... <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> can not, even should he wish to, rule through terror, like <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>. It is too late for that. ... He must respond to the beliefs of the people of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. His predecessors were forced to come to an accommodation with the Russian Orthodox Church, based on the latter's subservience. ... <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> has had to come to an agreement with the pope that acknowledges the spiritual power of the <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>. The Soviet leader will also have to come to an accommodation with the other divisions of religion, under the banner of Islam as well as <ORGANIZATION> Christianity </ORGANIZATION>, as the world witnesses, not the death of God, but the agony of communism.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 Dec. 10 <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angeles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> on defense spending: In anticipation of an enormous `` peace dividend'' from improved superpower relations, members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> have already begun laying plans for allocating the tens _ or even hundreds _ of billions of dollars that are expected to be saved on defense. The idea is to shift the windfall to domestic programs, from education to the war on drugs. ... <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, in its eagerness to fatten politically popular domestic programs, may cut too much from defense and leave <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> forces dangerously weakened in a world that still has its dangers, whatever happens in East-West relations. ... To prevent a weakening of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s defenses, both -LRB- President -RRB- <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> need to keep three important points in mind. _ Cut troops before anything else, but maintain enough strength to protect American interests. -LRB- For example, cutting the 2.1 million active-duty personnel by 20 percent _ 420,000 troops _ would save about $ 12.5 billion alone in fiscal 1994 -RRB-. ... _ Do n't be in a rush to weaken <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s strategic capability. ... -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> D </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- espite the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s paring of conventional forces, its massive nuclear arsenal remains largely intact. ... -LRB- T -RRB- he <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> should avoid excessively deep cuts, because nuclear systems tend to be a relatively cheap form of security. _ Do n't cut research and development. The R & amp; D portion of the defense budget _ less than 5 percent _ is arguably the best defense investment the taxpayers can make. Even as <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> agree to slash procurement for this and that weapon system, they must make sure not to jeopardize <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s lead in the technology of warfare.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 Dec. 9 <LOCATION> Watertown </LOCATION> -LRB- <LOCATION> Wis. </LOCATION> -RRB- <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> on medical research: A study published in the ... Journal of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> is being hailed for showing for the first time scientifically that being fit helps women live longer. In addition, the study, on the lives of 10,244 men and 3,120 women, who have been followed for eight to 18 years, was called persuasive confirmation of earlier ones. On review, the figures and conclusions seem unimpressive. Of the 13,444 enrolled for investigation between 1970 and 1981 by epidemiologist <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Blair </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aerobics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>, only 283 have so far died. That's a death rate of 21.2 per 1,000. It is not a large enough figure compiled over a long enough time to demonstrate that those `` least fit,'' regardless of how this is defined, are for men at 240 percent greater risk of dying and for women 360 percent than those `` most fit'' in the long run. Agreed that this is true for the sample tested. Nonetheless, it pushes statistics to the limits to say, as does <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Haskell </PERSON>, `` This is a major study.'' In 20 years it may be but not yet. Dr. <PERSON> Haskell </PERSON>, a cardiologist at the <ORGANIZATION> Stanford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION> and an expert in exercise physiology, acted as a consultant to the <ORGANIZATION> Aerobics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>. Fads exist in medical research as in other fields. We have an impression that this is true of exercise physiology. Exercising and keeping fit are certainly important, but other things in medicine as well as in our culture and society are even more so.
</TEXT>
