 </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Seneca </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> S.C. </LOCATION>, with making false statements on quarterly wage reports. Establishing a practice of hiring illegal aliens carries a maximum fine of $ 3,000 per alien plus six months' imprisonment, <PERSON> Stephens </PERSON> said. The penalty for harboring illegal aliens and for making false statements on quarterly reports is up to five years imprisonment and $ 250,000 in fines per count, he said.
