<HEAD>Earthquake, Berlin Wall Top News Interest</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: For release at 6:30 p.m. EST; time set by source</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The disastrous <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> earthquake and the crumbling of the <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> Wall were the recent news stories that loomed largest for Americans, a poll shows. Nearly three-quarters of people surveyed said they `` followed closely'' the stories about the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> tremor, according to the Times Mirror News Interest Index. The tumult surrounding the opening up of <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> was watched intently by half of those interviewed, the survey found. On the other hand, Americans showed little interest in stories about the resumption of hostilities in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> and state and local election coverage. Only 13 percent said they closely followed those stories. The index was based on a telephone survey of 1,230 adults taken between Nov. 9-12. The estimated margin of error is plus or minus 3 percentage points. Only the explosion of the space shuttle Challenger _ closely watched by 80 percent of those surveyed _ attracted more attention than the earthquake, officials said. The survey has been taken regularly over the last four years. Despite the fact that the quake interrupted the World Series, the survey found weak overall interest in that event, with 23 percent saying they followed the story.
