<BYLINE>By PEGGY FIKAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> appeals court today overturned the murder conviction of a black high school janitor who contended his prosecution in the 1980 rape and slaying of a white teen-ager was racially motivated. The prosecution of 38-year-old <PERSON> Clarence </PERSON> <PERSON> Brandley </PERSON> was marked by `` blatant unfairness,'' the court said in granting the nine-year Death Row inmate a new trial. But the court did not directly address the question of racism. <PERSON> Brandley </PERSON> was convicted of murdering 16-year-old <PERSON> Cheryl </PERSON> <PERSON> Fergeson </PERSON> at a high school. His first trial ended with a hung jury. An all-white jury found him guilty in a second trial. `` I'm trying to hold back the tears,'' <PERSON> Brandley </PERSON>, a former high school janitor, said from prison in <LOCATION> Huntsville </LOCATION> today. `` It's made my Christmas. It's been a long time. It's something I did n't think was coming.'' Defense attorney <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> DeGeurin </PERSON> said he would ask for <PERSON> Brandley </PERSON>'s release on bail while prosecutors decide whether to seek a new trial If the court agrees and <PERSON> Brandley </PERSON> makes bail, `` he'll be out before Christmas,'' <PERSON> DeGeurin </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> Montgomery </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Speers </PERSON> did not immediately return calls for comment on the ruling and on whether he would pursue a third trial. The appeals court, in a 6-3 opinion, said the state's investigative procedures lacked `` the rudiments of fairness. Among examples cited by the court were that another janitor who testified for the state allegedly was threatened by a <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> Ranger, and that the state suppressed information that could have implicated someone else. `` The principles of due process embodied within the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> Constitution, must not, indeed can not, countenance such blatant unfairness,'' wrote Judge <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Berchelmann </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr </PERSON>. In 1987, after a 10-day hearing, retired District Judge <PERSON> Perry </PERSON> <PERSON> Pickett </PERSON> recommended that <PERSON> Brandley </PERSON> get a new trial, ruling that the previous two had been tainted with racism. <PERSON> Brandley </PERSON>'s attorneys have offered evidence that police and prosecutors had set out to prove that <PERSON> Brandley </PERSON>, the only black janitor at the school, was guilty rather than seeking the real killer. During the 1987 hearing, <PERSON> Pickett </PERSON> was told that the district attorney and trial judge met secretly on strategy against <PERSON> Brandley </PERSON>. Prosecutors have denied <PERSON> Brandley </PERSON> was the subject of racial discrimination. `` Thank you, <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON>!'' <PERSON> Brandley </PERSON>'s mother, <PERSON> Minnie </PERSON> <PERSON> Ola </PERSON> <PERSON> Brandley </PERSON>, said when she heard the court's decision. Mrs. <PERSON> Brandley </PERSON>, who lives in <LOCATION> Conroe </LOCATION>, said she is confident a new trial will prove her son's innocence `` I think they have evidence to turn him lose,'' she said. `` My child did n't do that. We're hoping and all we do can is pray.''
