<FIRST>r w AM-Drugs-Workplace     12-13 0572</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drugs-Workplace,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>60 Percent of Workers Surveyed Back Some Form of Testing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sixty percent of American workers favor on-the-job drug testing, according to a Gallup poll released Wednesday by a corporate group that said the results give `` a green light'' to increased employer testing. The survey, done for a newly formed organization of 14 large corporations concerned about employers' rights, said workers tended to support some programs over others. For example, 51 percent of the 1,007 employees polled indicated that companies should have the right to randomly test any employee for drug use. Support rose to 70 percent for testing employees `` suspected of drug usage.'' Twenty-four percent of the workers said they had seen or heard of drug use by co-workers on the job. On the broadest question, 60 percent of the sample said they favored their company adopting some sort of drug-testing policy. Not counted were 9 percent whose employers already have such a program. Support for testing was strongest from workers in rural areas, those 55 and older, and those with an education of high school or less. Fourteen percent of those who did not attend college opposed drug testing at their company, compared to 28 percent for those with a college degree and 48 percent for those who had done post-graduate work. `` Workers' attitudes are far more conservative than we had anticipated,'' <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Bernardo </PERSON>, executive director of the new Institute for a Drug-Free Workplace, said in a statement. `` Employees simply do not want to tolerate working with drug abusers on the job,'' <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Bernardo </PERSON> said. `` More significantly, the survey reaffirms the policy of increasing numbers of employers who are drug testing, and gives a clear and unmistakable green light to further testing of employees and job applicants.'' The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Relations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> said in June that employers can not unilaterally begin testing unionized workers for drug use, but can test job applicants regardless of whether unions object. The board said employee testing falls under collective bargaining and therefore must be the subject of union-management negotiations. There was no immediate comment from the <ORGANIZATION> AFL-CIO </ORGANIZATION> to the survey, which did show employee reservations about drug testing. In one question, only 26 percent of respondents agreed that testing was `` a necessity.'' Forty-two percent said it should be done despite reservations, while 29 percent said it invaded privacy and should be done only under limited circumstances. The workers gave their highest support for drug testing of workers in safety-sensitive jobs. The 14 corporatons in the institute each have some sort of drug-testing program, de <PERSON> Bernardo </PERSON> said. They are <ORGANIZATION> BellSouth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Capital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cities-ABC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> USA </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Midland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Georgia-Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Goodyear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Rubber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Akron </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Hoffman-La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Roche </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Nutley </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>; <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZ