<HEAD>Bush Signs Everglades-Expansion Legislation</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 7 grafs new to include wetlands bill; picks up graf 4 pvs,
The 107,600-acre.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> signed legislation today clearing the way to expand Everglades National Park and ordering the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineers </ORGANIZATION> to restore the natural flow of water to the <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> `` river of grass.'' He also signed a measure providing federal matching funds to help preserve critical wetlands in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. He said the bills will help achieve his campaign goal of `` no net loss of wetlands.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> signed the North American Wetlands Conservation Act in a ceremony in the Roosevelt Room after signing the <LOCATION> Everglades </LOCATION> measure. The wetlands act will provide more than $ 70 million over four years to help purchase and preserve wetlands, which serve as vital feeding areas for ducks and other migratory fowl. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said the dwindling population of ducks `` is largely attributable to the steady loss of wetland areas that we've experienced. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has been losing wetlands at the rate of nearly 400,000 acres a year. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> does not favor a ban on development projects that destroy wetlands, but wants any development offset with an equal amount of acreage restored as wetlands. `` Even in times of serious fiscal constraints, we can still meet our highest environmental priorities and this is one of mine,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said in signing the <LOCATION> Everglades </LOCATION> legislation. The 107,600-acre expansion will be undertaken in cooperation with the state of <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, which will donate 35,000 new acres to the federal park. The government estimates it will cost $ 40 million to acquire the rest of the new acreage, with <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> havin agreed to pay 20 percent of the costs. The Everglades, the second largest national park in the 48 contiguous states, are home to 13 endangered species, but problems with the flow of waters have harmed the habitat for both birds and alligators. `` The woodstork, heron, ibis, egret and roseate spoonbill have all declined dramatically over the years,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. `` The <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> panther, the alligator and many species of fish are declining.'' `` The <LOCATION> Northeast </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Shark </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Slough </LOCATION>, the river of grass through southern <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, has been both too shallow and too deep,'' the president said. `` Through this legislation that river of grass may now be restored to its natural flow of water.'' <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> first enacted legislation in 1944 to create Everglades National Park, and it was dedicated by President <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Truman </PERSON> in 1947. Efforts to drain and reclaim wetlands from the 1880s through the 1930s drastically reduced the natural flow of water through the <LOCATION> Everglades </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Project </ORGANIZATION> in 1948 helped reduce the damaging flow of salt water and provided flood control, but left some areas with too much water and others with too little. The new legislation will require the corps to modify the Central and <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Project </ORGANIZATION> at an estimated cost of $ 45 million. It also puts limits on the use of waterboats in the <LOCATION> Everglades </LOCATION>, with current users allowed to keep using the craft on existing routes.
