<HEAD>Space Shuttle Launch Delayed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to update with details from NASA statement,
date swap with Titan commercial launch, picking up at the 6th graf previous,
`During a 10-day.'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOWARD BENEDICT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Aerospace Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday it had delayed the pre-Christmas launch of space shuttle <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> at least two days because of lagging work at the launch pad. A statement said the new date of Dec. 20 is `` success oriented,'' meaning that any minor new problem could slip the liftoff to the 21st. It said additional time is needed to validate systems on recently renovated launch pad 39A and to prepare <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>. `` We feel confident about readiness for a pre-Christmas liftoff,'' said <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Lenoir </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION>'s associate administrator for space flight. <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Karl </PERSON> <PERSON> Kristofferson </PERSON> said a lot of small problems, many associated with new pad facilities, had put launch crews behind schedule. If liftoff slipped to Christmas Eve or Christmas Day, it probably would be postponed a few more days to free workers for the holiday. With the change, the shuttle swapped launch dates with a Titan 3 commercial rocket that had been scheduled for liftoff on Dec. 20. The Titan, which is to boost British and Japanese communications satellites, was rescheduled for 7:20 p.m. EST Monday. During a 10-day mission, <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION>'s five astronauts are to put a <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> communications satellite into orbit and recover a science satellite before it falls to <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION>. The satellite has been in orbit nearly six years and is expected to re-enter the atmosphere in February. The flight duration will equal the longest shuttle mission to date and will be a stepping stone for even longer flights as <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> is being modified to stay aloft for 16 days and later for 28 days. Loading of propellants for <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION>'s in-flight propulsion systems and auxiliary power units began a day late Monday because a faulty connector on an electronics box had to be replaced. Once the fueling began, the launch pad had to be cleared of all non-essential personnel because it is dangerous. That prevented workers from making up lost time in other areas. Work was running late even before the connector problem because of difficulties working with new systems on a mobile launch platform being used for the first time and with the launch pad, which recently underwent a two-year, $ 50 million refurbishment, receiving 130 modifications. In announcing a Dec. 18 launch date, <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> cautioned last week that the flight might have to be delayed a day or so because of the new systems. Astronaut <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Brandenstein </PERSON> will command <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION>'s crew. The other crew members are pilot <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wetherbee </PERSON> and mission specialists <PERSON> Bonnie </PERSON> <PERSON> Dunbar </PERSON>, <PERSON> Marsha </PERSON> <PERSON> Ivins </PERSON> and <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Low </PERSON>.
