<HEAD>Profile of F.W. de Klerk</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-South Africa, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Even militant anti-apartheid leaders acknowledge that President F.W. <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Klerk </PERSON>, during four months in power, has moved faster toward political reform than any of his predecessors. But leading activists remain deeply suspicious of him, suggesting he wants to ease international pressure on <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> without forfeiting the white minority's ultimate hold on power. <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Klerk </PERSON>, 53, is viewed as an affable pragmatist, earnest but not charismatic. He has pledged to phase out discrimination, and has not shied away from confrontations with right-wing whites who want to maintain strict apartheid. However, he maintains his long-standing belief that <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> African </LOCATION> politics must be conducted along racial lines. <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Klerk </PERSON> was a lawyer before entering <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> in 1973. From 1978, he held a series of Cabinet posts, and in 1982 took on the powerful job of <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leader in the <LOCATION> Transvaal </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s most populous and wealthiest province. P.W. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>, who had headed the government since 1978, suffered a stroke in January and <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Klerk </PERSON> was elected to replace him as overall leader of the party. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> remained in the presidency until August, when he quit after the Cabinet failed to support his objections to a planned diplomatic trip by <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Klerk </PERSON> to <LOCATION> Zambia </LOCATION>. <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Klerk </PERSON> comes from a long line of <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> politicians, going back to his great-grandfather, who was a senator.
