<HEAD>Profile of Nelson Mandela</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-South Africa, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Unheard and unseen by the public since 1962, <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> is nevertheless the most respected leader among South African blacks, who consider him the embodiment of their quest for political freedom. <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON>, 71, has rejected repeated government offers to free him if he would renounce violence. He said the government should renounce violence, end apartheid and unban the <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> was regarded by many blacks as the paramount leader of the <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION>, although the highest office he held before it was banned in 1960 was deputy president-general. He was the first commander of its military wing, `` Spear of the Nation,'' which he helped form in 1961 to engage in a sabotage campaign. He subsequently toured <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, receiving military training and explaining the <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION>'s cause. He was arrested after his return, in 1962, and sentenced to five years' hard labor for leaving the country illegally and inciting blacks to violate the law by striking. In 1963, while <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> was imprisoned near <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Town </LOCATION>, police uncovered the <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION>'s underground headquarters on a farm near <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION> and seized documents outlining plans for the guerrilla campaign. In June 1964, he and seven co-defendants were sentenced to life in prison. <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> contracted tuberculosis at Pollsmoor Prison in <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Town </LOCATION> and was hospitalized in August 1988. After recovering, he was moved to <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Verster </PERSON> prison farm in the wine-growing town of <LOCATION> Paarl </LOCATION>, where he has been allowed to meet with a steady flow of relatives and political colleagues.
