<SECOND>AM-FDA-Acidophilus,260</SECOND>
<HEAD>FDA Warns Against Using Acidophilus Capsules</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> is urging consumers not to use an over-the-counter food supplement distributed by a <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> company because some bottles contain capsules with potentially fatal levels of stannous fluoride. <ORGANIZATION> Vitamin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Specialities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Wyncote </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, has asked its 22 retail stores in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> to recall acidophilus capsules with lot number 069296 and has notified 140 mail-order customers, the <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> said. The product is manufactured by Vita-Pure, the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> said in a release. According to the product label, the acidophilus capsules supply `` friendly bacteria to the intestinal tract'' and help restore and maintain the mucous membrane that lines the stomach and intestines. The company began the recall in late October after two consumers complained of vomiting and flu-like symptoms after using the product, the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> said. However, <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> said it was concerned that many consumers may still be unaware of the problem because only a small number of bottles were returned. An <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> analysis found that smaller capsules were mixed with slightly larger acidophilus capsules. The smaller capsules were found to have an average 784 milligrams of stannous fluoride. Stannous fluoride, used in toothpaste, is safe in small amounts. However, a 784-milligram dose could cause convulsions in an adult and could be lethal for a small child, the agency said. Five capsules could kill an adult. High doses of stannous fluoride can cause gastrointestinal upset and vomiting, which could limit the amount ingested and the adverse effects, the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> said.
