<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> appealed to the world's wealthiest countries Wednesday to make good on their promises of aid to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> so the new leaders in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> can `` put food on the table and goods on the shelves of stores.'' <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> described the plight of <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> as winter approaches as severe. `` Pledges alone are n't enough,'' he told a meeting of two dozen foreign ministers as they committed their treasuries to a coordinated assistance program valued at up to $ 6 billion in the next several years. Most of the aid takes the form of investment and trade credits not to be paid out immediately. Included in the assistance is a $ 200 million <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> contribution to a $ 1 billion stablization fund for <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>. Additionally, <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> announced the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> would provide $ 200 million to a 10-nation $ 500 million `` bridge loan'' for <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> that is to help tide the country past the Christmas season until the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> declares it qualifies for a comprehensive aid program. Except for the $ 200 million, which comes out of a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> fund, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> last month appropriated $ 938 million in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> assistance. <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>, a former <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> secretary, has taken the lead within the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration in encouraging Eastern European countries to adopt market economies. As a lure, he dangles <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid. Just before coming to <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> went to <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> for talks with reformist Prime Minister <PERSON> Hans </PERSON> <PERSON> Modrow </PERSON>. He promised the administration would consider economic support if the country continued to revise its economy and carried out a pledge to hold multiparty elections in May. <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> told the foreign ministers that `` the multiplying effects of people power are creating a new East-West equation. Ordinary men and women are peacefully asserting their basic human rights on a scale unimagined at the start of the year.'' But, <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> went on, `` It is our task to support this courageous reform effort. After the streets emplty of demonstrators, after the people select new leaders, after governments become the servants of the people, after all this _ the economies must put food on the table and goods on the shelves of stores.''
