<HEAD>Tamil Tigers Oust Rival Militia, 60 Killed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATTICALOA, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A powerful rebel group negotiating with the government for political power ousted a rival militia Wednesday in a battle that killed an estimated 60 people, mostly militiamen, residents said. In a three-pronged attack launched shortly before midnight Tuesday, the <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tigers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tamil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Eelam </ORGANIZATION> surrounded the town of <LOCATION> Batticaloa </LOCATION>, residents said. One young woman, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the rebels came down the coast road from the lagoon and the jungle late Tuesday night. By midmorning Wednesday, she said, the shooting had stopped. By sundown Wednesday, <LOCATION> Batticaloa </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> had received 26 bodies. `` Only one was a Tiger,'' a hospital official said. `` The rest were from the other side.'' Like many other people in this town of 60,000 people, he was reluctant to speak the name of the `` other side.'' But they acknowledged they meant the <ORGANIZATION> Tamil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>, a group set up shortly before the Indian peacekeeping forces withdrew from <LOCATION> Batticaloa </LOCATION> late last month. `` Most of them, according to parents, were forcibly conscripted to fight the <ORGANIZATION> Tigers </ORGANIZATION>,'' one hospital employee said. The Sri Lankan government has accused departing Indian troops, at the behest of pro-Indian Tamil groups, of training and arming the Tamil army, which the <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION> government has outlawed. The Indian government, which sent peacekeeping soldiers to <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION> two years ago to put down the Tamil rebellion, has denied allegations it created the <ORGANIZATION> Tamil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>. In addition to the 26 bodies at <ORGANIZATION> Batticaloa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION>, three more were seen along the road leading into town. Young Tiger guerrillas, most in their teens and carrying shining new AK-47 assault rifles, claimed at least 50 members of the <ORGANIZATION> Tamil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> were killed in the battle. Well-placed residents in <LOCATION> Batticaloa </LOCATION> estimate the total death toll at 50 to 60. One said it might be as high as 90. `` The bodies have been pouring in all day and still they are arriving,'' the hospital official said. `` More will come when it is light again and people can find transport.'' The last of the bodies to reach the hospital as darkness fell lay on the floors of vans parked inside the hospital's front gate. At least three had their hands tied behind their backs. In the fading light, their wounds were not clearly visible but all appeared to have been shot in the head or neck. `` My husband. I have lost my husband,'' wailed <PERSON> Nathivathany </PERSON>, in between sobs that shook her entire body. <PERSON> Nathivathany </PERSON>'s husband, Thayaparan, was one of the young men whose bodies lay in a heap in the back of the van. Friends said the young couple had been married only a short time. But elsewhere in the town, there was an air of calm, with teen-age <ORGANIZATION> Tigers </ORGANIZATION> standing along the streets in twos and fours. Red-and-white banners erected by the <ORGANIZATION> Tigers </ORGANIZATION> proclaimed `` great heroes days'' in the Tamil language. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Tigers </ORGANIZATION> were very polite when they came into town after the shooting,'' said an English-speaking woman. `` People gave them tea and said we had dreams for the liberation of <LOCATION> Batticaloa </LOCATION>. `` Eighteen months ago people of <LOCATION> Batticaloa </LOCATION> compained about our Tamil militia _ including the <ORGANIZATION> Tigers </ORGANIZATION> _ saying they had been forced to contribute money, provide free food and even their own television sets,'' said the woman, also speaking on condition of anonymity. But as the <ORGANIZATION> Tigers </ORGANIZATION> tried to enter the political mainstream, they also had embarked on a public relations campaign, one that seems to be working. The <ORGANIZATION> Tamil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> does not enjoy the same support. <LOCATION> Batticaola </LOCATION> is 135 miles east of <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION> and is one of the two eastern districts where <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> pulled out 10,000 of its troops in the past two months. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> has said the remaining 26,000 troops will be out of <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION> by Dec. 31.
