<HEAD>Sirens Mark Martial Law Anniversary; Youths Demonstrate</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with demonstrations. Picks up 6th
graf ``In his ...''</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Congress, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sirens wailed across <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> at noon Wednesday to mark the eighth anniversary of the 1981 martial-law crackdown, which <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> declared should be a reminder of the need for `` pluralism and tolerance.'' Hundreds of young people took to the streets in five cities, however, hurling rocks and firebombs to express anger at the crackdown and demand punishment for those responsible. In the most open discussion to date of the decision, newspapers were filled with articles examining Gen. <PERSON> Wojciech </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON>'s Dec. 13, 1981, declaration to suppress the Solidarity labor movement. `` Before December 1981 Solidarity did not appreciate the strength of the authorities,'' <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> Solidarity </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Gazeta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wyborcza </ORGANIZATION> newspaper. `` After December 1981, the authorities did not appreciate the strength of Solidarity.'' In the crackdown, carried out with military precision, communication to the outside world was cut, thousands of Solidarity activists were rounded up and interned, the union was ordered suspended and at least nine miners died resisting authorities. Eight years after the event, Solidarity has not only regained legal status but it has taken control of the government from the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. However, activists allowed <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON> to be elected president in July with the minimum number of votes required. While older Solidarity activists approached the anniversary somberly, hundreds of demonstrators in <LOCATION> Katowice </LOCATION> hurled firebombs and paint at the doors of the provincial party headquarters, state radio reported. In <LOCATION> Szczecin </LOCATION>, several hundred teen-agers rallied and marched to police headquarters where they burned <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON> in effigy, chanted `` Down with Communism,'' and threw stones and bottles at the building before police turned water cannons on them, radio said. A group of demonstrators attacked police headquarters with stones in <LOCATION> Wroclaw </LOCATION> and officers responded with truncheons, the state <ORGANIZATION> PAP </ORGANIZATION> news agency reported. Smaller anti-communist marches also took place outside the national <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> headquarters in <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> and, according to state television, in <LOCATION> Krakow </LOCATION>. In his message to mark the anniversary, <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> muted his criticism while stressing that there should be efforts at reconciliation. Whether Polish national interests required the implementation of martial law is a question `` that belongs to historians,'' <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> said. `` However one does not need scientific analysis to see the senselessness of the human losses and persecutions, the campaign of slanders and humiliations, the cult of force and the pacifying of public life. `` Today the tragedy of martial law reminds us of the need for cultured politics, pluralism and tolerance. The dramatic experiences of those days can not be repeated, because _ among other things _ we are wiser from those experiences. `` The tragedy of martial law can not overshadow the future, and the squaring of accounts can not replace the striving for a just and prosperous <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> said. Government spokeswoman <PERSON> Malgorzata </PERSON> <PERSON> Niezabitowska </PERSON> said the date has deep meaning for her, especially sitting in a government where `` literally, those who eight years ago were arrested and those who gave and signed the orders sit side by side.'' The fact the two sides could overcome their differences proves that `` those eight years, which were very hard and brought a lot of misfortunes, were not wasted. They became a lesson for both sides. The Communist side became convinced that without the participation of society it is not possible to govern. The opposition was shown that relentlessness in striving for freedom has got to be combined with political realism.'' Government spokeswoman <PERSON> Malgorzata </PERSON> <PERSON> Niezabitowska </PERSON> said the date has deep meaning for her, especially sitting in a government where `` literally, those who eight years ago were arrested and those who gave and signed the orders sit side by side.'' The fact the two sides could overcome their differences proves that `` those eight years, which were very hard and brought a lot of misfortunes, were not wasted. They became a lesson for both sides. The Communist side became convinced that without the participation of society it is not possible to govern. The opposition was shown that relentlessness in striving for freedom has got to be combined with political realism.'' Solidarity had called on factories nationwide to sound sirens at noon in memory of the day still vividly and painfully remembered. Among those interviewed by the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> weekly Polityka were Col. <PERSON> Wieslaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Gornicki </PERSON>, <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON>'s close aide, who said at the time he believed martial law was inevitable, although today he is unsure whether moderates on both sides could have prevented it. <PERSON> Gornicki </PERSON> said the public should remember Soviet pressure on <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, and Soviet leader <PERSON> Leonid </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brezhnev </PERSON>'s `` threats, about which the public still knows too little.'' At a March 1982 meeting with <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON>, <PERSON> Brezhnev </PERSON> `` sneered'' that martial law was a `` lamentable half measure'' and authorities should be even tougher, <PERSON> Gornicki </PERSON> said. Interior Minister <PERSON> Czeslaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Kiszczak </PERSON>, whose police and riot troops carried out the crackdown, told the newspaper he regrets the `` injustice and harm'' that people feel, but that as a historical experience martial law `` turned out to be educative and valuable.'' `` From this experience stems the success of dialogue and today's essentially changing <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>,'' he said. In a commentary, <ORGANIZATION> Gazeta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wyborcza </ORGANIZATION> said it is possible to discuss martial law `` in a calmer way.'' Justified non-violent resistance to martial law and loyalty to Solidarity through the difficult years finally allowed `` a historic breakthrough,'' it said. `` Though the price we have had to pay is great, all those years were not a lost time.''
