</ORGANIZATION> at the request of the leaders of the seven most industrialized nations, who met in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> in July well before the reform movements in other East European nations began to take root. To date, officials said, aid totaling up to $ 6 billion over several years has been granted or committed to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>. It ranges from emergency food to long-term export and investment credits. On Wednesday, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and nine other countries formally underwrote a stabilization fund of $ 1 billion to prop up the zloty, the Polish currency, and help make it convertible. <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> will pay $ 250 million to the fund, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> $ 200 million and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> $ 150 million. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> will each contribute $ 100 million and the remainder will come from <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> called the fund `` critical for the success of the currency and price reforms'' in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>. `` The fund is also taking on symbolic importance for the Poles, an indicator of whether the West will in fact stand with them when they make hard economic decisions,'' he added. He said in addition to paying into the stabilization fund, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is granting <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> another $ 800 million in a range of programs including investment credits, food and medical aid and trade guarantees. <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>