<HEAD>Former Comany Chairman Denies Bribery Charges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TETSUO JIMBO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The former chairman of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s largest company told a court Wednesday he was engaging in a normal Japanese business deal, not being bribed, when he accepted discount-priced stocks from a firm accused of buying favors. The trial of <PERSON> Hisashi </PERSON> <PERSON> Shinto </PERSON>, 79, former chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Nippon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telegraph </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telephone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which began Wednesday in <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, is the fourth of five scheduled trials in the Recruit bribery scandal. Defendants in the fifth trial, to begin Friday, are <PERSON> Hiromasa </PERSON> <PERSON> Ezoe </PERSON>, founder and former chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Recruit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> information services conglomerate, and two politicians accused of accepting bribes. A total of 12 defendants are charged with bribery and could face five years in prison each if convicted. <PERSON> Ezoe </PERSON>'s company allegedly tried to win favors and influence in the top ranks of politics, business and the bureaucracy. The Recruit scandal and trials have raised many questions about political gift-giving, business practices and the close ties between government and business in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> gave final approval Wednesday to legislation providing punishment for politicians who make donations at weddings, funerals and other events in their election districts without attending the event. Politicials have said constituents expect such donations. Under the new law, which takes effect Feb. 1, violators can be sentenced to a year in prison or fined up to 200,000 yen -LRB- $ 1,390 -RRB-. Shinto, who testified before Judge <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Toyoda </PERSON> in the no-jury trial, accepted the prosecution's factual allegations that he made about 21 million yen -LRB- $ 145,000 -RRB- in 1986 by buying shares in a Recruit subsidiary at a below-market price before they were offered to the public. `` I accepted the offer of shares, but I never regarded it as a bribe,'' Shinto said. He added that, during his business career, other companies had offered him similar shares as a sign of trust and longterm ties. `` Rejecting such an offer is considered rude in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>,'' he said. Shinto denied doing special favors for Recruit. The prosecution alleged that Recruit got favorable terms on telephone lines, maintenance and other services. `` The telecommunications market has become a free market and <ORGANIZATION> NTT </ORGANIZATION> is a private company,'' Shinto said. `` I ordered all my employees to increase our services to our clients, and I believe they did just that.'' Prosecutors also say Shinto helped Recruit obtain two U.S.-made supercomputers and gave it special assistance. Recruit bought the supercomputers from Shinto's company in 1987 and 1988 after <ORGANIZATION> NTT </ORGANIZATION> bought them from <ORGANIZATION> Cray </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` We were never asked by Recruit to buy supercomputers from <ORGANIZATION> Cray </ORGANIZATION>, but rather it was done by <ORGANIZATION> NTT </ORGANIZATION> independently to correct the trade imbalance between <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, and <ORGANIZATION> NTT </ORGANIZATION> asked Recruit to buy them from us,'' Shinto said. Japanese business circles were stunned by Shinto's arrest in March. He had a reputation for clean dealings and had seen his giant company through the change in 1985 from government to private ownership. He resigned last December, immediately after his involvement in the stock deal was disclosed. The Recruit scandal began in the summer of 1988 and caused the downfall of Prime Minister <PERSON> Noboru </PERSON> <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON>, who resigned last spring after acknowledging he received large donations from Recruit. Other key figures in the governing <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> also have been sidelined by the scandal and the honesty of ranking bureaucrats also has been questioned because of gifts they accepted from Recruit.
