<HEAD>From Cheerleader to Activist for Salvadoran Poor</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos NY25,HF2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER VILES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>THOMASTON, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Jennifer </PERSON> <PERSON> Casolo </PERSON>'s friends and parents expressed gratitude and relief Wednesday at the news that the church worker was being released from the Salvadoran prison where she'd been held on terrorism charges. `` I am deeply, greatly grateful to each and every one who has believed in <PERSON> Jennifer </PERSON> and her innocence,'' her mother, <PERSON> Audrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Casolo </PERSON>, told a news conference in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Sen. <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Dodd </PERSON>'s Whethersfield office just south of <LOCATION> Hartford </LOCATION> <PERSON> Casolo </PERSON>, 28, was arrested Nov. 26 after a raid on her house in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>, and was accused of storing weapons for leftist rebels. Police said they found thousands of rounds of Soviet-made ammunition and other armaments in the garden behind her home. Salvadoran President <PERSON> Alfredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Christiani </PERSON> announced Wednesday that <PERSON> Casolo </PERSON>, 28, had been released because of insufficient evidence and would be deported. Shortly afterwards, reporters saw the <LOCATION> Thomaston </LOCATION> native leave <LOCATION> Ilopango </LOCATION> prison with <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Ambassador <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Walker </PERSON>. `` You do n't know whether to laugh because you're happy or cry because you're happy,'' said <PERSON> Susanna </PERSON> <PERSON> Wallace </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Seminar </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Antonio </LOCATION>, the lay church group that sent <PERSON> Casolo </PERSON> to the Central American country in 1985. `` We hope this helps stop the persecution of church workers that's going on in <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Wallace </PERSON> said, weeping as she spoke. `` This confirms our standing all along of her innocence.'' In <LOCATION> Whethersfield </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Casolo </PERSON>'s father, <PERSON> John </PERSON>, thanked volunteers and officials `` for bringing our daughter home.'' In <LOCATION> Thomaston </LOCATION>, a western <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION> town of 7,000 people, the initial shock and disbelief over Casolo's arrest 2 -LCB- weeks ago was replaced by an effort to win her freedom. A hastily arranged prayer vigil drew 250 people and raised $ 1,000, teachers started a legal defense fund and other organized a letter - and Christmas card-writing drive Word of <PERSON> Casolo </PERSON>'s release spread quickly at <LOCATION> Thomaston </LOCATION> High School, where <PERSON> Casolo </PERSON> was student body president 10 years ago. `` All the faculty here are extremely elated that she'll be coming back home to us,'' said teacher <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON>. `` Word got around very very quickly, from room to room to room.'' A decade ago, <PERSON> Casolo </PERSON> was a cheerful, popular high school senior more interested in cheering on the basketball team than changing the world. <PERSON> Casolo </PERSON>, who came from a working class-family, finished at the top of her class, and honors came easily to her. In addition to being chosen student body president, she was the yearbook editor and was voted most ambitious, most creative and `` did the most for <ORGANIZATION> Thomaston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>.'' `` She was the hit of the school,'' <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilkinson </PERSON>, now a vice principal at the school, said Tuesday. `` She was very intelligent, inquisitive, a bundle of energy. If anything needed to be started for school spirit or something, she would always do it.'' Friends described her as a compassionate, caring teen-ager, but said there was little sign of the spirituality Casolo would find working among El Salvador's poor. Her parents divorced while she was a student. Her mother supported the family by working as a bookkeeper at a vocational high school in <LOCATION> Waterbury </LOCATION>. Friends say <PERSON> Casolo </PERSON> became more religious and more interested in social work while at <ORGANIZATION> Brandeis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, a prestigious liberal arts college in <LOCATION> Waltham </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass </LOCATION>. She took a double major in American studies and Latin American studies, was captain of the soccer team and graduated summa cum laude. Friends say <PERSON> Casolo </PERSON> experienced anxiety about choosing a career, torn between an attraction to social work and a feeling of obligation to find a well-paying job to help her mother. Social work won out. After working with Salvadoran refugees in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>, Casolo, who is fluent in Spanish, left for <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>. She worked for <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Seminars </ORGANIZATION>, which organizes visits for prominent Americans to <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>. `` I think that she was something she felt called to do rather than simply take a job and make a lot of money,'' said <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Abbott </PERSON>, a close friend from high school. The work put her in close contact with a wide range of Salvadorans, from President <PERSON> Christiani </PERSON> and military leaders to church leaders and opposition party politicians. Casolo quickly formed a spiritual attachment to the country and its people, particularly the poor. In a letter to a friend, she spoke of joining the <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> to become a nun. In another letter, she wrote, `` I'm a pastor without religion. Only with lots of love.'' Even after her arrest, <PERSON> Casolo </PERSON> remained upbeat, shouting her claims of innocence to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> reporters at her arraignment and describing her imprisonment as a `` life-changing experience.'' `` I ca n't say I have faith in the system to find me innocent,'' she said. `` But I believe my innocence will shine through.''
