<HEAD>New Brief Asks Wider Ethics Probe of D'Amato</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Green </PERSON>, whose complaint led to the congressional investigation of Sen. <PERSON> Alfonse </PERSON> <PERSON> D'Amato </PERSON>, asked the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ethics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Wednesday to widen its probe to include a <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> grant and <PERSON> D'Amato </PERSON> phone calls to a federal prosecutor. <PERSON> Green </PERSON>, a Democrat who lost the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> race to <PERSON> D'Amato </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.Y. </LOCATION>, in 1986, also said potential witnesses in the investigation should be subpoenaed to testify under oath. `` There are a lot of people with information who will be scared to speak out against <PERSON> D'Amato </PERSON>, given his reputation for ruthlessness, unless the committee puts them under oath, which in a sense protects them,'' <PERSON> Green </PERSON> said in an interview. He also said <PERSON> D'Amato </PERSON> should be put under oath. <PERSON> D'Amato </PERSON> said later he would testify before the committee `` in any way in which they request. And I'm delighted to make myself available and to cooperate with them in every way and any way.'' At a <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> news conference on another issue, <PERSON> D'Amato </PERSON> said he was unaware of <PERSON> Green </PERSON>'s latest move, `` but it would n't surprise whatever it is, and I'm delighted that we'll have an opportunity to have all of Mr. <PERSON> Green </PERSON>'s charges reviewed by the <ORGANIZATION> Ethics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>.'' He said he was confident he would be exonerated. <PERSON> Green </PERSON>, who currently runs the Democracy Project, a liberal research organization in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, said he filed the additional papers because the committee's special counsel, <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Schuelke </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, asked him for `` any new information, insights.'' The phone calls <PERSON> Green </PERSON> referred to were made by <PERSON> D'Amato </PERSON> to then-U.S. Attorney <PERSON> Rudolph </PERSON> <PERSON> Giuliani </PERSON> in 1984 and 1985. On one occasion, <PERSON> D'Amato </PERSON> passed along a plea from the Rev. <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Gigante </PERSON> for a reduction in the sentence of his brother, <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Gigante </PERSON>, a convicted loan shark who also has been reported to be an officer in the Genovese crime family. <PERSON> D'Amato </PERSON> has said he was merely trying to help the priest, a constituent. In the other call, made at the behest of the late criminal lawyer <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> Cohn </PERSON>, <PERSON> D'Amato </PERSON> urged <PERSON> Giuliani </PERSON> to review murder charges against an unnamed defendant. <PERSON> Giuliani </PERSON> has said he later concluded <PERSON> D'Amato </PERSON> was referring to <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Castellano </PERSON>, then boss of the Gambino crime family. <PERSON> D'Amato </PERSON> has said he was unaware of the identity of the defendant in the latter case and that he was trying to save <PERSON> Giuliani </PERSON>'s office from being embarrassed if the charges did n't stick. The <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> grant was $ 500,000 from a discretionary fund controlled by then-Secretary <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON>. The money was awarded to a coalition of black ministers, including the Rev. <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Sharpton </PERSON>, whose <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Youth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION> was to use the money to rehabilitate a building into a drug treatment center. The grant came one month after the group endorsed <PERSON> D'Amato </PERSON> for re-election in 1986. <PERSON> Sharpton </PERSON>, who is under indictment accused of ste