<HEAD>Aviation, Space Industries Short On Skilled Workers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Peace-Aerospace Impact</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Companies that build planes, spacecraft and related equipment have too few skilled workers, as <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> schools lag behind in science and math, an industry study concluded Wednesday. A survey of companies belonging to the <ORGANIZATION> Aerospace </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> showed 67 percent of the companies suffer from a shortage of scientists and engineers and 55 percent report a shortage of production workers. More than 80 percent said they expect more shortages in the future. The problem is made more serious by rapid changes in the technology needed in aerospace industries, by a lack of young people preparing for jobs with a technological focus, by the failure of women and minorities to choose such careers and by the fact that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> students generally are doing poorly in science and math, said the <ORGANIZATION> AIA </ORGANIZATION> study. The survey was compiled from responses of 30 major corporations, including nine of the top 10 <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> contractors and eight of the top 10 <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> contractors. Key shortages are occurring in jobs that involve computers, advanced materials, electro-optics and artificial intelligence, the study said. Among concerns raised by aerospace companies are that employees have insufficient hands-on experience, that schools put too much emphasis on theoretical models, that there is a lack of emphasis on design projects in college, and that people with advanced degrees are academically oriented and have to adjust to the faster pace of industry. Some companies also complained of deficiences in verbal and team-building skills among high-level professionals. Aerospace companies are responding to the problem by giving almost 40 percent of their total corporate contributions to education up to the high school level, with large amounts going to colleges and universities for research and development projects, the report said. A November report by the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Colleges </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Universities </ORGANIZATION> concluded that the nation faces a crisis in science education, with schools producing an inadequate number of science and engineering graduates.
