<HEAD>Carter to Investigate Nicaraguan Political Campaign Riot</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Former President <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> said Wednesday he will investigate a political campaign battle between government opponents and supporters this week that left one person dead and more than 20 injured. `` We hope to determine the causes of this violence,'' he told reporters. <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> arrived at the head of a delegation of observers, invited by both the leftist Sandinista government and the opposition, to monitor the process leading to national elections Feb. 25. It was his second trip here this year. Sandinistas and leaders of the National Opposition Union accused each other of inciting the Dec. 10 riot in <LOCATION> Masatepe </LOCATION>, 30 miles south of <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION>, in which a Sandinista campaign office and a private home were looted and two vehicles were burned. It was the worst outbreak of violence in the 2-month-old election campaign for president, vice president, a new legislature and municipal authorities nationwide. The Center for Democracy, a Washington-based observer group, blamed the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION>. A report by the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> States </ORGANIZATION> said the riot was deliberately provoked but that its observers could not determine who was responsible. <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> said he is pleased that so far all sides are intent on having free and fair elections. Accompanying <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> was his wife <PERSON> Rosalynn </PERSON>; former Sen. <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Evans </PERSON>, R-Wash.; and former President <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Oduber </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION> For the next three days they will travel throughout <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, talking to <ORGANIZATION> OAS </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> observer groups about the electoral process. <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> said he would like to see the money approved by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> for <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s Contra rebels channeled through a commission set up to oversee their demobilization. He stopped short of calling for demobilization of the Contras before the elections, saying, `` My hope is there will be no need for a Contra presence after the elections.'' <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> was commenting on this week's summit by five <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> presidents that called for disbanding the Contras and leftist Salvadoran guerrillas. The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration and Contra leaders want the Contras to remain in place as a fighting force until after the elections to make sure President <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> keeps his promise the electoral process will be open and fair. The five presidents agreed Aug. 7 in <LOCATION> Tela </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>, to call for demobilization of the Contras by Dec. 5 in exchange for <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON>'s promise of electoral fairness But Contra leaders ignored the deadline and Central American leaders passed it by after violence re-escalated in <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvavador </LOCATION> 10-year-old civil war.
