<HEAD>Mass Grave of Children Discovered in Northern Israel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Officials on Wednesday announced the discovery of a mass grave with the remains of 135 children of North African Jewish immigrants who died in a 1957 epidemic, <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> television reported. The report came after a day of prayers and accusations by other Jews from <LOCATION> Yemen </LOCATION> on the <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabian </LOCATION> peninsula. They feared the grave could hold the bones of about 600 children from their community that were reported missing in the 1950s shortly after their arrival in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. The discovery of the mass grave reopened one of the most mysterious chapters in the history of immigration to the Jewish state. There has never been an authoritative explanation of the disappearance of the Yemenite children. One theory is that they were taken to collective farms and lost contact with their parents. Another is they were dispersed to other immigrant camps. However, news reports said the remains in the mass grave were instead those of North African children who died during the epidemic. The unmarked mass grave was discovered last week in a cemetery in <LOCATION> Kfar </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Yona </LOCATION>, a village 20 miles north of <LOCATION> Tel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aviv </LOCATION>, when gravediggers tried to dig in an unused portion of the cemetery. The find was leaked to the press by a gravedigger who said he feared the children's remains might not be treated properly, <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> TV reported. Dozens of Yemenite families flocked to the gravesite Wednesday shortly after its discovery was announced on <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> radio. Almost 47,000 Yemenites, nearly the entire Jewish community, were brought to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> as part of `` Operation Magic Carpet.'' That program ended in 1950. <PERSON> Yisrael </PERSON> <PERSON> Kessar </PERSON>, a legislator from the left-of-center <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and a Yemenite immigrant, called on Prime Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> to order an investigation into the discovery after it was announced. However, police investigators said the remains were of children of <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> African </LOCATION> immigrants who died in a nearby hospital and were hastily buried in a mass grave without a marker for `` economic reasons,'' <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> radio reported. Most of the North Africans were from <LOCATION> Morocco </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tunisia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION>. There was no report of what sickness killed them, but various epidemics swept through Israeli camps in those years, including cholera and tuberculosis. The mass grave is next to the sites of two such camps. <PERSON> Nissim </PERSON> <PERSON> Atiya </PERSON>, a gravedigger who buried the victims in 1957, said the children's families were notified of their deaths, and `` it was all done officially.''
