<FIRST>r e BC-APArts:FilmReview     12-13 0848</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-AP Arts: Film Review,0864</SECOND>
<HEAD>At the Movies: ``Glory''</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ``Glory'' opens Dec. 14</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOLORES BARCLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Arts Editor</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 On July 18, 1863, despite fatigue and poor rations, the 54th <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Colored Volunteer Infantry marched across a half-mile of sand on a <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> beach to lead the ill-planned attack on <PERSON> Fort </PERSON> <PERSON> Wagner </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION> harbor. The regiment lost more than 40 percent of its men. The story of the 54th, the first black regiment from the North to fight in the Civil War, and its youthful white colonel, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gould </PERSON> <PERSON> Shaw </PERSON>, unfolds in `` Glory,'' <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Zwick </PERSON>'s masterful movie for Tri-Star Pictures. <PERSON> Zwick </PERSON> presents a powerful, moving tapestry of war's senselessness The screenplay by <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> Jarre </PERSON> is partly based on the books `` Lay This Laurel'' and `` One Gallant Rush,'' and letters <PERSON> Shaw </PERSON> wrote home to his parents. The movie _ narrated by <PERSON> Matthew </PERSON> <PERSON> Broderick </PERSON> as <PERSON> Shaw </PERSON> _ is largely seen through his eyes. Young and privileged, but disillusioned and battle-scarred after the gory and indecisive Battle of <LOCATION> Antietam </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Shaw </PERSON> returns to his wealthy, powerful and abolitionist parents in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> just in time for a lavish party and an offer from the governor to take command of an all-black fighting regiment. He rises in rank from captain to colonel and musters his men, who include his childhood friends <PERSON> Cabot </PERSON> -LRB- <PERSON> Cary </PERSON> <PERSON> Elwes </PERSON> -RRB-, who is white and becomes a major, and <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> -LRB- <PERSON> Andre </PERSON> <PERSON> Braugher </PERSON> -RRB-, a second-generation free black who volunteers as an enlisted man. Much of `` Glory'' focuses on the basic training of a ragtag group of runaway slaves and free men, who are denied all the basic supplies given to white soldiers, including proper shoes and the coveted blue uniform, and are asked to accept less pay. They have much to learn about soldiering and about human relations, in a fight for freedom and the restoration of the union. As Trip, an embittered runaway, <PERSON> Denzel </PERSON> <PERSON> Washington </PERSON> -LRB- `` Cry Freedom,'' `` The Mighty Quinn,'' `` Power'' -RRB- does a star turn. His hatred, desires, feelings are worn on his face, such as when he's flogged for supposedly trying to desert Not one word is uttered; he merely locks eyes with <PERSON> Broderick </PERSON> -LRB- `` <LOCATION> Biloxi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Blues </LOCATION>,'' `` War Games'' -RRB- and allows a single tear to fall. <PERSON> Broderick </PERSON>, meanwhile, shows clear repulsion and sorrow. Why? Because the whip _ a symbol of the servitude from which the men had fled _ had been used on Trip in the past: His back is a jungle of ugly scars. `` Glory'' becomes Trip's story _ as well as <ORGANIZATION> Shaw </ORGANIZATION>'s _ as the runaway undergoes a radical self-realization. In the end, the 54th becomes the only family he's ever known. <PERSON> Zwick </PERSON>, the Emmy-award winning director of `` Special Bulletin'' and `` thirtysomething,'' stresses visual acting in `` Glory.'' Action speaks louder than words, and he focuses on facial expressions and body movements rather than histrionics, gimmicks or slick words. He also is spare with dialogue. When the 54th marches past the white regiments _ who regarded the blacks as a joke and less than men _ to lead the assault against <PERSON> Fort </PERSON> <PERSON> Wagner </PERSON>, only four words are spoken by the once hostile whites: `` Give'em hell, 54.'' Ultimately, color no longer is the issue. The men are fellow soldiers about to die. And like `` Gallipoli'' and `` Hamburger Hill,'' the overriding issue becomes the utter futility of war. The battle scene at <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Wagner </LOCATION> is beautifully choreographed, the men running along the beach, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> flag full and billowing. It is poetic and yet powerful. `` Glory'' makes good use of battle scenes. They are exciting, frightening and realistic. At <LOCATION> James </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, the 54th gets its first taste of fighting. After firing a few rounds and watching a Confederate unit retreat, more Confederates appear through the mist like gray ghosts and the battle soon becomes hand-to-hand combat. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Lerner </PERSON> was second unit director, and <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Minor </PERSON> coordinated the stunts. `` Glory'' is bound to be a contender at Oscar time. It also has a haunting but overused score by <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Horner </PERSON>, with choral work by the Boys Choir of <LOCATION> Harlem </LOCATION>. The music is lovely but unfortunately the filmmakers use the same refrain so often that just about every scene becomes a climax. There are good performances by <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON> <PERSON> Freeman </PERSON> -LRB- `` Street Smart,'' `` Driving Miss Daisy'' -RRB-, <PERSON> Jihmi </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> as a stuttering enlisted man and <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Finn </PERSON> as the fierce no-nonsense Irish sergeant-major who whips the 54th into shape. <PERSON> Braugher </PERSON>, whose theater credits include `` Much Ado About Nothing'' and `` King <PERSON> John </PERSON>'' at the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> Shakespeare Festival, makes his film debut in `` Glory,'' and is someone to watch. <PERSON> Jane </PERSON> <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> appears as <PERSON> Shaw </PERSON>'s mother. The Freddie Fields production has a running time of 122 minutes and is rated R.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
