<HEAD>Schoolchildren, Residents Champion Embattled Beavers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE LOCKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HATFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Town officials, fearing that beaver dams would flood recently repaired <LOCATION> Linseed </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Road </LOCATION>, decided to rub out the rodents but found themselves having to take on schoolchildren and The Beaver's Club. Pupils at <ORGANIZATION> Breor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Elementary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in this small town about 20 miles north of <LOCATION> Springfield </LOCATION> fired off a batch of letters last week accusing selectmen of being cruel and asking, `` please do n't kill the beavers.'' About six beavers live in a marshy field next to the road, according to <PERSON> Micki </PERSON> <PERSON> Seigel </PERSON>, who lives in the area and has printed up bumper stickers saying, `` I love the Linseed Road beavers.'' This week, a pupil's letter reached <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Beavers </ORGANIZATION>' Club of <LOCATION> Hampden </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Hampshire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Counties </ORGANIZATION>, a Holyoke-based service group, asking them to help their namesakes. Selectman Chairman <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Zgrodnick </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> said Wednesday he remains convinced that trapping is the best solution to protect the $ 350,000 worth of repairs on the road. `` I do n't know much about beaver dams, but I know they're bad,'' <PERSON> Zgrodnick </PERSON> said. He defended his decision not to call in an engineer before authorizing the trapping, but said an engineer would be called in this weekend to assess the potential for damage. <PERSON> Zgrodnick </PERSON> said selectmen told people opposing trapping that if they could find another way to deal with the problem `` very, very quickly, go ahead.'' Beaver Club President <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Davignon </PERSON> said his group was not interested in joining the political fray, but was willing to consider a request for help if a compromise is agreed on, such as installing special drainage pipes. Club members visited <PERSON> Seigel </PERSON> this week at Running Gutter brook. A small beaver lodge and dam have turned the field by the road into a shallow pond now covered with ice. <PERSON> Seigel </PERSON> said her main objective was to buy time until the field froze over. `` I am not an animal rights activist,'' she said. `` It just seemed, why kill them if you do n't have to.'' The beavers appeared this summer and the issue of the road threat surfaced this fall, said <PERSON> Zgrodnik </PERSON>, who said he did not recall who first brought it up. Some in town said they were n't sure how the issue got so controversial. `` We were kind of caught surprised ourselves when we started reading in the newspapers and we started checking into it,'' said Water Commissioner <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Osepowicz </PERSON>. Even if beaver dams block storm drains, water will drain through slits cut into the curb, Highway Superintendent <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> <PERSON> Pease </PERSON> was quoted as saying in a local newspaper last week. <PERSON> Pease </PERSON> had no comment Wednesday. `` All the answers come from town hall,'' he said. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Decker </PERSON>, a biologist with the state Division of <ORGANIZATION> Fisheries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION>, said about 1,400 beavers are killed in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> each year during the season between Nov. 15 and Feb. 28. `` We get hundreds of nuisance complaints,'' <PERSON> Decker </PERSON> said.
