<HEAD>School Program Launched to Reduce Gun Violence Among Youths</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SANDRA WALEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The nation's first comprehensive program to teach kindergartners and high schoolers alike about the dangers of guns was launched Wednesday by <LOCATION> Dade </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>'s public schools. The special curriculum was developed following a record 43 gunshot deaths last year in <LOCATION> Dade </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> of children 18 and under; so far this year, at least 48 children have been killed in gun-related incidents in <LOCATION> Dade </LOCATION>, school officials said. The program was made necessary by an increase in the prevalence of guns in society, said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Krop </PERSON>, a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Dade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>. `` We now feel compelled, unfortunately, to teach kids about guns,'' <PERSON> Krop </PERSON> said earlier at a news conference at Coconut Grove Elementary. `` Essentially our message to young people is, ` You do n't touch a handgun.''' That message will be reinforced in the classroom with discussions aimed at helping students recognize unsafe situations and know how to react when encountering guns. A video also will be shown to middle and senior high students focusing on the trauma of a gunshot death or injury _ through the experiences of other kids. One teen-ager describes the trauma of accidentally shooting his father; also interviewed were a football player left paralyzed and a girl who lost a leg in gun attacks. Brochures and a video were being prepared for parents to help them insure the safety of their children. Wednesday was declared `` Gun Safety Awareness Day'' by <ORGANIZATION> Dade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Schools </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's fourth-largest school district. `` Today's youngsters are at a greater risk of gun violence than any previous generation,'' <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Lautman </PERSON>, executive director of the Center to Prevent Handgun Violence in <LOCATION> Washignton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, said Friday at the news conference. `` We want the <LOCATION> Dade </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> program to serve as the national standard for education to reduce gun violence, death and injury among youth.'' In 1987, one out of every 10 children who died in the nation was killed with a gun, and gun accidents were the fourth leading cause of accidental death for children, according to Ms. <PERSON> Lautman </PERSON>. A new state law aimed at protecting children from accidental shootings also authorized the development of a gun-safety program in public schools. The measure, which took effect in October, requires gun owners to take reasonable precautions to keep loaded weapons away from children 15 and younger; the law provides for jail time and fines for gun owner's carelessness. <PERSON> Dade </PERSON>'s program to prevent gun injuries and deaths among children is tailored by age groups. For example, at the elementary level the emphasis will be on role-playing, while in the sixth through 12th grades, students will focus on issues surrounding gun violence, including conflict resolution activities and the role of the media. The curriculum was developed following discussions in April led by volunteers from the <ORGANIZATION> Dade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Youth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Crime </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Watch </ORGANIZATION> with some 400 middle and senior high students about guns and gun violence. Among the findings, released Wednesday, were that students have mixed opinions on whether guns are good or bad, with black and Hispanics most aware of and involved with daily handgun violence; students believe guns are more common today than at previous times; and that anti-gun messages need to show more the pain and loss suffered by victims of gun violence. <PERSON> Dwayne </PERSON> <PERSON> Dupuch </PERSON>, a second grader at <ORGANIZATION> Coconut </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Grove </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Elementary </ORGANIZATION>, said he had never been around a gun but he knew what they could do. `` Kill,'' he said without hesitation. And what had he learned so far about them? `` Not to touch guns,'' said the shy 7-year-old.
