<HEAD>Two Soldiers Killed, Third Injured In Attack on Security Post</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout, UPDATING with details. No pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A band of 10 to 12 raiders attacked a security post near the Irish border with guns and bombs Wednesday, killing two British soldiers and seriously injuring a third, police said. No group claimed responsibility, but suspicion fell on guerrillas of the <ORGANIZATION> Irish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> fighting British rule in <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>. The gunmen escaped unhurt after the attack at <LOCATION> Derryard </LOCATION>, an isolated checkpoint about two miles from the Fermanagh border with <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Monaghan </LOCATION> in the <LOCATION> Irish </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ulster </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Constabulary </ORGANIZATION> said. The victims were members of the 1st Battalion of the King's Own Scottish Borderers. Six other soldiers and a police officer survived unhurt. A police statement gave this account: A truck backed up to the checkpoint. As soldiers approached, men inside opened fire and threw grenades, killing one soldier. As the men were firing, a van was driven into the checkpoint and abandoned. A short time later, it exploded, killing another soldier and wounding a third. The truck sped away. An army patrol spotted it headed for the border. The patrol fired but the men escaped, abandoning the vehicle at the border. About four hours before the attack, 12 masked gunman with a truck and van took over a nearby house. They left shortly before the attack, taking a tractor that had not been recovered. The deaths brought to 12 the number of British soldiers killed in <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> this year. Up to Wednesday, sectarian violence in <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> had killed 60 people this year, including 21 members of security forces. The mainly Roman Catholic <ORGA