<BYLINE>By MICHAEL GRACZYK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HUNTSVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> appeals court set aside the conviction of death row inmate <PERSON> Clarence </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Brandley </PERSON> on Wednesday, more than two years after a judge ruled the black man was unfairly tried in the slaying of a white teen-ager. `` This will make this Christmas as bright as can be. It was worth the wait,'' <PERSON> Brandley </PERSON> said from the visiting area of death row, where he spent nearly nine years and once came within six days of execution before getting a stay. `` It's been a long time,'' <PERSON> Brandley </PERSON>, 38, said after he was told the court's decision. `` I'm very thankful. I did n't know what it was going to, when it was going to be. It's a prayer that's been answered. It's going to take some time to sink in _ to soak in.'' In a 6-3 decision, the appellate court said <PERSON> Brandley </PERSON> did not get a fair trial when a jury convicted him of the 1980 strangulation and rape of a teen-ager at <ORGANIZATION> Conroe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>, where <PERSON> Brandley </PERSON> was a janitor. His first trial ended with a hung jury. An all-white jury found him guilty in a second trial. <PERSON> Brandley </PERSON>'s attorneys and supporters contended the conviction was racially motivated. Then on Oct. 9, 1987, after a 10-day evidentiary hearing moved from <LOCATION> Conroe </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Galveston </LOCATION>, retired state District Judge <PERSON> Perry </PERSON> <PERSON> Pickett </PERSON> recommended that <PERSON> Brandley </PERSON> get a new trial because the previous two had been tainted with racism. In Wednesday's decision, the Austin-based appeals court said the state's investigation of the slaying led to a trial that lacked `` the rudiments of fairness'' and ordered <PERSON> Brandley </PERSON> released to the custody of the <LOCATION> Montgomery </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> sheriff for a possible new trial. <LOCATION> Montgomery </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> District Attorney <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Speers </PERSON> said Wednesday he was `` obviously disappointed'' with the court's ruling. `` I felt the conviction should have been upheld,'' said <PERSON> Speers </PERSON>, who declined to comment further until he had reviewed the court's decision He planned a Thursday afternoon press conference, possibly to discuss whether he will pursue a third trial. Prosecutors have maintained that <PERSON> Brandley </PERSON> is guilty and denied allegations that he was the subject of racial discrimination. <PERSON> Brandley </PERSON> is the third <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> inmate in a year whose conviction has been set aside in cases that have drawn national attention. The court set aside the capital murder conviction of <PERSON> Randall </PERSON> <PERSON> Dale </PERSON> <PERSON> Adams </PERSON>, whose case was the subject of the movie `` The Thin Blue Line,'' for the 1976 slaying of a <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> police officer. The court later set aside the robbery conviction of <PERSON> Joyce </PERSON> <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> woman who prosecutors say will be tried again for her alleged part in the 1980 robbery of a fur store. The court said the outrage over the teen-ager's murder `` can not justify the subversion of justice that took place during the investigation, which ultimately affected the trial of her accused perpetrator.'' <PERSON> Brandley </PERSON>'s attorney, <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> DeGeurin </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>, said he would ask the court to set bail for his client and hoped <PERSON> Brandley </PERSON> would be home for Christmas. The appeals court refused Wednesday afternoon to set bond, and <PERSON> DeGeurin </PERSON>'s bail motion in a <LOCATION> Galveston </LOCATION> district court was not ruled on by late Wednesday afternoon from the 122nd district court in <LOCATION> Galveston </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Brandley </PERSON>'s attorneys offered evidence that police and <LOCATION> Montgomery </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> prosecutors had set out to prove that <PERSON> Brandley </PERSON>, the only black janitor at the school, was guilty, rather than seeking the real killer. Another janitor who testified for the state allegedly was threatened by a <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> Ranger, and the state suppressed information that could have implicated someone other than <PERSON> Brandley </PERSON>, according to examples of improper investigation cited by the appeals court. `` I'm sitting here screaming having a fit, I'm so happy,'' said <PERSON> Rose </PERSON> <PERSON> Upshaw </PERSON> of the Free <PERSON> Clarence </PERSON> <PERSON> Brandley </PERSON> <PERSON> Coalition </PERSON>, a 200-member, Houston-based group that has fought to keep <PERSON> Brandley </PERSON>'s case in the public eye. `` We're just excited. We just ca n't believe it.'' `` Thank-you Jesus!'' said <PERSON> Brandley </PERSON>'s mother, <PERSON> Minnie </PERSON> <PERSON> Ola </PERSON> <PERSON> Brandley </PERSON>, when she was told of the court's decision. `` Pray for us and let's hope everything works out.'' `` I'm thrilled to death for <PERSON> Clarence </PERSON> and his family,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Beathard </PERSON>, a fellow inmate. `` But I hope nobody out there makes the corny comment that the system works. The system failed <PERSON> Clarence </PERSON>. It's been eight years. And there are more and more of these cases coming up.''
