` Does this mean we abandon planning? Of course not,'' <PERSON> Ryzhkov </PERSON> said. `` We have to leave free to the market only that part of production that would not lead to unbalancing the economy.'' Price reform would be postponed until 1991 and 1992, and even then, some would remain under state control. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> desperately needs to reform its state-set prices, which waste enormous resources by charging too little for scarce and expensive goods. <PERSON> Ryzhkov </PERSON> indicated that every plan for price reform had been opposed. The program did include surface changes, including the creation of government bonds, raising interest rates, and long-term land leasing. The 2,250-member <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> interrupted the premier's 1-hour, 45-minute speech with lukewarm applause only when <PERSON> Ryzhkov </PERSON> declared the state would remain the owner of `` means of production'' _ factories and equipment. <PERSON> Ryzhkov </PERSON> said the government would begin using more economic rather than managerial means to run the economy in a second stage of reform beginning in 1993. He specifically cited control of prices, credit and investment. His report appeared to contain nothing that would give Soviets an incentive to work efficiently.
