<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> on Wednesday described the views of those who advocate the legalization of drugs as `` stupid and morally atrocious.'' `` It does n't make any sense,'' <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Policy </ORGANIZATION>, said in an interview. `` It is becoming something of a fashion to believe this in certain circles of opinion. But even though it's fashionable, it's still every bit as dumb and compassionless as it was before. <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> pressed his counter-offensive against the increasingly outspoken ranks of those arguing for drug legalization a day after <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sweet </PERSON> said drugs _ including cocaine and heroin _ should be legalized, taxed and dispensed by the state because the war on narcotics is being lost. Sweet, a Republican and former prosecutor appointed by President <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> as a trial judge in the <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION>, said it was `` time to abolish the prohibition _ to cease treating indulgence in mind-alteration as a crime.'' <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>, who denounced such views in a speech at <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> on Monday, said Wednesday that he is unswayed by the growth in the number of legalization advocates or by the fact that they cut across the political spectrum and include, for the first time, a federal judge. Vice President <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>, visiting <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION>