<HEAD>Britain Calls for Lifting Sanctions to End Apartheid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> said Wednesday the way to end apartheid in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> is by gradually lifting economic sanctions as the government dismantles its segregation system rather than imposing a trade embargo. Attempts to isolate the government of South African President F.W. de Klerk are not the answer, British Ambassador Sir <PERSON> Crispin </PERSON> <PERSON> Tickell </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>'s Special Session on Apartheid. `` Nor are sanctions. ... They certainly weaken the South African economy, and in doing so they increase misery and poverty, in particular among the most vulnerable parts of the community,'' its black majority, he said. `` Their political effect is to increase resistance to change rather than to encourage it,'' <PERSON> Tickell </PERSON> said. `` When Mr. <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Klerk </PERSON> does take the necessary steps, we believe it would then be right to lift some of the measures imposed by the international community, so as to acknowledge progress and encourage <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> to proceed further down the path of dialogue.'' <PERSON> Tickell </PERSON>'s advice received polite applause; in the 159-member <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>, the overwhelming majority of nations believe <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> is implementing limited reforms only in response to the limited sanctions imposed so far. Most nations favor a total, mandatory trade embargo against <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, butthe <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> have used their veto power in the <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> to consistently block such moves. A <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> call for all nations to sever economic, military, sports and cultural links with <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> also has met with partial success. Apartheid has established a racially segregated society in which the 28 million South African blacks have no vote in national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
