<HEAD>Yugoslavia's Croatian Republic Endorses Free Elections</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ZAGREB, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A communist congress endorsed a multiparty system and free elections for <LOCATION> Croatia </LOCATION> Wednesday, opening the way for a non-communist government in <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s second-largest republic for the first time in 44 years The congress also elected <PERSON> Ivica </PERSON> <PERSON> Racan </PERSON>, 49, as new leader of the Croatian <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Racan </PERSON>, who has publicly advocated radical democratic reforms within communist <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>, received 41 votes in a secret ballot in the Central Committee. The only other candidate, <PERSON> Ivo </PERSON> <PERSON> Druzic </PERSON>, received 29 votes. <PERSON> Dragutin </PERSON> <PERSON> Dimitrovic </PERSON>, a member of the party's decision-making <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, said the party by its actions `` is showing its readiness to put its platform to the public for approval.'' Twelve burgeoning political opposition movements already exist in the central Yugoslav republic and seek official legalization. Parliamentary elections are scheduled in April. <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> is in its worst crisis since the communists consolidated power in 1945. The question of pluralism instead of continued one-party rule is straining already tenuous ties between some republics and a moribund economy heightens tensions. The liberal northern republic of <LOCATION> Slovenia </LOCATION> was until now the only of <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s six constituent regions to openly advocate introduction of Western-style democracy. The communist leadership of <LOCATION> Serbia </LOCATION>, the largest republic, vehemently opposes introduction of a multiparty system both in <LOCATION> Serbia </LOCATION> and federally. Last month, <LOCATION> Serbia </LOCATION> severed all business and official ties with <LOCATION> Slovenia </LOCATION>.
