<HEAD>Man Who Was Homeless Gets Teaching Job</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An electrician who slept on the streets after losing his job and his family said he won a position as a teacher at a technical school because he refused to give up hope. <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> Delano </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, 42, said he learned where to get free coffee and find shelter while living on the street, but kept thinking there must be a way out. `` I can still remember that I wanted to find a job. But how? I stunk and was dirty,'' <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> said recently. `` Who in his right mind would hire me? `` I finally went to a shelter because I knew the people who ran them knew how to help me get back on my feet.'' <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> is n't homeless any more. He learned new skills through Jubilee Soup Kitchen's career development program, and teaches commercial and residential electrical installation at <ORGANIZATION> Triangle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tech </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> said he found his life going into a tailspin after returning to his native <LOCATION> Lorain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, in 1984 from the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Area </LOCATION>, where he'd worked as an electrician for years. His electrical contracting business in <LOCATION> Lorain </LOCATION> failed, and a breakup with his wife, June, followed. <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> came to <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> almost three years ago because he had relatives in the city, but said he was unable to break into the skilled electrician's field. `` Then, when I filled out applications for lower paying jobs, they would look at my trade experience and tell me I was overqualified,'' he said. `` I finally got some odd jobs through a temporary job placement service by lying on my application and saying that my only skill was as a dishwasher.'' <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> took his first step back when a caseworker introduced him to Jubilees' 12-week career program. He was offered the job at <ORGANIZATION> Triangle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tech </ORGANIZATION> even though he had no teaching experience. <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Hathaway </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Triangle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tech </ORGANIZATION> said <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>'s positive attitude was a deciding factor when he hired him to start work Oct. 2. `` He was n't mad at the world because of what happened to him,'' he said. `` He just wanted to put it all behind him and get on again with his life.'' <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> said he's trying to restore relationships with his sons _ <PERSON> Aaron </PERSON>, 23; <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON>, 20; and <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>, 18 _ all in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> after losing touch with them. `` It's hard for me to pick up my relationships with them again because I'll have to tell them what happened to me,'' he said. `` That's hard.''
