<HEAD>Jennifer Casolo Arrives In U.S. After Salvador Deports Her</HEAD>
<HEAD>Retransmits a0797 with `a' category code. Eds: SUBS grafs 6-10, `President
Alfredo ..., with 10 grafs to UPDATE with quote from mother, travel plans
changed, details and quote from Miami news conference, Conn. preparations
for homecoming; picks up 11th graf: `Christiani told ...; SUBS 21st graf:
`Christiani said ..., to DELETE outdated first reference to Dodd.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK REYNA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION> woman accused of storing arms in her garden for leftist rebels returned to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> on Wednesday night after being freed from prison and deported from war-ravaged <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>. `` I do n't think I've suffered as terribly as thousands of Salvadorans have suffered here,'' <PERSON> Jennifer </PERSON> <PERSON> Casolo </PERSON>, 28, said in <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> before boarding a commercial flight to <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> 2 -LCB- weeks after she was jailed on terrorism charges. Accompanied by <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Ambassador <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> at <ORGANIZATION> Comalapa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airport </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Casolo </PERSON> insisted on her innocence when she was allowed to speak briefly with a few pool reporters. She said she signed a release statement acknowledging she was arrested and imprisoned on suspicion of having stored weapons and ammunition for rebels, but added, `` My position was always that I was innocent.'' <PERSON> Casolo </PERSON> said she believed her release supports that contention. She telephoned her parents in <LOCATION> Thomaston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, from the airport. <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> said she told `` them she'll be home for Christmas.'' He also said she had expressed the desire to return to <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> someday. `` She sounded confident, her voice was loud and clear,'' said her mother, <PERSON> Audrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Casolo </PERSON>, after talking with her daughter. `` She sounded like a happy person. She said she loved me very much.'' President <PERSON> Alfredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON> said earlier there was not enough evidence to continue holding Casolo. She was released into the custody of the ambassador, who picked her up in a black Cadillac escorted by Jeeps on Wednesday at the women's prison at <LOCATION> Ilopango </LOCATION> on the eastern outskirts of the capital. The caravan went to the airport and entered through a restricted entrance. Reporters were not allowed access either at the prison or airport. <PERSON> Casolo </PERSON> was put on an <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> flight to <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> and ushered to an undisclosed location upon her arrival, said the Rev. <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Long </PERSON>, chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Seminars </ORGANIZATION>, who traveled with her on the plane. `` It was a very emotional time for her, being taken straight from the prison to the airport and deported, because of her love for the people and the country of <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Long </PERSON> said. She decided late Wednesday to remain in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> and not return immediately to her home in <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION>, according to staffers for Sen. <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Dodd </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Conn </LOCATION>., who has followed the case Her travel plans beyond that were undecided, but church officials at the <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> news conference said <PERSON> Casolo </PERSON> planned to hold a news conference sometime Thursday. In <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION>, friends and well-wishers in her hometown prepared for her homecoming. <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Abbott </PERSON>, a close high school friend of Ms. <PERSON> Casolo </PERSON>'s, put up a sign on the town green that said, `` Welcome Home, <PERSON> Jennifer </PERSON>. We Love You.'' <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON> told a news conference he thought Casolo probably had cooperated with rebels of the <ORGANIZATION> Farabundo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marti </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>, who have fought U.S.-supported governments for 10 years and launched a major urban offensive in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> last month. `` I am morally convinced that <PERSON> Miss </PERSON> <PERSON> Casolo </PERSON> is guilty,'' he said. The case against <PERSON> Casolo </PERSON> will proceed and she was asked to remain available in case judicial authorities need to question her further, <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON> said. `` Evidence _ be it incriminating or exculpating _ will continue to be gathered,'' the president said. `` If the evidence against her becomes sufficient, she will be summoned to return for trial.'' He acknowledged that little could be done to make her come back to <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>. Casolo and two Salvadoran friends were arrested Nov. 26 in a police raid on her house. She was charged with terrorism, possessing weapons of war and criminal association, all of which she denied. There was no immediate word on the cases against those two Salvadorans. In the walled garden behind the house, police said, they dug up 103 mortar shells, 213 blocks of dynamite, 405 detonators, 150 feet of slow-burning fuse and 21,945 rounds of ammunition for Soviet-made automatic rifles. She said she did not know how the materiel got into the yard of her rented home on the northwestern edge of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON> denied his rightist administration was pressured to free Casolo by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, the key financial supporter of his government. `` The judge's decision to release her is strictly judicial,'' he said. `` It is a political decision that we have made to deport her.'' Judge <PERSON> Guillermo </PERSON> <PERSON> Romero </PERSON> of the criminal court handled the case. <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON> said he spoke with Sen. <PERSON> Dodd </PERSON>, who telephoned several times to ask about the case, but `` at no time did Sen. <PERSON> Dodd </PERSON> try to exert pressure. Indeed, his position was that, if there was sufficient proof against her, her trial should go forward.'' <PERSON> Dodd </PERSON> said earlier Wednesday he was told in telephone conversations with Salvadoran officials, including <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON>, that Casolo would be freed and expelled by Thursday afternoon. A statement issued by his office said <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON> `` informs me that the judge in her case has ultimately concluded the charges against <PERSON> Jennifer </PERSON> were not fully supported by the evidence, and that she could not thus be fairly prosecuted under Salvadoran law.'' <PERSON> Casolo </PERSON> spent five years in <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>, working for <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Seminars </ORGANIZATION>, which organizes tours for Americans to learn about the civil war. <PERSON> Salvador </PERSON> <PERSON> Ibarra </PERSON>, her defense lawyer, filed a writ Monday requesting her release for lack of evidence. <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON> said the judge ruled favorably on the writ. Her last <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> residence was in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>, and Rep. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> McDermott </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Wash </LOCATION>, said Wednesday: `` I am glad for <PERSON> Jennifer </PERSON>'s sake that she has been released because there were serious questions about the ability of the Salvadoran judicial system to provide her a fair trial. `` There are many individuals who do not have the benefit of so many friends in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. Our relief at <PERSON> Jennifer </PERSON>'s release must not diminish our concern for the many other church workers she leaves behind.''
