<HEAD>Sikh Wanted in Japanese Airport Bombing Extradited to Canada</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VANCOUVER, British Columbia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Sikh wanted in connection with a 1985 bombing that killed two baggage-handlers unloading a Canadian jet at <LOCATION> Narita </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> near <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> was extradited to <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> on Wednesday. <PERSON> Inderjit </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> <PERSON> Reyat </PERSON>, 37, who worked in <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> as an auto electrician before moving to <ORGANIZATION> Coventry </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, in 1986, appeared briefly in <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Vancouver </LOCATION> after arriving on a flight from <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Reyat </PERSON> was arrested in <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> in February 1988 and fought extradition until the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lords </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s highest legal body, refused to consider his appeal. He faces two charges of manslaughter and five counts of possessing explosives. Evidence presented during his extradition battle indicated a bomb exploded and killed two Japanese baggage handlers on June 23, 1985, as luggage was being unloaded at <LOCATION> Narita </LOCATION> from a Canadian <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> flight that had just arrived from <LOCATION> Vancouver </LOCATION>. The evidence indicated the suitcase bomb was to be transferred to an <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION> flight to <LOCATION> Bangkok </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Bombay </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>. On the same day, an <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION> flight from <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Montreal </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Bombay </LOCATION> via <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> blew apart off <LOCA