<HEAD>Kenyan Woman Battles Plan for 60-Story Building in People's Park</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIDRIKKE SCHANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The ruling political party's plan to put up <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s tallest building in a park set aside 26 years ago for the common man stirred enough outrage in environmentalist <PERSON> Wangari </PERSON> <PERSON> Maathai </PERSON> that she went to court to stop it. That raised the hackles of Parliament _ which held her action to be tantamount to suing the head of state _ and the court eventually threw the case out as lacking merit. But not before the issue raised a public outcry rarely seen in <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION>. Officials found themselves accused of being irresponsible, insensitive and unaccountable. Soon after independence from <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> in 1963, <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION>'s first president, <PERSON> Jomo </PERSON> <PERSON> Kenyatta </PERSON>, dedicated the 10-acre park on the edge of <LOCATION> Nairobi </LOCATION> for the use of everyday Kenyans. He called it <LOCATION> Uhuru </LOCATION> _ Swahili for freedom. Today the park is an oasis that offers an inexpensive respite for <LOCATION> Nairobi </LOCATION>'s thousands of day laborers. Many of them, lacking money for lunch, use the park for what sarcastically is known as an `` airburger'' _ a lunch-hour nap. After plans for the park were announced by the <ORGANIZATION> Kenya </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's only legal political party, President <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> arap </PERSON> <PERSON> Moi </PERSON> allowed debate to go on for a little more than a month. Then he assailed the building's critics as having `` insects in their head'' and told them to `` shut up.'' His order silenced most of the building's detracters. Not Mrs. <PERSON> Maathai </PERSON>. She went to court despite <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>'s threats to have her <ORGANIZATION> Green </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Belt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION> tree-planting organization banned. The park has a processional, a pond with recreational row boats, walkways and tiered levels for relaxing and picknicking; it provides a getaway for the `` wananchi'' -LRB- common people -RRB- living in the crowded neighborhoods and slums ringing the city. Scores of citizens in letters printed by <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION>'s two independent newspapers pleaded with the government to put the complex elsewhere. They, like Mrs. <PERSON> Maathai </PERSON>, have been dismissed as ignorant and subversive by the government's most vocal stalwarts in a country where views contrary to the official position are strongly discouraged. In a letter to <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION>, Mrs. <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mwangi </PERSON> wrote: `` I use the park with my family most weekends. I see people there who have no other forms of recreation, with their families, men with wives and barefoot children but happy to have those moments of tranquility when they can forget the struggle of daily living. ... `` Please have a care for the wananchi. We are already suffering from other problems.'' <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION>'s leaders maintain the project will lend prestige to what already is one of <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s most developed and prosperous cities and will provide thousands of needed jobs. Critics do n't dispute these aspects of the project; they say they just want the building moved to one of the other vast open areas surrounding the city. The complex, which is expected to cost $ 197 million and take about four years to complete, will include a 60-story main tower with a four-story statue of President <PERSON> Moi </PERSON> in front, two 10-story wings, an auditorium, parking for 2,000 people, and conference facilities for 5,000 people, even though a conference center already exists just a quarter of a mile from the proposed site. In a public statement, the <ORGANIZATION> Architectural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION> protested putting the project in the park. It contended the building will destroy the grassy belt on <LOCATION> Nairobi </LOCATION>'s perimeter that earned the metropolis the name `` <LOCATION> Green </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> in the Sun.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Maathai </PERSON> has earned the most vehement and vitriolic condemnation from Parliament for her outspoken criticism of the building, which has continued despite the president's directive for people like her to shut up. Mrs. <PERSON> Maathai </PERSON> initially was reviled for her protests in letters to individual members of <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>, the British high commissioner -LRB- ambassador -RRB- and the <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> media magnate <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Maxwell </PERSON>, who owns a share of the ruling party's media interests. She also called on the people of <LOCATION> Nairobi </LOCATION> to `` stand up and raise their voices.'' She drew even harsher rebukes for seeking a court injunction to bar construction of the complex. Members of Parliament assailed her 12-year-old <ORGANIZATION> Green </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Belt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION> as bogus and subversive. On Dec. 11, the High Court dismissed her suit _ a `` non-starter from the date of filing.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Maathai </PERSON>, who before the ruling accused the court of being more concerned with `` politics than law,'' said she was disappointed in the decision but would appeal it to the attorney general's office. `` The most important thing is to rise and express one's opinion and say no when you should say no,'' she said. `` If we are not listened to then at least we have done what we could do within our own constraints.''
</TEXT>
