<HEAD>For Release PMs Thursday, Dec. 14</HEAD>
<HEAD>Workers Will Want More in 1990, Says Chamber</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Losing the fight to prevent an increase in the minimum wage has left the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> in a somewhat sullen mood about the immediate economic consequences. It will, the chamber says, result in the loss of hundreds of thousands of job opportunities, ignite a new round of wage inflation, raise the deficit, compromise <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> competitiveness and force some companies to forego expansion. The chamber was in the forefront of opposition to the increase, which takes the hourly minimum to $ 4.25 from $ 3.35, and it still smarts from the defeat, saying it resulted when `` sound economics fell victim to political expediency.'' More recently it expressed its ire in The Business Advocate, a monthly newspaper delivered to members and opinion leaders, saying the inrease will have a ripple effect on workers in higher-paying jobs. `` When wages at one level increase, employees at higher levels place a new and greater value on their services,'' said <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON>, director of the chamber's Employee Relations Policy Center. He said numerous studies concur in his finding that the increase will cost jobs. He cited one by the <ORGANIZATION> Congressional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> that indicated between 125,000 and 800,000 jobs would be lost if the rate were raised to $ 4.55 as once proposed. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> agreed, however, to a lesser increase, bringing the minimum to $ 3.80 on April 1, 1990 and to $ 4.25 one year later. It also permits a lower, short-term training wage for some teenagers. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> cites a 1981 report by the <ORGANIZATION> Minimum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Study </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, named by former President <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>, that found that each 10 percent increase in the minimum wage has the potential to raise the nation's payroll by 0.76 percent. Since the new law will raise the wage 27 percent, the Business Advocate article concludes that labor costs will rise by about 2.05 percent, or more than $ 46 billion. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> did express satisfaction that `` though we lost the last battle, we saved businesses more than $ 9 billion by holding off a wage increase for the past three years,'' and that it helped push through a training wage. The latter, opposed by organized labor, will allow employers to pay a lower minimum wage for three months to first-time workers under age 20. The training wage of $ 3.35 would begin April 1, 1990, rising to $ 3.61 a year later. While the minimum wage puts a base under minimum wages in much of the nation, it is already exceeded in other areas, with some food outlets already paying $ 6 an hour or even more for unskilled workers. The chamber article did n't address another criticism of the higher minimum, one made by <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Dunkelberg </PERSON>, dean of <ORGANIZATION> Temple </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>'s business school, that the increases might not be as effective as believed in reducing poverty levels. <PERSON> Dunkelberg </PERSON> testified during hearings held prior to the law's signing on Nov. 17 that many earning the minimum are not primary breadwinners in their families but instead are relatively comfortable people earning second incomes Regardless of who gets the minimum wage, and the automatic increases that lift it over the next two years, the chamber said it expects those earning above the minimum are likely, as a consequence of the law, to want more. `` Expect wage pressure,'' it warned.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Thursday, Dec. 14.</NOTE>
