<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Dec. 17, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Town Torn Between Forgetting and Remembering Flight 103</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LON1 of Dec. 13</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BARR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOCKERBIE, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The crater of <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> Flight 103, the deepest, most visible scar on the town where it fell, is disappearing under new homes. At the end of November, contractors began building 11 houses in <LOCATION> Sherwood </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Crescent </LOCATION> where the falling wreckage of the <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 747 killed 11 residents of <LOCATION> Lockerbie </LOCATION> last Dec. 21, the final deaths of a terrorist bombing that killed the 259 passengers and crew of Flight 103. `` Some people needed an awful lot of sustaining just to get to this week,'' said <PERSON> Malcolm </PERSON> <PERSON> McGeorge </PERSON>, who directs a team of social workers in the town. `` The frustration that it has taken so long to rebuild has been very great, crushing for some people. Others have little interest, because they do n't really want to go back, but feel they have to go back because so much effort has been put in by so many people.'' The crater has been filled and the street restored. Burnt shells of houses have been pulled down, and only muddy vacant lots betray the extent of the destruction. The construction reflects the determination to wipe out all traces of the disaster. Along the sidewalk of <PERSON> Sherwood </PERSON> <PERSON> Crescent </PERSON>, however, a lone pot of flowers testifies to a town torn between remembrance and forgetting. <LOCATION> Lockerbie </LOCATION> lost its quiet obscurity just after 7:03 that cold Wednesday night, when explosives hidden in a radio-cassette recorder shattered the <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> jet `` Maid of the Seas.'' At 36 seconds past 7:03, the <ORGANIZATION> Eskdalemuir </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Observatory </ORGANIZATION> 15 miles from <LOCATION> Lockerbie </LOCATION> recorded seismic shocks, apparently caused by the falling wreckage. The main part of the fuselage, with enough jet fuel to push a 747 from <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, exploded in <LOCATION> Sherwood </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Crescent </LOCATION>. Shattered metal and flaming fuel spewed over dozens of houses, and debris blocked traffic on the four-lane north-south highway. A forward portion of the fuselage landed across town in <LOCATION> Rosebank </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Crescent </LOCATION>. The plane's nose fell 3 miles from town, across the road from the stone church at <LOCATION> Tundergarth </LOCATION>. `` The night it happened, one of the first things I saw was the body of a child hanging in a tree,'' said <PERSON> Ronnie </PERSON> <PERSON> Hall </PERSON>, who lives in the <LOCATION> Rosebank </LOCATION> area. `` That child will never leave me.'' The town's population of 3,500 nearly doubled with the influx of a thousand police officers, 700 military personnel, 500 other volunteer and support workers, and hundreds of reporters, photographers and camera crews. Sheep now graze placidly where the plane's nose fell and the two shattered houses in <ORGANIZATION> Rosebank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Crescent </ORGANIZATION> have been rebuilt, but the memories remain. `` When you think the number of houses -LRB- in <LOCATION> Rosebank </LOCATION> -RRB- that face in that small area where 61 bodies were found ... there must be more than a hundred people who could not avoid seeing that mayhem,'' <PERSON> McGeorge </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Sandy </PERSON> <PERSON> Pelling </PERSON>, assistant director of social work for the <LOCATION> Dumfries </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Galloway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, recalled one family that `` identified with the young boy that was lying in their garden for two days _ they started grieving for him, they wanted to know his name.'' <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunter </PERSON>, whose home was 120 yards from the <PERSON> Sherwood </PERSON> <PERSON> Crescent </PERSON> crater, brought his family back to the house two days after the disaster. `` We wanted back in, to settle the kids if nothing else,'' he said. Repairs put them out of the house for six weeks, however, and it was 10 months before the job was complete. But they never thought of moving, he said. Before talking with a reporter, <PERSON> Hunter </PERSON> shooed his daughters out of the parlor. Talk of the disaster upsets them, he said, and with the onset of winter he realized his older daughter, now 5, had become afraid of the dark. `` We do talk about it with them on their own. They understand what happened,'' he said. In the months after the disaster, some adults as well as children had difficulty sleeping, <PERSON> McGeorge </PERSON> said. `` There were reports of children not sleeping or having nightmares or playing what their parents thought were rather bizarre, unsavory games _ playing airplanes and crashing them and so on,'' he said. `` But that's definitely understandable, and people were encouraged to understand that was OK, that it was a way of dealing with it.'' He said there have been no reports of children developing serious behavioral problems. `` I think the people with the serious and lasting problems are in the uniformed services ... just because of what they had to do in the recovery of bodies,'' <PERSON> McGeorge </PERSON> said. The torn bodies reawakened some men's memories of combat service, in one case going back to World War I, he said. For some women, the disaster brought back moments of great personal loss _ of a husband, a child or parents. `` One of the things you hear people say is that they do n't feel safe anymore. If it happened once it can happen again,'' <PERSON> McGeorge </PERSON> said. `` Some of them are quite unable to use public transport _ buses or trains. Airplanes are just out of the question.'' <PERSON> McGeorge </PERSON> said some residents have admitted fearing the dark, or the noise of a passing truck or express train. When one <LOCATION> Lockerbie </LOCATION> man took a train to <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, his wife kept the television on all day expecting news of a rail disaster. Reflecting on the work in <LOCATION> Lockerbie </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Pelling </PERSON> talks about `` the timelessness of disaster'' for survivors. `` It is there, it has happened, it is always going to be there,'' he said. `` While they desperately want to get this episode behind them and feel they are going forward, they are not going to be able to shake off the night of the 21st in quite as easy terms.'' Agencies that came to help are thinking now of leaving. `` I think we should melt away. We're another scar of the disaster,'' said <PERSON> Alex </PERSON> <PERSON> McElroy </PERSON>, who directs the Community Support office set up by the regional council. <PERSON> McElroy </PERSON>'s office runs by two clocks, one set on <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> because some of its contacts are with authorities and insurors in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> as well as with relatives of the American victims. The approach of the anniversary made memories unavoidable. On the afternoon of Dec. 21, the town will dedicate a monument in the Dryfesdale Cemetery bearing the names of the 270 dead. A memorial service will be held that night outside the town hall, used a year ago as a temporary mortuary. Some <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> relatives of victims plan to attend. `` We're hoping that after the 21st we can get back and have our town to ourselves,'' said <PERSON> Valerie </PERSON> <PERSON> Moloney </PERSON>, who works with a childrens' group formed after the disaster. <PERSON> Hugh </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON>, a member of the district council, agreed. `` I think they see it as a watershed, a time for looking forward again. I think people hope -LRB- the anniversary -RRB- will be an end to the media attention.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Dec. 17</NOTE>
