<HEAD>Lockerbie Not Limiting Rebuilding to Crash Damage</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Flight 103-Lockerbie, b0543</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOCKERBIE, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The wrenching disaster of <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> Flight 103 had an unexpected side effect for this small market town. The rebuilding effort has given residents the impetus to push for some renewal projects. Beyond paying to rebuild destroyed homes and other essential repairs, the local government has borrowed money to refurbish dozens of units of public housing. Residents also pushed for better lights and street repairs, and got them. And now they are pressing plans for a park on the site of an abandoned factory. `` We just took a good look at ourselves and decided we were being badly done by,'' said <PERSON> Ronnie </PERSON> <PERSON> Hall </PERSON>, vice chairman of a residents committee in the <LOCATION> Rosebank </LOCATION> area. `` We're grasping the opportunity, because now the regional council is very sympathetic to requests from <LOCATION> Lockerbie </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> said. `` I think they are things we should have pushed for years ago.''
