<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-89 1338EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s i BC-Flight103-Investigation Adv17   12-13 0451</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Flight 103-Investigation, Adv 17,0456</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv17</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Dec. 17, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>First Suspect Named in International Hunt for Pan Am Bombers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Flight 103-Lockerbie, b0543</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 For 12 months, police have doggedly sought the bombers of <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> Flight 103 but said little officially about the progress of their international manhunt. Here's what they have confirmed and what news reports have said following the explosion and crash that killed all 259 people on the plane and 11 on the ground last Dec. 21: _ One week after the disaster, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> confirmed a bomb blew up the <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 747 and said investigators had found evidence of a powerful plastic explosive _ In February, Scottish police said the bomb was planted in a <ORGANIZATION> Toshiba </ORGANIZATION> radio-cassette player and probably checked in as hold baggage in <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, where Flight 103 originated West German police had seized similar bombs in October 1988 and arrested 16 members of a Palestinian group. All but two were soon released, including <PERSON> Marwan </PERSON> <PERSON> Khreesat </PERSON>, who some people believe assembled the bomb in <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION>. _ News reports have frequently pointed to the Popular Front for the <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Palestine-General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION>, a radical Palestinian group based in <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>, as the leading suspect The group's leader, <PERSON> Ahmed </PERSON> <PERSON> Jibril </PERSON>, repeatedly has denied involvement but has also reportedly boasted he was paid by <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> to avenge the downing of an Iranian airliner by a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> warship. <PERSON> Hafez </PERSON> <PERSON> Dalkamoni </PERSON>, one of <PERSON> Jibril </PERSON>'s top aides, is one of the two suspects still held in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. _ Some news reports said the bomb was smuggled to <LOCATION> Malta </LOCATION>, checked onto an <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Malta </ORGANIZATION> flight to <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> and transferred to <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> without an accompanying passenger Others say the bomb began its journey in <LOCATION> Larnaca </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>, in a suitcase switched with one belonging to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> intelligence officers returning home after looking for American hostages in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. _ A court in <LOCATION> Uppsala </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>, last month identified <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> <PERSON> Talb </PERSON>, a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Popular </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Struggle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>, another radical faction, as a suspect in the Flight 103 bombing Scottish police were permitted to remove clothing from his <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION> apartment, reportedly to compare with shreds of clothing found in the wreckage. <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> <PERSON> Talb </PERSON> is awaiting verdicts, due Dec. 21, on charges of murder and attempted murder in connection with four bombings in northern <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. Court documents show he was in <LOCATION> Malta </LOCATION> in October 1988. _ <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION> Rep. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Traficant </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> released portions of a report, said to have been prepared for <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION>'s insurance underwriters, that alleges the terrorists got the bomb aboard the plane through a CIA-protected drug smuggling ring at <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> airport. The <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> called the allegations nonsense.
</TEXT>
