<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Dec. 17, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Prescription Drug Abuse Down But Rules Hamper Some Treatment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Drug enforcement officials are declaring a partial victory in one battle of the war on drugs: the diversion of prescription drugs to the illicit market. Cases of prescription drug abuse reported to the national <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Abuse </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Warning </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION> have fallen by almost one-third since 1981. But some medical professionals say the tougher new rules are preventing effective treatment of many Americans with legitimate needs for such medication. In 1981, 131,618 incidents of pharmaceutical abuse were reported to the warning network, but by 1988 that number had dropped to 88,525, said <PERSON> Gene </PERSON> <PERSON> Haislip </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enforcement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. `` This is the one part of the drug problem where we have made genuine progress and reduced the size of it,'' said <PERSON> Haislip </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> DEA </ORGANIZATION>'s diversion control chief And yet, the diversion of legal drugs remains `` a very large problem,'' he said. Most frequently abused are the narcotic painkillers Percodan, Dilaudid and codeine; the stimulants amphetamine and <PERSON> Preludin </PERSON>, both prescribed for short-term treatment of obesity; the sedative Doriden; and tranquilizers such as Valium, <LOCATION> Librium </LOCATION>, Xanax and Diazepam. The profit potential in diverted drugs is huge. A single 4 milligram tablet of Dilaudid costs a bonafide patient about 60 cents but can sell on the street for as much as $ 60, <PERSON> Haislip </PERSON> says. He estimates that up to 15 percent of the 25 billion prescription pills and capsules manufactured legally each year wind up on the street. The drugs reach the black market through several routes: physicians who intentionally write unnecessary prescriptions, patients who convince doctors that they need the drugs when they do n't, pharmacies that falsify records and thefts from drug stores. The authorities' biggest weapons in the battle against diversions have been tighter regulation of physicians and pharmacies and monitoring of prescriptions. Some observers contend the requirements have made life more painful for patients with a legitimate need for frequently diverted drugs. `` Physicians go out of their way to avoid attracting the attention of regulatory agencies,'' write physicians <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stratton </PERSON> <PERSON> Hill </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> and <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fields </PERSON> in a new book, `` Drug Treatment of Cancer Pain in a Drug-Oriented Society.'' `` As a result, they underprescribe the dosage of opiates and fail to provide patients with prescriptions for drug quantities sufficient to cover a reasonable time interval, thus making frequent requests for resupply necessary,'' the doctors write. `` This prescribing behavior is humiliating for patients.'' Take the case of a <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> minister highlighted in a documentary film by <PERSON> Hill </PERSON>, who works at a <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> cancer center. The Baptist minister, suffering from cancer and seeking a stronger painkiller from his doctor, was rebuffed as if he were an addict. `` You're a dope head and I'm going to dry you out while you're in here,'' the minister quoted his physician as saying In an interview, <PERSON> Hill </PERSON> related the case of another patient who was receiving a toxic dose of acetaminophen because his docotor was prescribing it in combination with codeine rather than a stronger medication _ simply to avoid the scrutiny that attends prescriptions for the most frequently diverted painkillers. The <ORGANIZATION> DEA </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Haislip </PERSON> said the federal regulation specifies that the legitimate treatment of pain should not be impeded. He rejected arguments that physicians are hesitant about prescribing necessary drugs, noting that morphine prescriptions rose 300 percent from 1982 to 1986. `` That's an enormous increase, but the statistics do not show any such comparable increase in diversion for that drug, which leads me to believe that it is for cancer and most all of it is legitimate,'' <PERSON> Haislip </PERSON> said. However, he acknowledged that some patients may have trouble finding pharmacies willing to carry certain controlled drugs. A recent nationwide survey found that only 38 percent of responding drug stores routinely stock an oral morphine preparation, in many cases because of fear of robbery. While some doctors shy away from prescribing the most potent drugs, a few others have made an illegal living from it. Officials cite the case of Dr. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON>. He ran two weight-reduction clinics in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> and `` was writing about 45 percent of the prescriptions for Preludin for the state of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>'' when arrested in 1982, said <PERSON> Wilbur </PERSON> <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> DEA </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>. Prosecutor <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> <PERSON> Harrison </PERSON> said at the time that investigators sent undercover agent <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON>, who is not overweight, to one clinic to buy the stimulant. `` <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> told him they would have to make it look legal, so <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> would have to bring four fat girls with him,'' <PERSON> Harrison </PERSON> said. `` He came back with the girls, all law enforcement officers, and got the prescriptions.'' <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON>, originally indicted on 63 counts, pleaded guilty in a plea bargain to one count of illegally prescribing the drug. He lost his medical license and was sentenced to five years in prison, <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> said. The federal Controlled Substances Act of 1970 tightened the rules for those handling drugs with a potential for abuse. Such drugs are broken down into five categories, or schedules: _ Schedule I drugs, such as heroin, have the highest potential for abuse but no accepted medical use and can be used only for research _ Schedule II drugs are the most dangerous and subject to abuse This category includes Percodan, Dilaudid, morphine and some codeine formulations as well as amphetamines and Preludin. Federal regulations require that everyone who prescribes or handles Schedule II drugs register with the <ORGANIZATION> DEA </ORGANIZATION>; that manufacturers, distributors and pharmacies complete special DEA forms on every transaction; that patients have a written prescription that can not be refilled; and that the drugs be kept in a safe by the manufacturer, importer and distributor _ but not the pharmacy. The <ORGANIZATION> DEA </ORGANIZATION> even sets production limits. _ Schedule III, IV and V drugs pose a lesser danger and are deemed less subject to abuse Doriden is a Schedule III drug and most tranquilizers are Schedule IV. Schedule V includes many over-the-counter narcotic preparations. Federal regulations for the Schedule III, IV and V drugs are increasingly lenient. Nine states have gone beyond federal rules, imposing a multiple-copy prescription system, with most of the states requiring the physician, the pharmacy and state officials to retain a copy of each prescription. Officials of the states _ <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> _ say such programs enable them to spot those who seem to be prescribing or dispensing inordinate amounts. All the state programs affect Schedule II drugs. Some include a few Schedule III drugs, and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, citing an alarming number of prescriptions, recently added the Schedule IV sleeping pills and tranquilizers such as Valium and <LOCATION> Librium </LOCATION>. Officials say <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>' multiple-copy program helped crack the case of Dr. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON>, although the long lines outside his clinics in <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Nacogdoches </LOCATION> already had attracted law enforcement attention. The White House Conference for a Drug Free <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> recommended in June 1988 that all states establish such programs, and the <ORGANIZATION> DEA </ORGANIZATION> supports them. The <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pharmaceutical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> and some drug companies oppose the programs, citing concerns about patient care, among others. <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Webb </PERSON>, the pharmaceutical association's professional affairs director, said Schedule II prescriptions go down dramatically as soon as such programs are instituted, and that can hurt patients `` who truly do need large quantities of medication.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Dec. 17</NOTE>
