<FIRST>s a BC-Drugs-Cancer Adv17   12-13 0681</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Drugs-Cancer, Adv 17,0700</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv17</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Dec. 17, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Parents of Dying Girl Struggled To Get Morphine To Ease Her Pain</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Drug Diversion, b0547</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX19 of Dec. 13</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Dewey </PERSON> and <PERSON> Matilda </PERSON> <PERSON> Houck </PERSON> have seen the drug war from the other side, fighting a sometimes futile battle to obtain painkillers for a 5-year-old daughter being destroyed by cancer. They raced to hospitals at all hours of the day and night to get prescriptions for morphine that were good only for 48 hours, searched the area for pharmacies that would risk the possibility of a break-in to carry the drug, and tried to comfort their terrified daughter when she asked the unanswerable question: `` Why does this have to happen to me?'' `` It is tragic enough to lose a child, but it's awful to live with the terror of her agony,'' <PERSON> Matilda </PERSON> said in an interview at her home in this <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, suburb. <PERSON> Kendra </PERSON> <PERSON> Laurel </PERSON> <PERSON> Houck </PERSON> was born Oct. 28, 1983; she died March 3, 1989. A six-month failure by doctors to diagnose her neural blastoma meant that when it was discovered in August 1986, the only options left were experimental treatments. The doctors told the Houcks their only child would have had a good chance of recovery had the cancer been diagnosed earlier. Instead, for the next 2 -LCB- years, the family suffered through experimental treatments, enjoyed a 10-month remission, doled out dosages first of codeine and Demerol and later morphine, celebrated <PERSON> Kendra </PERSON>'s fifth birthday and learned all about the nation's drug laws. Two days after Halloween 1988, <PERSON> Kendra </PERSON>'s condition deteriorated dramatically. `` From that day on, it became morphine ... and even that was n't real effective,'' said <PERSON> Dewey </PERSON> `` She would be screaming on morphine,'' said <PERSON> Matilda </PERSON>, a gentle woman whose voice wavered as she tried to restrain tears. `` It just was n't cutting the pain. She was conscious and in agony.'' By the time <PERSON> Kendra </PERSON> died, her eyes pressed open day and night by a brain tumor, she was taking more than 100 milligrams of morphine every four hours. To <PERSON> Dewey </PERSON>, `` the real issue ... is access'' to morphine. The Houcks found that very few pharmacies carry the drug out of fear of robberies; those that do generally have very little on hand for the same reason. <PERSON> Dewey </PERSON> said pharmacies refused to tell him over the phone whether they carried morphine because they feared a holdup. The prescriptions were good only for 48 hours, which meant that in times of need, they would race to <ORGANIZATION> Children </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> to get one from the doctors who knew <PERSON> Kendra </PERSON>'s condition. But they could not get the morphine there because <PERSON> Kendra </PERSON> was at home, not in the hospital. Eventually, they found a pharmacist who knew their situation and would have the morphine ready when they needed it. He sold it to them at cost. Even then, the price was $ 494 for a typical three-day supply, <PERSON> Matilda </PERSON> said. `` I felt like the sick and dying are paying the price for our drug war,'' she said. These are not radical, anti-establishment people. They did not attempt illicit street buys of heroin for <PERSON> Kendra </PERSON>'s pain _ something experts say would not have helped her _ or marijuana for her nausea. `` That would have been an option to us had we chosen to do it in an outlaw way,'' <PERSON> Dewey </PERSON> said, but it would have been `` 100 percent inconsistent'' with their lifestyle. In addition, he said, they were concerned how <PERSON> Kendra </PERSON>'s mix of drugs, had it included heroin or marijuana, would have affected her. Merely handling the morphine seemed odd to <LOCATION> Dewey </LOCATION>. `` It was strange to fool with this stuff that was verboten,'' he said. `` We had jugs full of it and we could not get enough'' for <PERSON> Kendra </PERSON>. After <PERSON> Kendra </PERSON> died, the nurse immediately cleared out all the leftover controlled substances, destroying them in the presence of another health-care professional. `` I did n't understand why I could n't just flush it down the toilet with the Valium'' he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Dec. 17</NOTE>
