<FIRST>a a BC-BehindtheWheel Adv23-24   12-13 0853</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Behind the Wheel, Adv 23-24,0875</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv23</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv24</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, Dec. 23-24, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Lexus LS 400: Comfort, and Delicious Attention to Detail</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto, LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN M. JOB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>For The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 The 1990 Lexus LS 400 is a car drivers will want to live in. I did. The LS 400 test car had better soundproofing than my apartment and an ambience several notches higher. It further beat out my abode by coming equipped with an automatic compact disc player, operating by remote control from the trunk. As a friend noted: `` This is a car that you would n't mind riding in, even if you had a horrendous commute. In fact, you'd look forward to it.'' Such is the calming influence of the Lexus, the first of a new breed of Japanese imports designed to lure buyers from such upscale European luxury cars as <ORGANIZATION> Mercedes-Benz </ORGANIZATION>, BMW and <ORGANIZATION> Jaguar </ORGANIZATION>. Early indications are that the LS 400, the larger of the two Lexus models available, is a worthy competitor. `` Lexus transports you literally and figuratively into another dimension,'' says Car and Driver magazine. `` The car's smoothness and air of total integration is both a wonder and a delight.'' Automobile magazine says, `` Another master stroke from the land of the perfect machine.'' Both magazines have named the LS 400 one of their top 10 autos of the 1990 model year. What is so alluring about the LS 400? After all, on the outside, this Toyota product is understated. The rounded front end resembles that of a Mercedes. My first clue to the pampering offered by the LS 400 was the electronic steering wheel that automatically tilts and telescopes in or out to a pre-set position as the key fits into the ignition. The steering wheel also contains an airbag. Then came the whisper-soft startup. For the first couple of times, I needed to check the automatic lights on the test car's dashboard to confirm the engine had started On the road, the car was equally quiet. <ORGANIZATION> Goodyear </ORGANIZATION> worked 18 months to develop a tire that meets <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION>'s rigid standards for that peaceful ride. I also admired the smooth shifting of the four-speed, automatic overdrive transmission. I barely noticed as the powerful 32-valve, V8 engine and well-tuned transmission went through their paces. And the antilock brakes were the most sensitive I've encountered. Finally was the attention to detail. Front seats were wide and comfortable, with electronic controls for personal adjustments. Even the headrests were electronic. <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> used a computer to study passengers' weight distribution so the seat design would ease fatigue. The height of the seatbelt anchors also were electronically adjustable, so shorter people do n't have to tolerate chafing at the neck; with the touch of a button, the belt could be lowered on the door post. The power window buttons were well-designed, to accommodate even long fingernails. <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> had its engineers put on fake nails before deciding the final design of the window buttons. The premium sound system, with the remote CD player in the trunk, was superb. The changer holds six compact discs, selected before the drive begins, and is operated from the dashboard panel. A convenient two-cup holder popped out from the center armrest, and the spacious trunk contained a nifty first aid kit, complete with travel case, and an auto repair kit. The LS 400 is larger and more popular than the other Lexus model, the ES 250. Company spokeswoman <PERSON> Mindy </PERSON> <PERSON> Weiman </PERSON> said that of the more than 9,000 Lexus vehicles sold since the line was introduced in September, the majority are LS 400s. Target buyers are baby boomers entering their peak earning years, she said, noting that the number of Americans aged 35 to 65 will grow from 78 million to 94 million into the next decade. Household income of the Lexus buyers will be $ 50,000-plus, <PERSON> Weiman </PERSON> said. Early Lexus sales showed the interest of import owners. Among the first 1,000 buyers, 35 percent traded in European imports, while 20 percent traded in Japanese models, <PERSON> Weiman </PERSON> said. Twenty percent traded in domestic vehicles. In its competition with the European luxury cars, the Lexus has an advantage in price and a disadvantage as the new kid on the block. The LS 400 starts at $ 35,000, thousands less than the Mercedes 300E, at $ 39,950, and the lowest-priced <ORGANIZATION> Jaguar </ORGANIZATION>, the $ 39,700 XJ-6 four-door sedan. But Lexus does n't have the years of name recognition granted the <ORGANIZATION> BMW </ORGANIZATION>, Mercedes or <ORGANIZATION> Jaguar </ORGANIZATION> nameplates. That does not deter <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> from predicting sales of 16,000 Lexus cars this year, with sales next year set for 75,000. The LS 400 is a new vehicle, so Consumer Reports does not list owner complaints. But in early December, <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> recalled all 8,000 LS 400s to fix a sticky cruise control mechanism and replace a defective stoplight cover that would melt if the light was left burning. In addition, Lexus mechanics were also to make sure a connector between the alternator and the battery was seated properly. If not clicked into place, battery power could be drained, Lexus spokesman <PERSON> Kurt </PERSON> <PERSON> Von </PERSON> <PERSON> Zumwalt </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Dec. 23-24</NOTE>
