<HEAD>Times Mirror Says Op Profit Rise Unlikely in 1989, NY Times Co. Has
Charge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A weak advertising market for newspapers in the <LOCATION> Northeast </LOCATION> is part of the reason for <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mirror </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>'s declaration that it is unlikely to have higher operating earnings this year and for a big charge against fourth quarter earnings at <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mirror </ORGANIZATION> executives told securities analysts on Tuesday that higher circulation costs at its <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angeles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> newspaper and a settlement of a legal dispute also figured in its projection of a possible decline in operating earnings for 1989 If operating earnings decline, it would be the first such drop at <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mirror </ORGANIZATION> since 1982. Separately, <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> announced a $ 44 million charge against fourth quarter earnings, due to its investment in its forest products operation and estimated costs related to expected voluntary union staff cuts at <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION>, its flagship newspaper. The staff cuts, which are expected to involve mainly production workers, were attributed to weak advertising volume in the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> region and further automation of printing and production facilties. Analysts who follow the newspaper business have said they expect ad revenue growth for newspapers to remain sluggish next year, particularly in the <LOCATION> Northeast </LOCATION> where the economy appears weaker than in other regions. Times Mirror, a media and information company based in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, owns the <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> and several Eastern newspapers, including <ORGANIZATION> Newsday </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Newsday </LOCATION>, The <LOCATION> Hartford </LOCATION> Courant and the <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION> Sun newspapers. The company's earnings from operations were up 7 percent for the first nine months of 1989 to $ 1.62 a share from $ 1.58 a share a year earlier. But <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Erburu </PERSON>, the company's chairman and chief executive, told analysts at <ORGANIZATION> PaineWebber </ORGANIZATION>'s 17th annual media conference that it was was unlikely the company would `` continue to show year-to-year improvement in operating earnings'' for the full year. <PERSON> Erburu </PERSON> cited the difficult operating environment facing the company's newspapers in the <ORGANIZATION> Northeast </ORGANIZATION>, the costs of trying to sign up new subscribers after the Nov. 2 closing of the rival <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angeles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Examiner </ORGANIZATION> and a $ 5 million settlement of a legal case involving <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mirror </ORGANIZATION>'s cable TV operations. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Laventhol </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mirror </ORGANIZATION>, said while the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> was turning in a `` solid year'' with increases in both retail and classified advertising, the company's Eastern papers were reporting ad revenues barely even with a year ago, with classified advertising lineage down 7 percent. For 1988, <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mirror </ORGANIZATION> earned $ 331.9 million, or $ 2.58 a share, on revenue of $ 3.33 billion. Operating earnings amounted to $ 2.27 a share. <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mirror </ORGANIZATION> said it has stepped up its cost-containment program to offset some of the volatile economic and market conditions expected next year. `` We have good reason to believe that we can show improvement in 1990 barring an economic downturn,'' <PERSON> Erburu </PERSON> said. In addition to newspapers and cable operations, <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mirror </ORGANIZATION> owns four television stations and publishes magazines and books. In a news release Tuesday, <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> said 35 cents of its 57 cent per share charge in the fourth quarter stemmed from a determination that it would not fully recover an equity investment in its forest products operation. The market for newsprint has been glutted with supply. The remaining 22 cents per share of the charge stemmed from estimated expenses of voluntary union staff reductions at The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION>. The company has been in talks with its printers and plans to talk with other unions for production workers about staff reductions, spokeswoman <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Nielsen </PERSON> said. The reductions stem from weak advertising volume in the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> region and automation of newspaper production in the composing room, the planned closing of a printing facility at <LOCATION> Carlstadt </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, and the opening of an automated printing and distribution facility in <LOCATION> Edison </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, in late 1990. The company did not estimate earnings for the fourth quarter ending Dec. 31. For the first nine months of 1989, the company earned $ 285.6 million, or $ 3.63 a share, on $ 1.30 billion in revenue. The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> is a diversified communications company that publishes newspapers and magazines, operates television stations and syndicates news and feature stories worldwide. It also owns substantial interests in paper mills and has a stake in the Paris-based <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION>.
