<HEAD>Chevy Urges Dealers to Order More Cars</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> bulletin sent to Chevrolet dealers apparently turned into more orders for cars to be built in January, a company spokesman says. The bulletin said dealer orders through Nov. 22 were far below scheduled production and warned of plant shutdowns if the pace did n't pick up. `` The bottom line is whatever signals we sent to the dealers in late November clearly had an effect,'' said Chevrolet spokesman <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Kramer </PERSON>. As of Tuesday, the 4,800 Chevrolet dealers had ordered about 75,000 cars from the January production of nearly 91,000, <PERSON> Kramer </PERSON> said. That was up substantially from the 24,130 cars that dealers had requested as of Nov. 22, he said. `` It is critical that all dealers immediately analyze their product needs and submit orders immediately,'' said the bulletin, quoted in a story in Monday's Automotive News trade journal. `` Adequate order banks are necessary to maintain uninterrupted production.'' `` There's no kidding about it,'' <PERSON> Kramer </PERSON> said. `` We're scratching for every order we can get and our dealers are scratching for every sale that they can get.'' <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>, owner of Sir <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Chevrolet-Geo </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Raleigh </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, said his business never received the bulletin. He said he has been trimming orders for 1990 vehicles because of costs of keeping them on hand. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> officials have contacted his dealership nearly daily `` giving us the opportunity to order some more vehicles,'' <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> said. He has resisted large-scale orders, opting instead to keep his inventory in the 45 - to 50-day range `` I think in their -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>'s -RRB- selling, they could n't hesitate to mention the fact that there may be some plant closures in January and February, even in some of the hotter lines,'' <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> said. `` As we see it right now, that's their problem. Our immediate problem is selling vehicles.'' Chevrolet and Geo sales for the first 11 months of this year were 1,262,158 cars, down 7.3 percent from the same period last year. Last week, <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> announced that some of its car - and truck-making plants in <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> would close briefly in January because of slumping dealer orders Even before the 1990 model year got off to its official start on Oct. 1, dealers were saying they planned to cut orders from manufacturers by up to 30 percent. <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Tonkin </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Automobile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dealers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, has urged the 20,000 members of his organization to cut orders even more to avoid costs of holding large inventories of cars on their lots.
