<HEAD>UAL Board Meets Against Backdrop Of Buyout Turmoil</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Lead prospects uncertain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Takeover turmoil continued to cloud the future of <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> as directors of parent <ORGANIZATION> UAL </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> gathered for today's regularly scheduled board meeting at the company's Chicago-area headquarters A new employee buyout plan that <ORGANIZATION> UAL </ORGANIZATION>'s management drafted was received cooly by leaders of <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION>'s pilots and flight attendants, and ripped by the powerful <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> union. Their response apparently has left Chairman <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Wolf </PERSON> without a firm proposal for raising <ORGANIZATION> UAL </ORGANIZATION>'s stock price and staving off disgruntled investors. Opposition from the Machinists helped scuttle a $ 6.75 billion pilot-management bid for the nation's second-largest airline in October and their support is considered important to the success of a revised offer. The Machinists represent about 25,000 of <ORGANIZATION> UAL </ORGANIZATION>'s 70,000 workers. The plan floated by <ORGANIZATION> UAL </ORGANIZATION> management in meetings with employee groups would value <ORGANIZATION> UAL </ORGANIZATION> at $ 240 a share, or $ 5.43 billion, the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION> reported Tuesday, quoting unidentified sources. The plan envisions <ORGANIZATION> UAL </ORGANIZATION> employees owning about two-thirds of the stock and public stockholders about one-third, the <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION> said. <ORGANIZATION> UAL </ORGANIZATION> management would invest $ 30 million for a 2 percent stake in the company and be granted options for another 6 percent, the report said. `` If that's the deal, it's unacceptable. We will oppose it,'' said <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Freeman </PERSON>, an adviser to the Machinists, in a telephone interview from his <LOCATION> Roseland </LOC