<HEAD>Ramada Shareholders Approve Restructuring Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM F. RAWSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Approval of a corporate restructuring plan by <ORGANIZATION> Ramada </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> shareholders has cleared the way for the sale of <ORGANIZATION> Ramada </ORGANIZATION>'s 825 hotels and formation of a new company to operate its <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> casinos. The restructurng plan was approved Tuesday at a special shareholders' meeting in <LOCATION> Scottsdale </LOCATION>. Under the plan, <ORGANIZATION> Ramada </ORGANIZATION> would sell its international hotel business to <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hotel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Holdings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> for $ 540 million. A new company, <ORGANIZATION> Aztar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, would be formed at the same time to operate Ramada's three casinos. The transaction was approved by the <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> gaming commissions Tuesday. `` Assuming that everything goes as scheduled, we will close the entire transaction next week,'' said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Snell </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Ramada </ORGANIZATION>'s chairman and chief executive officer, after the meeting More than 96 percent of the 30 million shares that were voted approved the plan, under which each shareholder would receive $ 1 in cash and one share of <ORGANIZATION> Aztar </ORGANIZATION> stock for each share of Ramada stock. <PERSON> Ramada </PERSON>'s original restructuring plan, which the company scrapped in October, included an offering of $ 400 million in debt securities, including $ 230 million in subordinated debt, or `` junk bonds,'' to finance the new company. Under that plan, shareholders would have received approximately $ 7 plus one share of <ORGANIZATION> Aztar </ORGANIZATION> stock for each share of Ramada stock. The company announced in October that it would not go forward with that plan because of `` unfavorable conditions'' in the junk-bond market, which has been depressed and unstable for months. The new plan includes a $ 170 million offering of debt securities and eliminates the junk-bond offering. Under the plan, each shareholder would receive $ 1 in cash plus one share of <ORGANIZATION> Aztar </ORGANIZATION> stock for each share of Ramada stock. Ramada spokesman <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Cole </PERSON> said that under the new plan, <PERSON> Ramada </PERSON> would assume $ 230 million less in new debt, but would pay out $ 240 million less to its stockholders. `` It will be a less leveraged, stronger company,'' <PERSON> Cole </PERSON> said. Fewer than 200 employees will lose their jobs once the transaction is completed, <PERSON> Snell </PERSON> said. `` The main reduction is in the hotel group,'' he said.
