<HEAD>Agencies Cite Reports of Rudder Control Problems on 737s</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 More than a dozen reports of problems with rudder trim controls on <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 737s have been made since a plane skidded off a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> runway in September, two federal agencies investigating the accident said. The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday they have asked <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> to provide data on any reports it has received on rudders set in unexpected positions on its 737-300 and 737-400 model jets. <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Schleh </PERSON> said the jet manufacturer is compiling the data. <PERSON> Schleh </PERSON> said it is not clear whether the federal request is connected with the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> incident. `` This is just part of the information the <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION> accumulates in the normal course of an investigation like this,'' he said. <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Lopatkiewicz </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, said the agency has received at least a dozen reports, including two involving foreign airlines, of instances `` where the crew says it discovered the rudder was trimmed in a way that they did n't expect. The board began receiving the reports after its investigators found that the rudder was improperly set on <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION> Flight 5050 as it tried to take off from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> LaGuardia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> on Sept. 20. Two passengers were killed and 45 injured when the 737-400 veered during takeoff and skidded into the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>, breaking into three pieces. The board will decide later this week whether it will hold public hearings on the accident, <PERSON> Lopatkiewicz </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Duff </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> said his agency has launched its own investigation after receiving several reports of rudder trim problems. The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> expects to receive further information from <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> next week and then will decide whether to order any action, such as a design change or modification, <PERSON> Duff </PERSON> said. The inquiries are limited to the 737-300 and 737-400 models because they have electrically driven trim activators. Earlier 737-100 and 737-200 models have manual cranks. `` The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> has looked into the incidents to try to determine if the cause was related to human factors or a mechanical problem or a combination of both,'' <PERSON> Duff </PERSON> said. The investigations will include whether a crew member inadvertently activated the rudder trim switch and an examination of the cockpit gauge that indicates how the rudder is trimmed.
