<FIRST>a f PM-OntheMoney Adv14   12-13 0574</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-On the Money, Adv 14,0589</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv14</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release PMs Thurs Dec. 14</HEAD>
<HEAD>Rules For the Last-Minute Giver</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The season is in full swing when charitable organizations form a sort of joint venture with <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Claus </LOCATION> and Uncle <PERSON> Sam </PERSON>, filling mail boxes, telephone lines and shopping malls with requests for contributions. The fund raisers expect results from those extra efforts because they carry a double-edged appeal _ the emotional spirit of the holidays, and the pragmatic allure of a last-minute tax deduction. Some people object to this merger of generous and selfish motives. But from a practical standpoint, financial advisers say, a knowledge of the tax rules can make a big difference in how effectively you devote your limited resources to religious or community service groups, private education, or any other cause you consider worthy. First of all, the experts point out, you ca n't take any writeoff these days for charitable contributions unless you itemize deductions. That's important to consider, because the standard deduction has been sharply increased in the last few years. For 1989, it is $ 3,100 for a single taxpayer and $ 5,200 for a married couple filing a joint return. Contributions wo n't provide you with any extra tax saving if they and your other deductions, such as mortgage interest, do n't add up to more than those amounts Tax specialists advise people on the borderline to consider bunching deductible expenses such as contributions into alternate years and itemizing only in those years. There are strict rules as well covering just what contributions are deductible. Money given to a recognized church or charity, for instance, is almost surely eligible for a writeoff; country club dues almost surely not. `` An organization can -LRB- and undoubtedly will -RRB- tell you whether your contribution to it is tax deductible,'' says the accounting firm of Price Waterhouse in its annual Personal Tax Advisor. Gifts to individuals, or designated for an individual's use, are excluded by the rules. Also excluded are contributions to business or civic leagues and political parties or candidates. On the other hand, an eligible cash contribution is deductible in the year in which it is made, even if you use borrowed money. That means that you can give by credit card in December, pay the credit-card bill later and still take a deduction for 1989. Many organizations also readily accept non-cash gifts, such as old and outgrown clothing or furniture. `` Specific records must be kept to support a deduction for donated property,'' observe accountants <ORGANIZATION> Deloitte </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Touche. Once the amount you claim in this category surpasses $ 500 in any year, the documentation requirements grow increasingly stringent. Some special incentives exist to donate stocks or other securities that you have owned for more than a year and have appreciated in value since you bought them. Under most circumstances, you can take a deduction for the present value of such a contribution _ and avoid paying taxes on the capital gain that occurred while you owned the asset in question. Much different advice applies in the case of securities that are worth less now than when you bought them, since giving them directly involves passing up a deductible tax loss. Such property `` should not be contributed to a charity,'' says <ORGANIZATION> Deloitte </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Touche. `` It should be sold to realize the loss, and the proceeds of the sale should be contributed to charity.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Thurs Dec 14</NOTE>
