<HEAD>Legislative Leaders Endorse Northeast Buyout of PSNH</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES with comments from legislative news conference; CORRECTS
name to Public Service Company sted Co. in lead; minor editing throughout.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMA LOVE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Northeast Utilities made major gains today in its bid to buy <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hampshire </ORGANIZATION>, the first big investor-owned utility to go bankrupt since the Depression. State <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Bartlett </PERSON>, whose support was seen as key to <ORGANIZATION> Northeast </ORGANIZATION>'s success in a special legislative session scheduled for Thursday, now will support the $ 2.3 billion buyout. And <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> _ which had held out hope of winning the right to reorganize itself _ threw in the towel. House Speaker <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> Scamman </PERSON> announced at a news conference that <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> leaders in both houses had united behind the <ORGANIZATION> Northeast </ORGANIZATION> plan after winning agreements intended to protect consumers and other <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION> utilities. `` We're very confident they have protection and future -LRB- power -RRB- supply'' based on the agreements,'' <PERSON> Scamman </PERSON> said. The changes will be amendments to the <LOCATION> Northeast </LOCATION> takeover bill scheduled for a vote Thursday. Despite the developments, the vote still is too close to call, the No. 2 Republican in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> said. `` I wo n't make any prediction,'' Majority Leader <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Dupont </PERSON> said. He said he had n't decided how he would vote. Democrats, heavily outnumbered in the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION>, continued to oppose the <LOCATION> Northeast </LOCATION> plan. `` We have come to no agreement,'' <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Democratic Leader <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Chambers </PERSON> said this morning. Connecticut-based <ORGANIZATION> Northeast </ORGANIZATION> proposes seven annual rate increases of 5.5 percent, the first taking effect Jan. 1. Northeast says the plan is `` Seabrook neutral,'' meaning it would not change regardless of whether <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Seabrook </LOCATION> nuclear power plant operates. The $ 6.3 billion plant, which plunged <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> into bankruptcy reorganization in January 1988, is idle for lack of a federal operating license. The <ORGANIZATION> Nuclear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regulatory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> could issue a license as early as January, but appeals in federal courts are certain. <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hampshire </ORGANIZATION>'s largest electric utility, had been viewed recently as a distant second in the takeover competition. At a morning news conference, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Duffett </PERSON>, president and board chairman, attributed the utility's decision to drop out of the competition mainly to political opposition and <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>'s inability to win support from key creditor groups. Northeast, far and away the leading contender before today, had been seen as having little chance of winning legislative backing without support from <PERSON> Bartlett </PERSON>. As late as Tuesday night, <PERSON> Bartlett </PERSON> continued negotiating for further concessions from <LOCATION> Northeast </LOCATION>. Legislative Democrats, and some Republicans, say the <LOCATION> Northeast </LOCATION> plan would be a windfall for investors without protecting consumers. Republican Gov. <PERSON> Judd </PERSON> <PERSON> Gregg </PERSON> and other supporters of the agreement say the plan is far from ideal, but is the best that could be achieved under difficult circumstances _ and has the important benefit of avoiding years of legal wrangling and uncertaintly about rates. <PERSON> Gregg </PERSON>, whose office had no comment this morning, charged Tuesday that the Democrats' real agenda in opposing Northeast is stopping <PERSON> Seabrook </PERSON>. Democrats are espousing `` the old agenda of let's kill <PERSON> Seabrook </PERSON> at any cost, even if the cost is that <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hampshire </ORGANIZATION> consumers end up paying a lot more for energy and may not have the available supply they need in the future,'' <PERSON> Gregg </PERSON> said. Chambers denied it. `` The <LOCATION> Seabrook </LOCATION> issue is really a minor issue in all of this,'' she said Tuesday. `` This plan gives absolutely no protection to consumers and permits the company to make incredible profits.'' Republicans outnumber Democrats 3-1 in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and 2-1 in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, but <PERSON> Chambers </PERSON> said Tuesday she doubted that Republicans had sufficient votes to pass the <LOCATION> Northeast </LOCATION> plan. <PERSON> Gregg </PERSON> disagreed, predicting the plan would pass. Even if the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> passes the <LOCATION> Northeast </LOCATION> plan, it would need approval by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Bankruptcy Judge <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Yacos </PERSON> and various government agencies. Any changes to the plan presumably would require the approval of <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> creditors, whose representatives had accepted the <ORGANIZATION> Northeast </ORGANIZATION> plan as it stood before today.
