<FIRST>s f BC-Flight103-Security Adv17   12-13 1079</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Flight 103-Security, Adv 17,1119</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv17</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Sunday Dec. 17</HEAD>
<HEAD>Lockerbie Legacy Makes Terrorism Fact of Life for Airlines</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Airlines worldwide have tightened security since the <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> jumbo jet terrorist explosion over <LOCATION> Lockerbie </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>, spending large amounts of money on defenses that range from bomb-sniffing dogs to baggage X-ray gear. But two more big passenger planes have crashed in the year since then in presumed terrorist sabotage, and experts warn that another <LOCATION> Lockerbie </LOCATION> could happen tomorrow. The Flight 103 bombing that killed 259 people in midair Dec. 21, 1988, has made terrorism a sobering and expensive fact of life for the airlines, especially the big <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> carriers that fly overseas. Sophisticated bombs timed to explode during flight have replaced hijacking as terrorists' favored mode of operation. The burly guards, body searches, bomb detectors and dogs trained to smell hidden explosives have become increasingly familiar staples of air travel, helping to drive ticket prices higher. The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> sent a key directive to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> airlines a month after the <LOCATION> Lockerbie </LOCATION> crash, requiring specific measures for inspecting baggage and screening passengers. For example, the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> has ordered installation of sophisticated explosive-detection gear in 40 airports by next October. `` The aviation industry has taken steps to ensure better controls,'' said <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Walker </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Risks </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>, a consulting firm. But, he said, `` terrorism is escalating worldwide; the terrorists are generally one step ahead of what airlines are able to do.'' In July 1988, the airlines intensified anti-terrorist defenses in response to the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>'s downing of an <ORGANIZATION> Iran </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> jetliner. But terrorists sneaked a sophisticated explosive through <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION>'s security system six months later After the Pan Am bombing, the airlines again strengthened security. Then, last September, a <ORGANIZATION> UTA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> French </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airline </ORGANIZATION> DC-10 exploded over <LOCATION> Niger </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, in a suspected bombing that killed 174 people including seven Americans. In November an <ORGANIZATION> Avianca </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 727 crashed near <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>, in what authorities called a suspected bombing by drug traffickers retaliating for a government crackdown. Airlines once declined to discuss security. But in the aftermath of the <LOCATION> Lockerbie </LOCATION> disaster, the airline industry has started making security a subtle part of its marketing campaign to attract and reassure passengers. For example, extensive publicity has been given to the so-called thermal neutron analysis explosive detectors that the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> has required. <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Trans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> have been the first to install the new devices. The company that makes them, <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Applications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, said they will be `` an important working model for other airlines to learn from as the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> security program goes forward.'' Still, most carriers still wo n't talk specifically about how much money they spend, although it is in the millions of dollars. They also criticize the government for not absorbing more of the cost. `` The airline industry is the surrogate target for the government,'' said <PERSON> Homer </PERSON> <PERSON> Boynton </PERSON>, director of security for <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, the largest <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> carrier. `` The government ought to give us more help and more assistance.'' But <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Farrar </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, called security `` a cost of doing business. Traditionally, the airlines have paid the cost of equipment needed for security reasons.'' Like jet fuel and passenger food, airline security is an expense that comes out of revenues or as a special surcharge added to ticket prices that passes the bill to travelers. Pan Am, for example, adds $ 5 to the cost of a one-way trans-Atlantic ticket. <PERSON> Boynton </PERSON> said American is the only major <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> airline that uses its own employees for all security work. Most big carriers have their own security divisions but also contract with outside companies for passenger screening in airports and other protective services. American, which operates a growing number of flights to <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, spends $ 11 million to $ 12 million a year on security, <PERSON> Boynton </PERSON> said. Its program is partly modeled on that of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> El </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Al </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, which has a reputation for the toughest security measures. Spokesmen for American, <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Trans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lines </ORGANIZATION>, queried by the <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, all said their carriers strengthened what they called already-tight security after <LOCATION> Lockerbie </LOCATION>. Representatives of UTA and <ORGANIZATION> Avianca </ORGANIZATION> said those airlines stepped up security after disaster struck them. While financially strong airlines such as <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> can afford top-quality security as well as newer, safer jets, there is concern that weaker carriers could be tempted to cut corners. <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION>, for example, lost $ 158.3 million for the first nine months of this year, compared with a loss of $ 21 million in the same period in 1988. In every financial quarter since <LOCATION> Lockerbie </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> has largely blamed its poor financial condition on falling trans-Atlantic passenger traffic resulting from the crash. In a recent ABC News special broadcast, some former security employees of <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> alleged serious deficiencies in the airline's screening system. According to <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> security supervisor in <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, where Flight 103 originated had a criminal record, unknown to the airline. The former employees charged that <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION>'s security was compromised by cost-cutting and concern about on-time performance. Because it has been sued by a number of relatives of <LOCATION> Lockerbie </LOCATION> crash victims, <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> can not respond specifically to the allegations about its <ORGANIZATION> Alert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, said <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Jeff </PERSON> <PERSON> Kriendler </PERSON>. He called the charges `` false and misleading'' and `` a vindictive effort to discredit a former employer.'' `` We strongly reject any suggestion that <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> or Alert would have deliberately compromised the safety of passengers and crew members to effect on-time departure or to cut costs,'' <PERSON> Kriendler </PERSON> said. Last August, President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> created the Presidential Commission on Aviation Security and Terrorism, scheduled to make recommendations to him next spring. The seven-member panel, headed by former labor secretary <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> McLaughlin </PERSON>, plans to evaluate aviation security, the handling of terrorist threats against air travel and whether the public should be told of them, and the government's treatment of terrorists' victims. At its first hearing, on Nov. 17, former <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> security director <PERSON> Billie </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON> told the panel that air security is `` seriously deficient'' in high-threat areas such as <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>. Other experts agree. `` We are way behind in taking the necessary measures that will help to prevent this kind of tragedy happening again,'' terrorism expert <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilkinson </PERSON> recently told a news conference in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. `` Another <LOCATION> Lockerbie </LOCATION> could happen tomorrow.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday Dec. 17</NOTE>
