<HEAD>Police Warning Follows Computer Sabotage Disks in Mail</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GRAHAM HEATHCOTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Computer disks purporting to give information about AIDS have damaged computers at <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> banks, hospitals, universities and commercial institutions, police said Wednesday. The Fraud Squad at <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> Yard police headquarters said an unspecified `` destructive mechanism'' had been found in the disks which had rendered computers unusable in 10 cases. The squad said it had reports of the floppy disks being received by mail in different parts of the country, from <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Edinburgh </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>. There were no confirmed reports of the disk being received outside <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. The squad said it was investigating criminal damage caused by the disks to computers at banks, hospitals, universities and commercial institutions. The recipients were not identified. Two disks turned up Wednesday in the mail at the <ORGANIZATION> London </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> and others were sent to the <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION>, the City of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> police said. The City police, responsible for the financial district, warned companies to be on their guard. `` These disks must on no account be placed in computers. They are obviously meant to interfere with systems,'' City police headquarters said. City police said the disks apparently contained information about the disease AIDS, or acquired immune deficiency syndrome. An accompanying letter asked for a `` license fee'' of either $ 189 or $ 378, depending on the type of license, to be sent to an address in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>. But the envelope was mailed in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kensington </LOCATION> <LOCATION> district </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> police said. The letter warned in small print that if the money was not paid the sender would use program mechanisms to stop a computer functioning normally, City police said. Computer companies said they believed addresses for receiving the disks had been obtained from PC Business World, a British weekly trade paper devoted to computing. <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Hirst </PERSON>, an expert on computer sabotage, told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> the rogue disk was not of the virus type, which spoils computer systems by duplicating itself, but a `` Trojan'' which does direct damage. The name comes from the ancient Greek wooden horse concealing soldiers who came out at night to destroy the city of Troy. `` There are two programs on the disk,'' said <PERSON> Hirst </PERSON>, former technical editor of Virus Bulletin and a consultant on computer software. `` The first is an installation program and the second is a questionnaire on the risk of AIDS which will not run unless it is installed on a hard disk. It then prints off an invoice for a company in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> but the damage has already been done by the installation,'' he said. <PERSON> Hirst </PERSON> said he suspected the intention of the sender was entirely malicious. `` Money does not appear to be the motivation,'' he said. `` It may be difficult to understand but there are people out there who get a kick out of showing how clever they are. They may have a grudge against the world. They enjoy the idea of doing serious damage to people they do n't know, like those who put glass in baby food,'' he said. The alarm was first raised on Tuesday by Dr. <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Solomon </PERSON>, chairman of a group of users of personal computers, who said he received a similar disk the previous day. `` If you have not installed it, then do n't. It seems to be some kind of sabotage,'' <PERSON> Solomon </PERSON> said. At the <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, an official, speaking anonymously, said: `` You must be off your head if you get an unsolicited disk and put it in your machine.'' The official said the disks would never have been put into the market trading system. If someone wanted to find out what was on them, he said, they would have used an internal system for transmitting office memos.
</TEXT>
