<TEXT>
 A tentative contract settlement was reached Wednesday between negotiators for Post Cereal and about 1,000 workers who struck 39 days earlier. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Powers </PERSON>, president of Local 374 of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cereal </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Bakery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION>, said union officials were recommending that members approve the proposal at a ratification vote scheduled for Thursday afternoon. `` I'm sure the membership will support us,'' he said. `` We're just pleased that this thing is coming to an end. Workers may be back at work as early as this weekend, with most returning on Monday, union officials said. Contract talks had snagged on the company's proposal to increase worker contributions to the medical insurance plan, something Powers said was addressed in the new contract. On Sunday, union members rejected the company's last proposal by more than a 2-1 margin. Negotiators met for about two hours Tuesday and again on Wednesday. `` We sincerely hope that employees will ratify this new offer so production can resume,'' said <PERSON> Kathy </PERSON> <PERSON> Beiser </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION>, a division of <ORGANIZATION> Kraft </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foods </ORGANIZATION>. `` We believe that ratification and a return to work are in the best interest of all concerned parties.'' The strike has shut down operations at the main plant of Post, <ORGANIZATION> Battle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Creek </ORGANIZATION>'s No. 2 employer behind <ORGANIZATION> Kellogg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. Analysts say the shutdown has added to the problems facing Post as it suffers falling sales and a declining market share in the ready-to-eat cereal industry
