<HEAD>GAF and Vice Chairman Convicted of Stock Manipulation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal jury on Wednesday convicted <ORGANIZATION> GAF </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and a top executive of manipulating the price of a company's stock, as the government won another victory in its crackdown on Wall Street fraud. After two previous mistrials, the jury in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> found <ORGANIZATION> GAF </ORGANIZATION> and Vice Chairman <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sherwin </PERSON> guilty on all eight counts of stock manipulation, securities fraud, wire fraud and conspiracy. Two <ORGANIZATION> GAF </ORGANIZATION> subsidiaries were acquitted of all charges. <PERSON> Sherwin </PERSON>, 56, of <LOCATION> Princeton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, faces up to 40 years in prison and $ 2 million in fines when sentenced March 9 by Judge <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> <PERSON> Lowe </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> GAF </ORGANIZATION>, a <PERSON> Wayne </PERSON>, N.J.-based chemical and building materials manufacturer, could be fined a total of up to $ 4 million. <PERSON> Sherwin </PERSON>'s attorney, <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Kaufman </PERSON>, said he would appeal the conviction. <ORGANIZATION> GAF </ORGANIZATION> said in a statement: `` We will leave no stone unturned in pursuing every avenue of appeal. We continue to have complete confidence in <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Sherwin </PERSON>, who will continue in his postions as vice chairman and chief administrative officer.'' <ORGANIZATION> GAF </ORGANIZATION>, two subsidiaries and <PERSON> Sherwin </PERSON> were indicted in July 1988 for allegedly trying to boost the stock price of <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carbide </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> in 1986 shortly before selling a large block of Carbide shares. When the case was first presented to a jury a year ago, it attracted wide attention as the first criminal trial stemming from the insider trading scandals of the mid-1980s. Since then, several other cases have resulted in jury convictions, including the Princeton-Newport Partners racketeering and fraud case and the stock manipulation trial of <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> investor <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bilzerian </PERSON>. The first <ORGANIZATION> GAF </ORGANIZATION> trial ended in mistrial last January when <PERSON> Lowe </PERSON> determined prosecutors unintentionally withheld a piece of evidence. A second mistrial was declared in March when the jury deadlocked after 12 days of deliberations. `` Justice is finally done,'' said Assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Loewenson </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>. After the verdict, an ashen-faced <PERSON> Sherwin </PERSON> embraced his wife and daughters `` I'm terribly disappointed and I'm innocent of these charges,'' he said to reporters. The subsidiaries found innocent of the charges were <ORGANIZATION> Jay </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> GAF </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chemicals </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. The government's case against <ORGANIZATION> GAF </ORGANIZATION> was based largely on the testimony of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> broker <PERSON> Boyd </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jefferies </PERSON>, an admitted felon who has payed a key role in other securities fraud cases as part of a plea agreement with the government. <PERSON> Jefferies </PERSON> testified that <PERSON> Sherwin </PERSON> asked him in October 1986 to boost <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carbide </ORGANIZATION>'s price to $ 22 a share and agreed to pay $ 40,000 to cover losses in the deal. A higher stock price would have meant more money for <ORGANIZATION> GAF </ORGANIZATION>, which had accumulated 10 million shares of <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carbide </ORGANIZATION> during a failed takeover bid in 1986. <ORGANIZATION> GAF </ORGANIZATION> sold five million shares to <ORGANIZATION> Salomon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> for $ 23 each on Nov. 10. After a six-week trial, the jury returned its verdict after about eight hours of deliberations, compared with some 93 hours in the second mistrial. The verdict also came despite the introduction of new evidence in the trial's last week that apparently contradicted key testimony by <PERSON> Jefferies </PERSON> and a trading asistant at his firm. Defense attorneys introduced telephone records indicating that no calls were placed on long-distance WATS lines from the <ORGANIZATION> Jefferies </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> brokerage to <ORGANIZATION> GAF </ORGANIZATION> or Sherwin during times in October 1986 when the government alleged the manipulation was discussed. Defense lawyers had branded <PERSON> Jefferies </PERSON> as a crook who had schemed illegally with jailed stock speculator <PERSON> Ivan </PERSON> <PERSON> Boesky </PERSON>, who paid $ 100 million to settle insider trading charges in late 1986. <PERSON> Boesky </PERSON> fingered <PERSON> Jefferies </PERSON>, who last year agreed to plead guilty to two securities law violations. <PERSON> Jefferies </PERSON> earlier this year was sentenced to five years probation and a $ 250,000 fine.
