<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Fall</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Precedes LONDON-BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Gold prices tumbled in worldwide trading Wednesday, while the dollar finished mixed against other major currencies in choppy, hectic dealings after rebounding overseas. On the Commodity Exchange in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, gold bullion for current delivery settled at $ 408.10 a troy ounce, down $ 9.80 from late Tuesday. <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> quoted a late bid for gold at $ 408 an ounce, down $ 9. The plunge in gold also helped depress other precious metals, such as silver. Dealers attributed gold's decline largely to profit-taking from its recent steady rise and to technical market factors. They noted particularly strong selling by <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> investors. In currency trading, <PERSON> Zlatko </PERSON> <PERSON> Glamuzina </PERSON>, chief currency dealer at the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> office of <ORGANIZATION> Banco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> di </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sicilia </ORGANIZATION>, likened Wednesday's trading to `` a tug of war between the bulls and the bears. `` The bulls would like to see the dollar go up and they say it has reached its bottom, but the bears are trying to pulling it lower and seem to be winning the battle overall,'' <PERSON> Glamuzina </PERSON> said. The dollar got a boost from rumors that Soviet President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> had resigned, although they were swiftly denied by the Soviet Embassy in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, currency dealers said. Also supporting the dollar were reports of intervention by some central banks to push down the value of the surging <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> mark, they said. Putting a damper on the dollar, however, was speculation that the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> was easing interest rates. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, where trading ends before <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s business day begins, the dollar fell 0.77 Japanese yen to close at 143.70 yen. It traded at 144.13 yen in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, and at 144.05 yen in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, up from 144.00 yen late Tuesday. The dollar was stronger against the British pound. Sterling bought $ 1.5955 in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, down from $ 1.6027 Tuesday; and $ 1.6000 in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, down from $ 1.6085 late Tuesday. Other late dollar rates in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, compared with late Tuesday's rates, included: 1.7280 West German marks, down from 1.7322; 1.5645 Swiss francs, down from 1.5732; 5.9070 French francs, down from 5.9185; 1,289.00 Italian lire, up from 1,284.75; and 1.1597 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1625. Late dollar rates in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, compared with Tuesday, included: 1.7390 West German marks, up from 1.7335; 1.5965 Swiss francs, up from 1.5765; 5.9475 French francs, up from 5.9275; 1.9430 Dutch guilders, down from 1.9715; 1,296.25 Italian lire, up from 1,285.75; and 1.1585 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1625. Gold fell in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to a late bid price of $ 411.25 an ounce from $ 417.50 Tuesday. In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>, gold slipped to $ 411.00 an ounce from $ 416.75. Earlier, in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold fell $ 1.08 to close at a bid $ 414.73 an ounce. Silver prices also fell sharply. On <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Comex, silver bullion for current delivery settled at $ 5.544, down from $ 5.672 late Tuesday. Silver fell in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to $ 5.59 an ounce from $ 5.70.
