<FIRST>s f BC-BorderRebound Adv17   12-13 0981</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Border Rebound, Adv 17,1010</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv17</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Sunday Dec. 17</HEAD>
<HEAD>El Comeback: Retailers on Border Enjoying Return of Mexican Shoppers</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>McALLEN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s reviving economy is on display at <LOCATION> La </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mall </LOCATION>, where the parking lot is full of license plates from across the border. In this city 10 miles north of the <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Grande </LOCATION>, and all along the U.S.-Mexico frontier, one fact of international trade stands out: Mexican shoppers have returned to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to visit and shop, recovering from the brutal 1980s that brought `` la crisis.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Banco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nacional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> de </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mexico </ORGANIZATION> says Mexicans are spending as much and possibly more money on the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> side of the border than they did 10 years ago. As a result, <LOCATION> McAllen </LOCATION>'s La Plaza Mall has the highest sales per square foot of any of the 70 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> shopping centers owned by the <LOCATION> Indianapolis </LOCATION>, Ind.-based <PERSON> Melvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION>, said <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON>, southern regional manager with the firm. La Plaza's average merchandise sales of $ 404 per square foot is more than double the firm's national average of $ 189 per square foot The company's No. 2 mall is <PERSON> El </PERSON> <PERSON> Paso </PERSON>'s Cielo Vista, with sales of $ 338 per square foot, <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON> said. He attributes much of the border malls' success to the crowds of Mexican shoppers returning over the past two years. `` The Mexican nationals, what they're looking for is quality,'' <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON> said. `` They are not looking for sales.'' `` We have a lot of <LOCATION> Monterrey </LOCATION> traffic that drives, a lot of traffic from <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> that fly and the regular bus traffic that come across,'' said <PERSON> Tommy </PERSON> <PERSON> Joyner </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> McAllen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION>. That is a vast improvement over just a few years ago. After huge oil revenues and massive public spending and borrowing led to a brief boom from 1979-81, a sudden drop in oil prices in 1981 fractured the Mexican economy. Mexicans watched the peso diminish from a value of 26 to the dollar at the beginning of 1982, to 149 to the dollar by the end of that year. Border retailers on the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> side soon found their stores empty. The Mexicans' money suddenly bought only one-sixth of what it used to buy, so they no longer could shop in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The disappearance of the Mexican shopper quickly drove many stores out of business all along the border. Mexican expenditures in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> by 1983 dropped to half of what they were in 1979. Business in 1983 was off 80 percent in downtown <LOCATION> McAllen </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Fallek </PERSON>, owner of <PERSON> Mike </PERSON>'s Man Shop and the Palais de Parfum in downtown McAllen and another men's clothing store at La Plaza Mall He estimated that 85 percent of his downtown sales and 60 percent of mall sales are to Mexicans. Although the peso by 1987 dropped to 2,500 to the dollar as foreign debt plagued the nation, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s economy since has begun to calm down. The exchange rate fell only to about 2,650 by December 1989. Mexicans are spending abroad again because the peso has stabilized, and because of new confidence in President <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Gortari </PERSON>'s economic liberalization, said <PERSON> Isabel </PERSON> <PERSON> Bagnasco </PERSON>, an economist with the <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> City-based <ORGANIZATION> Banco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nacional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> de </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mexico </ORGANIZATION>. `` We are now having an economy with stable prices,'' she said. If Mexican spending on the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> side of the border for the second half of 1989 continues at the rate of the first half, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> retailers will surpass the $ 2.24 billion sales to Mexicans that <ORGANIZATION> Banco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nacional </ORGANIZATION> estimated for the boom year of 1979. During 1988, Mexican purchases of $ 2.09 billion in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> were $ 500 million higher than in 1987, the bank said. Steady growth in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s 1,500 border assembly plants, or `` maquiladoras,'' also has boosted the buying power of a new industrial work force of about 350,000. `` When <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> comes across, it stirs up the whole economy,'' said retailer <PERSON> Fallek </PERSON> in <LOCATION> McAllen </LOCATION>. `` They feel better about themselves, about their country and their government. Right now, they do n't seem so worried.'' Retail sales growth of 22.6 percent in 1988 in the <LOCATION> McAllen </LOCATION> area was the biggest increase of all the state's metropolitan areas, according to the State Comptroller's office. In the adjacent <LOCATION> Brownsville-Harlingen </LOCATION> area at the southern tip of the state, retail sales grew by 15.8 percent in 1988. In <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paso </LOCATION>, the retail growth rate was 9.5 percent. For comparison, sales grew state wide by only 6.4 percent in 1988. Retailers say this year will turn out even better. <PERSON> Fallek </PERSON> said the gradual return of the Mexican shoppers since last year will make 1989 his best year since 1981. <LOCATION> Brownsville </LOCATION> retailer <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Begum </PERSON> said he also has seen a steady improvement in sales since the peso crash cut his sales in half. His downtown New Yorker store caters to customers like the woman from <LOCATION> Matamoros </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, who on a recent Friday stopped in looking for something to wear to a party and bought a $ 2,500 fur coat. At the other end of the border, <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ysidro </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, retailers see the same recovery, said <PERSON> Doug </PERSON> <PERSON> Perry </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION>. `` There does n't seem to be a lot of -LRB- retail -RRB- space available for anything, particularly close to the border,'' <PERSON> Perry </PERSON> said. Another positive economic sign in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> is the cooling of its runaway inflation that hit 159 percent in 1987. Inflation dropped to 52 percent in 1988, and is projected to be 20 percent for 1989 and 15 percent in 1990. Inflation, however, still makes many products cheaper in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> than in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. Inflation-fighting consumers can be found among the Mexicans driving or flying home with new dresses and toys, as well as those carrying bags of toilet paper and groceries across the international bridges.
</TEXT>
