<HEAD>Great Northern Wages Battle Against Georgia-Pacific Solely in Courts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIRK BEVERIDGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Great </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Northern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nekoosa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday his paper company is not discussing any `` white knight'' friendly mergers or defensive restructuring to thwart the takeover attempt by <ORGANIZATION> Georgia-Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. Great Northern instead is pinning its hopes on courtroom decisions to fend off the unsolicited $ 63 a share tender offer, valued at a total of $ 3.8 billion `` While we're in the courts we're not considering anything else,'' <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Laidig </PERSON>, chairman and chief executive of Great Northern. `` Naturally we're talking to our financial advisers about what the future would look like when we finish winning this court fight with <ORGANIZATION> Georgia-Pacific </ORGANIZATION>, but there's actually no specific work going on right now and we certainly are not looking for a white knight,'' <PERSON> Laidig </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Laidig </PERSON> said other paper company executives have brought up the takeover attempt but he has made sure not to get into any talks about alternate mergers. When <ORGANIZATION> Georgia-Pacific </ORGANIZATION> made its initial offer of $ 58 per share on Oct. 31, there was speculation by some analysts that other paper companies might enter the bidding, but that has not happened. Great Northern stock finished down 50 cents at $ 61.75 a share on Wednesday. <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> was unchanged at $ 50.87 -LCB- a share. `` I've talked to some other CEOs who have said they're sorry to see this situation the way it is, but nobody's gone any farther than that, because I would n't have let them even if they wanted to,'' <PERSON> Laidig </PERSON> said. Laidig would not name any of the executives he had talked to, but said <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> also has heard from foreign companies that are watching the situation. `` We sell a lot overseas and there have been people who questioned whether there was a long-term interest in staying independent or something like that,'' <PERSON> Laidig </PERSON> said. `` Now whether that characterized the fact that they might be interested in some other action or not, I do n't know. We certainly have had a lot of our customers overseas who have indicated they are interested in whether we do or do not stay independent. But none of them have come forward and said, ` We'd like to buy you, or buy this or buy that or anything like that.''' The legal battles are being fought in federal court in <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>, where <ORGANIZATION> Georgia-Pacific </ORGANIZATION> filed a lawsuit challenging Great Northern's `` poison pill'' takeover defense and a state anti-takeover law, and in <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION>, where Great Northern has filed an antitrust suit against <ORGANIZATION> Georgia-Pacific </ORGANIZATION> The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> also is examining the proposed merger for potential antitrust problems and is expected to state any objections by Dec. 21. `` We think that our offer for Great Northern will succeed, and we think our acquisition offer fully complies with antritrust laws,'' spokeswoman <PERSON> Gail </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said Wednesday from <ORGANIZATION> Georgia-Pacific </ORGANIZATION>'s headquarters in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Laidig </PERSON> was in <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION> on Wednesday for a news conference at which he defended company lawyers for persuading <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Gene </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> to unseal a <ORGANIZATION> Georgia-Pacific </ORGANIZATION> consultant's study that showed different cash-flow scenarios based on a theoretical merger followed by sales of Great Northern mills in <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Georgia-Pacific </ORGANIZATION> said the study, unsealed this week, had been rejected long ago and accused Great Northern of a `` cheap shot.'' <PERSON> Laidig </PERSON> said his company felt that people in <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> were entitled to the information and <ORGANIZATION> Georgia-Pacific </ORGANIZATION> should have disclosed it previously. But in response to a question, <PERSON> Laidig </PERSON> said he would not make promises about Great Northern's willingness to protect jobs and sensitive woodlands. The company, based in <LOCATION> Norwalk </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, and incorporated in <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>, has been in business for almost a century in <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> and does n't believe it has to prove anything to Mainers, he said.
