<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Integrated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday announced a second-quarter loss of more than $ 1 billion due to failing businesses and cheap asset sales in a bid to avoid bankruptcy. The struggling financial services firm said the loss exceeded a previously anticipated $ 600 million decline mainly because of substantially lower-than-expected proceeds from the sale of its core businesses. Integrated reported a loss of $ 1.04 billion, or $ 141.15 a share, on revenue of $ 70.59 million in the April-June quarter. That compared with earnings of $ 12.78 million, or 68 cents a share, in the same period a year earlier. The once high-flying real estate concern stumbled trying to expand into financial services. Integrated attributed the delay in reporting its second-quarter results to drastic changes since it defaulted on nearly $ 1 billion in debt in June. Integrated stock closed unchanged at 37 -LCB- cents Wednesday in <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> trading. Before announcing the default, Integrated traded at around $ 15 a share. `` Obviously what happened to them in a major way is just shocking,'' said <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Fendrich </PERSON>, a managing director for <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Poor </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> `` Everybody knew that Integrated was a deteriorating situation, but nobody expected it to be an exploding one.'' Integrated is seeking to restructure its debt and raise capital to meet payments on a total of $ 1.75 billion in debt to and avoid seeking bankruptcy court protection from its creditors. The bulk of the second-quarter losses was pinned on write-downs in the value of businesses and assets Integrated has sold, discontinued or plans to sell because of its financial troubles. A major contributor to the loss was the much-reduced sale price for its central financial services businesses. Integrated in November reached agreement to sell the businesses to <ORGANIZATION> Broad </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> financial services concern, for a maximum of $ 225 million. It had hoped to receive $ 450 million. That deal, which is pending, is subject to price adjustments at the time of closing that are expected to lower its value. `` These losses reflect the serious impact of our liquidity problems,'' Integrated said in a statement. `` We are attempting to address these problems by working with our creditors to restructure the debt.'' For the first six months of 1989, <ORGANIZATION> Integrated </ORGANIZATION> reported a loss of $ 1.04 billion, or $ 141.93 a share, on revenue of $ 180.8 million, compared with profits of $ 19.86 million, or 59 cents a share, on $ 213.8 million in revenue a year earlier. The write-downs affect the financial services subsidiaries being sold to Broad: <ORGANIZATION> Integrated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Life </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Des </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Moines </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Capitol </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Life </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Integrated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Asset </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, an investment adviser; <ORGANIZATION> Integrated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Equity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZ