<HEAD>Massachusetts Bond Rating Falls To Lowest In Nation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL BEEGAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> got the lowest state credit rating in the nation Wednesday when <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Poor's dropped its long-term bond rating from A to BBB. That put <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> a step below <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>, which is rated BBB Plus, said <PERSON> Cathy </PERSON> <PERSON> Daicoff </PERSON>, S & amp; P's managing director of municipal finance. Only a year ago, the state's economic boom was such that it was dubbed the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Miracle </LOCATION> and nearly carried Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> to the White House. Now the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> is struggling with tax hikes to ease an estimated $ 800 million budget deficit for the current fiscal year. `` <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> is the lowest-rated state,'' Ms. <PERSON> Daicoff </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> Moody </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, the other major rating service, dropped <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> last month from A to <ORGANIZATION> Baa </ORGANIZATION> 1, tying it with <LOCATION> Lousiana </LOCATION> as the lowest-rated state. The two services use different ratings and different symbols, so they are not directly comparable, Ms. <PERSON> Daicoff </PERSON> said. State Treasurer <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Q. </PERSON> <PERSON> Crane </PERSON> said he was n't surprised by S & amp; P's action. `` You ca n't argue with the fact there is a serious shortfall,'' he said. `` The only way it can be addressed is by some very important and difficult cuts in our way of life, plus an input of fresh new revenue streams, whether they be sales tax, sin tax or income tax increases,'' <PERSON> Crane </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' chief financial adviser, <ORGANIZATION> Admininstration </ORGANIZATION> and Finance Secretary <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Lashman </PERSON>, said the bonds still carry an investment-grade rating, allowing them to be purchased by major pension funds and other institutional investors. Asked if there was a danger of <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>' rating falling into the junk-bond category, <PERSON> Lashman </PERSON> said, `` If we do n't get a tax package very soon, we are in serious danger of it.'' Ms. <PERSON> Daicoff </PERSON> said credit rating would n't be upgraded immediately even if the state were to erase the budget deficit of about $ 800 million for the current fiscal year. `` For a higher rating to be assigned, we would have to see a sharp reversal of the financial trends of the last 18 months,'' she said. `` We would also have to be assured that any future fiscal problems are addressed in a prudent fashion. `` S & amp; P expects the state to remain under fiscal stress for some period of time,'' she said. <PERSON> Crane </PERSON> said he hoped the rating would improve before February, the next time the state plans to go to market with long-term debt, but <PERSON> Lashman </PERSON> agreed an upgrading would take a long time. `` The last time this happened, it took us 13 years to get back to a top rating,'' <PERSON> Lashman </PERSON> said. S & amp; P said the downgrading affects $ 4.6 billion in outstanding direct general obligation state bonds. The ratings service also lowered from A to BBB the ratings on $ 2.5 billion in agency debt secured by state guarantees. That debt includes bonds issued by state authorities when the borrowing is not backed up by a stream of dedicated revenue, such as tolls or fees. S & amp; P also lowered the rating on $ 747 million in direct general obligation short-term notes from `` SP-1'' to `` SP-2.'' However, Ms. <PERSON> Daicoff </PERSON> said the state's planned sale of $ 1.2 billion in short-term commercial paper will carry the highest A-1-Plus rating because it is backed by a letter of credit from three Japanese banks. That sale includes $ 700 million in new borrowing and a $ 500 million rollover of existing short-term debt. The borrowing is required for the state to make a $ 1.1 billion aid payment to cities and towns at the end of the month. `` The rating is based on the banks' creditworthyness, not the commonwealth's,'' Ms. <PERSON> Daicoff </PERSON> said.
