<HEAD>Boeing To Pay $500 Million In Bonuses To Workers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> will pay $ 500 million in bonuses this month to its employees worldwide, including non-union workers, the company said Wednesday. Of that amount, $ 374 million will go to nearly 107,000 employees in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state, including more than 35,000 non-union workers in the <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> area. Both union and non-union workers will receive bonuses of 10 percent, the company said. <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION>'s largest private employer, said earlier it would give office workers, administrators and supervisors bonuses, but did not give a percentage until Wednesday. Office workers have received bonuses annually, but professionals and administrators last got bonuses three years ago, said <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Binder </PERSON>, company spokesman. The 43,000 members of the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Aerospace Workers in the state got 10 percent bonuses last Friday, averaging more than $ 3,000 each. Under their contract ratified Nov. 20 after a 48-day strike, they will get bonuses of 5 percent next year and 4 percent in 1991. If about 28,000 members of the <ORGANIZATION> Seattle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Professional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineering </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Employees </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> approve a contract offer, they will receive 10 percent bonuses Dec. 22. The engineers and technical workers have until Dec. 18 to vote on the tentative contract. The proposed offer calls for engineers to get a bonus this year only, but technical workers would get a 5 percent bonus next year and 4 percent the following year. Engineers would get an average bonus of nearly $ 4,000 while technical workers would receive nearly $ 3,000. The 1989 bonuses will also be distributed in four other areas with major <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> operations: <LOCATION> Wichita </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kan. </LOCATION>, $ 72 million; <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, $ 18.5 million; <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ore. </LOCATION>, $ 7 million; and <LOCATION> Huntsville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ala. </LOCATION>, $ 7 million.
