<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 House Majority Leader <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON> and other members of the Democratic leadership complained Wednesday that President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is relying for economic counsel from aides who have also served as advisers for <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. White House spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> dismissed the complaint as `` a political cheap shot.'' President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> himself, in a brief exchange with reporters as he left the Oval Office early in the evening, said, `` Mr. <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON>'s complaining So what's new?'' <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON> and 11 other House Democrats sent a letter to <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> counsel and ethics watchdog <PERSON> Boyden </PERSON> <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> saying they were `` deeply troubled by reports that senior officials in the administration may be serving in the dual capacity of advising the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government while simultaneously providing counsel, advice or other services to foreign governments ... corporations or other foreign entities.'' They said the chief <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> expert for the President's <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advisers </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Michigan </ORGANIZATION> Professor <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Saxonhouse </PERSON>, is an adviser to Japanese financial groups, including a research institute financed by <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION>. They also noted that <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Boskin </PERSON>, chairman of the president's council and <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s chief economic adviser, served on the board of a similar institute supported by the Japanese Finance Ministry before he took his current post `` This raises serious questions about conflicts of interest,'' said the Dec. 12-dated letter. The Democrats asked <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> to identify other administration officials who `` serve in a dual capacity'' with any foreign entity. <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said <PERSON> Boskin </PERSON> had quit the Japanese advisory panel in December 1988, a month before the start of the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration. <PERSON> Boskin </PERSON> was then a <ORGANIZATION> Stanford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> economics professor; he had been a top adviser toBush during the 1988 campaign. <PERSON> Saxonhouse </PERSON> is an unpaid adviser on a Japanese ministry board that has not met in two years, said <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON>. He said <PERSON> Saxonhouse </PERSON> works only part time for the White House, and `` there's no conflict of interest.'' <PERSON> Saxonhouse </PERSON> is not subject to ethics rules that cover the White House staff. `` <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON>'s a Japan-basher, that's all,'' said <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON>. <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON> could not be immediately reached for comment. He is in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, his staff said. <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON> sought the Democratic presidential nomination in 1988 on a platform of tough trade laws to restrict imports from countries with big trade imbalances with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, such as <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. The Democrats' complaint was sparked by an article in Sunday's <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> on <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s lobbying efforts in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and